<html><head><title>Debt Ceiling Politics:  Economists & Investors React</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<center><h2>Debt Ceiling Politics:<br>
Economists and Investors React</h2></center>
<hr>
<center>[ <a href="#quotes">Skip Introduction</a> ]</center> <P><i>As congressional Republicans move toward passing a federal budget that cuts spending and taxes and balances the budget by 2002, Clinton administration officials warn of a government default if there is any delay in raising the $4.9 trillion debt ceiling.  Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin has warned that a debt limit "crisis" could "interrupt Government operations,... generate uncertainty in the domestic and international securities markets, and increase the Government's cost of borrowing."  And White House Chief of Staff Leon Panetta has accused congressional Republicans of "playing with fire" by rattling the financial markets with the specter of default.  But  financial markets look at the future, not the present.  In fact, leading investors and economists seem to be more concerned about the failure to bring federal spending under control than they are about temporary non-payment of debts.</i><P>
<P><hr width="50%"><P>
<a name="quotes">
<h3><center>WHAT ABOUT</a> 
A "TRAIN WRECK"?</h3></center>
<ul>
"It would be tragic if delaying payments of interest and/or principal on U.S. Treasury obligations is needed to compel our Administration and Congress to achieve an agreement to balance the Federal budget.  The implications of even temporarily delaying these payments are broad, important, and profound.
<P>
However, let's not allow fears of temporary "market instability" to serve as an excuse for equivocating on spending cuts and entitlement reform.  Markets look at the future, not the present.  Despite widespread predictions that the Dow would drop "hundreds of points" at the onset of the Gulf War, it rose over a hundred points the first hour after bombing began.  The markets focused on the solution to the problem, not the bombing.  If the so-called train wreck occurs, the markets will focus on the eventual outcome.  If the markets believe the chaos will finally lead to decisive action, they will rise.  If the markets believe decisive action will not be forthcoming, they will decline.  Whatever the expectations, they will overwhelm disruptions  caused by the delay of these payments.  If decisive action is the end result, there will be no "black mark" on treasury securities; rather, lower government borrowing costs will be the result for years to come.
<P>
Be assured, we are not advocating the so-called train wreck.  Paying interest when due and principal at maturity on its securities is about as inviolate a commitment of the U.S. government as there can be.  As serious and deep as our differences are on how to achieve a balanced budget, they are clearly bridgeable.  An agreement which balances the budget and achieves long term entitlement reform is within our reach as a nation.  The true question is whether it is within the reach of our political leaders.  While such agreement should be achievable without default, from a financial market standpoint, the costs our economy will bear from a temporary default are less than the costs we now bear from the uncertainties about our budget outlook.  The costs of our political leaders failing to produce deficit reduction are greater than those of failing temporarily to pay interest and /or principal on U.S. Treasury securities.
<P>
Let us do neither.  Stop the nonsense and rhetoric.  Sit down and solve this thing for the good of America.  Now."</ul>
<P>
<font size="-1"><b>Stanley F. Druckenmiller</b><br><i>Chief Investment Officer & Managing Director</i>		                 
 <br>      
<b>Soros Fund Management</b>						    
 <P><b>    Kenneth G. Langone 
 </b><BR><i>Chairman & Managing Director</i>
<br><b>Invemed Associates, Inc.</b></font>
<P>
<i>The Washington Post</i><br>
September 26, 1995
<P><hr width="50%">
<P>
<ul>"...As for payments to U.S. debt holders, a potential default will be no more than a bump along the road to a balanced budget.  In 1987 and 1990, the government hit against the debt ceiling, and we heard the same apocalyptic rhetoric we hear today.  In 1985, as Congress and the Reagan administration were busy erecting the Gramm-Rudman-Hollings guillotine, the debt ceiling was reached, and default loomed.  Relying on a number of technical fixes, the Treasury Department was able to forestall actual default, but the uncertainty lasted more than a month.  Did the market implode?  Far from it:  Stocks actually staged a rally taking the S&P index to its then-all-time high.  There's a lesson in that earlier experience that holds true today:  The value of the debt investors buy depends on the dynamism of the U.S. economy -- not the fate of the U.S. government." -- <i>Wall Street Journal 10/13/95</i>
</ul><b>James C. Miller III
<br>Counselor to Citizens for a Sound Economy
<br>Director, Office of Management and Budget 1985-1988</b>
<P><P>

<ul>"Tying the statutory debt ceiling legislation to a major fiscal policy initiative is not new.  Of course, everybody knows that any technical 'default' or disruption would be the result of the game of political chicken rather than questionable economic soundness.  That is precisely why its impact on financial markets would be temporary and costless.  Presently, the pattern of moderate economic growth, vastly improving inflation fundamentals and the expectation that the Fed will lower its funds rate target to ease the restrictive stance of monetary policy, set the stage for further declines in interest rates.
<P>
Any disruption in the Treasury's auction schedule or delay in interest payments would not influence these fundamental determinants of lower interest rates.  The last time the debt ceiling legislation become embroiled in the fiscal debate -- in fall 1990-- financial markets were nonplused by the political game-playing, and interest rates declined continuously.  Financial markets reward credibility and responsibility of policymakers, both monetary and fiscal.  Is it possible that a 'default related' disruption would actually accelerate the decline in rates -- providing net long-run savings to taxpayers -- by raising the perceived probability of a quicker enactment of fiscal reform"?
</ul><b>Mickey D. Levy<br>
NationsBanc Capital Markets Inc.</b>
<P><P>
<ul>
"Congress has a sacred obligation to reduce the deficit once and for all.  It's imperative that we not hold that obligation hostage to the bond market.  When the deficit is reduced, borrowing will obviously be less costly for the government."
</UL><b>Al Dunlap 
<br>Chairman and CEO
<br>Scott Paper</b>
<P><P>
<ul>
"The very question of a 'train wreck' contains the built-in assumption of self-importance that Washington brinksmanship really matters.  What really would matter is a default on the economic portion of the 'Contract With America.'  If the 'train wreck' happens, it will take second billing to whatever Microsoft announces that day.  And the impasse will end when vendors start demanding C.O.D. terms on food deliveries to Congressional dining rooms."
</ul><b>T. J. Rodgers
<br>President & CEO
<br>Cypress Semiconductor</b><P><P>
<ul>
"The equity markets will respond favorably to deficit reduction which entails actual spending cuts not 'sleight of hand' accounting.  A pro-growth tax cut including capital gains would also be a positive.  When it comes to predictions of a 'train wreck' or 'default' in Washington, Congress should disregard the scare tactics of the Clinton Administration which has done nothing to solve our secular problems.  Clinton is trying to defend the status quo, not provide real solutions."
</ul><b>Richard T. Weiss
<br>Portfolio Manager 
<br>Strong Funds</b><P><P>
<UL>
"The bond market will respond favorably to deficit reduction achieved through real spending cuts to achieve a balanced budget by 2002 -- even if the political battle to get there causes a temporary default.  The bond market will not respond favorably to the prospect of tax increases to close a budget gap -- nor favorably to a balanced budget in out years achieved through assumed economic growth."
</ul><b>Daniel Gressel
<br>Teleos Asset Management
<br>New York, NY</b><P><P>
<ul>"If Congress, or the American public is looking for an honest assessment of how the financial markets will react to this Budget Showdown, they need only review recent history of the world currency markets.  Increasingly, over the last few years, the currency markets have been acting as the world's credit-market-Cop.  The world's financial markets have made clear their strong disapproval of Congressional spending through a clear inverse correlation between Congressional spending (or proposing to spend) and the value of the dollar -- a proxy for the U.S.'s credit rating.  With each new spending bill, such as the Crime Bill or the failed Balanced Budget Amendment, the dollar tanks.  If Congress truly wants to prevent a 'train wreck' they had better pursue this balanced budget proposal -- full steam ahead."
</ul><B>James C. Kennedy
<br>Kennedy Capital Management, Inc.
<br>St. Louis, MO</b><P><P>
<ul>"'Train Wreck'?  What Train Wreck?  Seriously, as President Reagan told Budget Director James Miller in 1986, 'Let's shut down the government and see if any one notices.'  In our opinion, the financial markets are up strong since last November because they are correctly anticipating less government and lower taxes.  They are not worried about the government's short-term borrowing needs.  If the markets were concerned, particularly the bond market, interest rates would have moved up long before now.  Long term, the financial markets care much more about tax policy (by a wide margin) than any other single issue.  Tax policy makes the world go around.  Lower taxes mean lower interest rates, stronger economic growth, and higher stock prices.  Higher taxes mean the reverse.  Now, if Congress fails to pass a significant tax cut, then we would be worried.  Not only would that be bad news for the economy and the financial markets, it would also be bad news for Republicans.  They would lose big at the ballot box."
</ul><B>Mark J. Deschaine
<br>President and Chief Investment Officer
<br>Investment Counselors Incorporated - St. Louis, MO</b><P><P>
<ul>"The danger to the financial markets is not that the government will miss an interest payment.  The danger is that the Congress will buckle to the Clinton Administration's reluctance to bring down the growth in federal spending."
</ul><B>Richard Rahn
<br>President
<br>NOVECON</b><P><P>
<ul>"When thinking about the upcoming 'train wreck', we can either focus on the immediacy of the crisis or the systemic factors leading to the crisis.  If we expend our energies on the crisis, we can rest assured that we will see the crisis again and again -- each time becoming more brutal.  The systemic factors have to do with Congress's acting on the behalves of Americans' failure to control spending.  The debt crisis is a moral failure of the American people -- an inability to live within our means and a callous disregard of future generations."
</ul><B>Walter E. Williams
<br>Department of Economics
<br>George Mason University</b><P><P>
<ul>"I am confident that no default will occur even if the debt limit is not raised before November 15.  The Treasury and the Federal Reserve have many ways of preventing this from occurring.  Moreover, investors are sophisticated and know that even if a technical default occurs they will still be paid all that is due them shortly.  And even in a worse case scenario, in which a technical default raises borrowing costs slightly, this will be more than offset by the reduction in borrowing costs that will result from shrinking government spending and balancing the federal budget.  For these reasons, Congress should not allow the Clinton Administration's scare tactics to derail the first real effort in 25 years to get the budget under control."
</ul><b>Bruce Bartlett
<br>National Center for Policy Analysis
<br>Former Treasury Department Official</b><P><P>
<ul>"Worries over a significant backlash in financial markets due to a so-called budget 'train wreck' are grossly overblown.  If some kind of temporary default on federal government securities actually occurred -- though quite doubtful -- the impact on the bond market would likely be small and short-lived.  Indeed, a real threat to U.S. financial markets looms if capital gains tax reductions, including indexation for inflation, were to somehow fall by the wayside.  Since the Republican congressional victories in November 1994, equity markets have been robust, especially small-cap, high-tech stocks.  Markets have been counting on a significant capital gains tax cut; if this fails to materialize then we should be worried."
</ul><B>Raymond J. Keating
<BR>Chief Economist
<br><a href="/sbsc/home.html">Small Business Survival Committee</a>
<br>Co-author of</b><i>D.C. By the Numbers:  A State of Failure</i><P><P>
<ul>"I agree with Stanley Druckenmiller and Kenneth Langone: the costs of failing to produce the right fiscal policy are greater than those of failing temporarily to pay interest and/or principal on U. S. Treasury securities."
</ul><b>John Mueller
<br>Vice President & Chief Economist
<br>Lehrman Bell Mueller Cannon, Inc.</b>
<P><hr><center><P>[  <a href="/townhall/spotlights/11-6-95/welcome.html">Budget Reconciliation Spotlight</a> | <a href="/townhall/welcome.html.cgi">Town Hall Home</a> ]
</center></body></html>


