<html>
<title>
Press Release:Millitary Cuts' Global Impact
</title><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<h2><center>News Release</h2>
<hr>
<i><b><a href="http://www.townhall.com/heritage/">The Heritage Foundation</a></b><br>
214 Massachusetts Avenue, NE<br>
Washington, D.C. 2002<br>
(202) 546-4400</i>
<hr>


<h3>BUDGET CUTS WILL END AMERICA'S<br>
 GLOBAL POWER, ANALYST SAYS</b><br>
B-2, NMD Funding Lauded</center>
</h3><p>
<br>
<b>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE
<p>
WASHINGTON, AUGUST 1, 1995 --</b> "America's days as a global military power capable of defending its worldwide interests will be numbered" if Congress goes along with Clinton administration defense budget cuts, according to a Heritage Foundation analyst.
<p>
"If the president and Congress do not change course on defense budget policy, the result will be forces smaller than those needed to execute national strategy, a collapse of the strategy itself, and ultimately the exposure of America's vital national interests to foreign threats," says Baker Spring, Heritage's senior defense analyst.
<p>
"No amount of rationalization can cover up this cold, hard fact. New technologies will not save America from this disastrous outcome. Nor will new strategies that downplay threats to American interests," says Spring.
<p>
Spring says both the Clinton administration and Congress are at fault since there is only a $9.6 billion difference in total spending between their respective seven-year defense plans. "For all intents and purposes, the two are roughly the same," says Spring. "Both budget plans would reach the year 2002 with military spending levels that are less than 60 percent of what they were in 1985," he says.
<p>
Spring says Congress should establish a congressional staff study on how best to close the gap between projected defense budgets and actual national security requirements. The study group should be appointed by the chairmen of the Senate and House defense committees, and function like a similar 1985 body that produced a report on military reorganization.
<p>
The study's starting point ought to be that current military spending plans will result in Defense Department underfunding of at least $110 billion in a five-year period, compared to what would be required to pay for the force structure envisioned by the Clinton administration in its 1993 Bottom-Up Review (BUR), Spring says.
<p>
With the shortfall, U.S. military forces will have to be reduced even more than now planned, with the Army going from 10 to eight active divisions, the Air Force from 20 tactical fighter wings to 15, the Navy to 300 ships from 346, including only nine carriers rather than 12, and with only 140,000 active Marines, compared to 174,000.
<p>
So much military muscle will be cut that by the turn of the century the United States "will not have enough power to fight a major regional conflict like the Persian Gulf War without abandoning its security commitments elsewhere in the world," Spring says.
<p>
As an example, Spring cites the Air Force's deployment of 10 tactical fighter wings during the Persian Gulf War. Due to maintenance and backup needs, at least one-third of a wing is needed in reserve for each full wing in combat. This means putting just 10 wings in a future Gulf War would tie up the entire 15 wing Air Force of 2002, according to Spring. He says the same disturbing force calculus would apply to the Army and the Navy.
<p>
The weak U.S. military posture will also force America's allies to reassess their commitments to regional-based defense alliances, probably beginning with NATO, Spring says. "Under these circumstances, an independent European nuclear force, with Germany's direct involvement, is not out of the question," according to Spring. Japan could also be expected to either re-arm and fend for itself, or seek to play stronger regional powers like China and Russia against each other.
<p>
Finally, U.S. access to the international trade that undergirds much of America's economic prosperity would be seriously threatened, including the nation's access to critically needed petroleum supplies. "Two world wars in this century should have taught Americans that drastically scaling back our regional defense commitments is a dangerous thing to do," says Spring.
<p>
In related Heritage papers released today, Thomas Moore, Heritage's deputy director of foreign policy and defense studies, finds at least some encouragement in the Senate Armed Services Committee defense authorization bill, which will soon be considered by the full Senate.
<p>
The Senate bill would put the nation on course for building Theater Missile Defenses against short-range regional missile threats and a National Missile Defense (NMD) to protect the U.S. homeland against long-range strategic ballistic missiles. The bill also includes start-up funds for an anti-cruise missile defense.
<p>
Moore says proponents should expect and vigorously oppose efforts to drop the nearly $500 million in NMD funding increases included in the bill by the Senate Armed Services panel.
<p>
In a second related paper, Spring argues that the $356 million included in the Senate defense bill to pay for dismantling the former Soviet Union's nuclear weapons should be used instead to keep the B-2 Stealth bomber production line open.
<p>
According to the General Accounting Office, these funds "have been used by individuals and institutions in the former Soviet states working to create new weapons of mass destruction." Funds would be better spent on the B-2, which is virtually invisible to enemy radar and thus will be able to project American power around the world from continental U.S. bases, Spring says.
<p>
Twenty B-2 bombers have already been paid for, but the Senate bill lacks a provision included in the House defense bill for spending $553 million to keep the aircraft's production line open for another 20 planes.
<p>
With the $356 million fund shift to the B-2, the Senate then can make up the remaining $188 million difference with the House by shifting non-appropriate funds supporting the Atlanta Olympic Games, weather reconnaissance, the Defense Business Management University, counter-drug surveillance activities and land mine clearing assistance, Spring says.
<BR><HR WIDTH="30%"><BR><CENTER><A HREF="/heritage/hbut.map"><IMG SRC="/heritage/hbut.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A></CENTER></body>
</html>
