<head>
<title>Bill Frist Press Release</title>
</head>
<body>
<center>
<h2>Bill Frist</h2>
<Font Size=5>United States Senator
Tennessee</Font Size=5>
</center>
<p>
<hr>
June 29, 1995<br>
Contact:  Jill Miller<br>
(202) 224-5401<br>
<p>
<center>
<b>FRIST DEMONSTRATES HOMPAGE, WELCOMES<br>
"TOWN HALL" TO INFORMATION SUPERHIGHWAY</b>
</center>
<p>
 U. S. Senator Bill Frist today welcomed the conservative movement to the information superhighway, and demonstrated his homepage at a Capitol Hill event to kick off the Heritage Foundation's Town Hall Internet community. Town Hall will provide Internet users with a link to conservative organizations and publications. Frist was the first Republican in Congress to have a homepage on the World Wide Web, and spearheaded an effort to bring the World Wide Web into the United States Senate.
<p>
"As a physician, I used technology every day to save the lives of my patients, and now as a Senator, I'm using technology every day to keep in touch with my constituents," Frist said. "It is imperative that our government be accessible through the World Wide Web, which is expected to have more than 100 million users within the next few years. With Town Hall and active participation by elected officials, the Internet can allow citizens to not only learn about, but become a part of the conservative movement."
<p>
In February, Frist asked the Senate Rules Committee to provide the Senate with access to the World Wide Web. Earlier this month, the Committee approved Frist's request. Senator Frist's homepage on the Internet includes his biography, Congressional Record statements, press releases, office information, and links to other government and non-political organizations.
</body>
</html>
