<head>
<title>Congressman Robert Dornan's Biography</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center>
<h2>Robert K. Dornan Biograohy</h2>
</center>
<hr>
<br>
U.S. Congressman Robert K. Dornan, from Garden Grove, California, now serving in his
eighth term, represents California's 46th Congressional District.  Located in Orange County south
of Los Angeles, the District is comprised of all or parts of the cities of Anaheim, Santa Ana,
Garden Grove, Tustin, Irvine, Stanton, Orange, Fountain Valley and Fullerton.<p>
<h2>Congressional Duties</h2><p>
Congressman Dornan represented California's 27th District beach cities in Los Angeles
County from January 1977 to January 1983.  In 1984, he was elected from California's 38th
District in central Orange County.  Much of the 38th was reapportioned into the 46th District in
1992.<p>
Because of his background in national security, Dornan was chosen to serve on the Permanent
Select Committee on Intelligence.  He also serves on the Armed Services Committee where he has
championed such vital defense projects as funding for the B- I and B-2 bombers, the F/A- 18 fighter and
the V-22 tiltrotor, development of effective ground combat identification systems, and maintaining proper
levels of Guard and reserve forces.  As the Defense Department downsizes in the post Cold War era,
Dornan has worked to assist those U.S. soldiers, sailors and airmen who will be released from duty.  His
proposal to assist discharged service members gain teacher certification will help integrate former militarypersonnel into the civilian economy and also help raise the quality of American education by tapping into the vast human resources and expertise of U.S. armed forces personnel.<p>
Dornan was a member of the former Select Committee on Narcotics Abuse and Control
where he was involved in formulating U.S. policy to fight the war on illegal drugs.  He is an active
supporter of the new "Weed and Seed" program that is designed to "weed out" criminals in drug-infested areas and plant the seeds of economic and educational opportunity.  As a result of Dornan's efforts, an area of Santa Ana, California, has been designated as a "Weed and Seed Pilot Program."<p>
Dornan's other congressional duties include memberships on the Human Rights Caucus, Grace
Commission Caucus, Empowerment Caucus and Hispanic Caucus.  He is a permanent observer to the
Geneva Arms Control Negotiations.  During 1989 and '90, Dornan chaired the Republican Study
Committee.  He continues to sit on the RSC Executive Committee and chair its foreign affairs and
defense task force.  He is co-chairman of the Republican POW/MIA Task Force.  He is a member of
congressional task forces on Tax Policy and Job Opportunities, Welfare Reform, the Strategic Defense
Initiative, Civil Rights, and Terrorism.<p>
 Dornan is honorary president of the American Chapter of the International Committee for a
Free Vietnam.<p>
<h2>Personal</h2><p>
Congressman Dornan, a Roman Catholic, was born in New York City on April 3,
1933, to Harry and Mickey McFadden Dornan.  He married the former Sallie Hansen of Santa
Monica, California, on April 16, 1955.  They have five children: Robin Mary, Robert Jr.,
Theresa Ann, Mark, and Kathleen Regina.  The Dornans have nine grandchildren.<p>
<h2>Professional Experience</h2><p>
After graduating from Loyola High School in Los Angeles in 1950 and attending Loyola
University until 1953, Congressman Dornan, at age 19, volunteered for service in the United States Air
Force.  Upon earning his silver wings, he served as a peacetime fighter pilot with the world's first
supersonic jet fighter wing.  In 1958, Dornan left active duty and joined the California Air National Guard
as a fighter pilot and then the U.S. Air Force Reserve as a rescue and seaplane pilot and an intelligence
officer, achieving the rank of captain.  He survived two jet fighter emergency parachute ejections as well
as two "dead stick" forced landings (F- 1 00 jet fighter and H- 1 3 solo helicopter).<p>
Dornan has piloted virtually every aircraft in the U. S. military arsenal including the B-1, U-2 and
the SR-71 "Blackbird" as well as the Israeli "Kfir," the British "Tornado," "Harrier" and "Hawk," and the
French "Mirage." He completed his service in the Reserve in May 1975.<p>
Dornan produced and hosted radio and television public affairs shows in Los Angeles
from 1965 to 1976.  In 1968 and 1969, he was awarded Emmys.<p>
Throughout the 1960s, Dornan was active in domestic civil rights activities.  He marched
with Rev.  Martin L. King, Jr., in August 1963.  In addition, in 1970, on his television program
"The Robert K. Dornan Show," he originated the POW/MIA bracelet as worn by more than 5
million Americans and, in 1979, the Prisoner of Conscience bracelet worn for Soviet Jewish and
Christian dissidents.<p>
 Dornan was president of the American Space Frontier Political Action Committee from
1983 to 1988.<p>
<h2>Awards and Honors</h2><p>
In recent years, Congressman Dornan has been recognized for his efforts to spur economic
growth by working to reduce taxes and government spending.  For example, the National Tax
Limitation Committee rated him 100 percent for his record of fiscal responsibility and the
National Taxpayers Union ranked the congressman as one of the 30 most frugal members of the
House.  Dornan has also received the Golden Bull-dog Award from the Watchdogs of the Treasury
and the Jefferson Award from Citizens for a Sound Economy.<p>
In addition, Dornan received the Spirit of Enterprise Award from the U.S. Chamber of Commerce,
the Guardian of Small Business Award from the National Federation of Independent Business, the SoundDollar Award from the Free Congress Foundation, the Thomas Jefferson Award from the Food
Distribution Industry, the National Leadership Award from the American Security Council, and an award
of appreciation from the Disabled American Veterans.<p>
<h2>Memberships</h2><p>
Congressman Dornan is a member of the Air Force Association, American Legion, American He-
licopter Society, AMVETS, Association of Former Intelligence Officers, Association of Naval Aviation,
Knights of Columbus, Los Angeles Philanthropic Society, National Guard Association of California, Navy
League, and the Reserve Officers Association.<p>
<h2>Political</h2><p>
On December 17,1985, Congressman Dornan became the first member of Congress to
endorse for president then Vice President George Bush.  He seconded the nomination of Bush
for President at the New Orleans Republican National Convention on August 17, 1988.  During
the 1988 campaign, he campaigned in more states (34) than any other of Bush's surrogate
speakers.  In 1992, Congressman Dornan was again national co-chairman and California vice
chairman of the Bush for President campaign.<p>
<br>
<br>
<a href="http://www.umr.edu/~sears/primary/dornan.html">Go to Robert Dornan Home Page</a><br>
<a href="dornspee.html">Robert Dornan Announcement of Candidacy</a><br>
<a href="contents.html">Introduction</a>
</body>
