<html>
<head>
<title>Richard Lugar: Biography</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center>
<h2>Richard Lugar: Biography</h2>
</center>
<br>
<hr>
<br>
Senator, Farm Manager, Educator, Mayor, Entrepreneur, School Board Member,
Naval Officer, Rhodes Scholar, Valedictorian, Runner, Grandfather, Father,
Husband...Statesman.<p>
Richard Green Lugar-a fifth generation Hoosier-is the senior United States
Senator from Indiana. The former two-term mayor of Indianapolis was elected
to the Senate in 1976, and re-elected in 1982 and 1988.<p>
Surveys have shown that Lugar is the most popular public figure in Indiana;
he shattered all statewide election records in his last campaign, capturing
the most total votes, 1,430,525, greatest plurality, 761,737, highest
percentage, 68.1, and most counties, 91 of 92.<p>
<h2>National Leader in Agriculture, Nutrition, Forestry</h2><p>
While known as a valued national spokesman for U.S. interests in
international debate, Lugar is the highest ranking Republican official in
agricultural matters, as senior member of the Senate Agriculture Committee.
Lugar often worked on his father's Marion County farm as a boy and
continues to actively manage the cultivation of its 604 acres of corn,
soybeans and trees.<p>
<h2>Outstanding Legislator</h2><p>
During his third Senate term, Lugar became the fourth person ever named
"Outstanding Legislator" by the American Political Science Association.
In addition to noting bills successfully authored by Lugar, the award
recognized his ability to extend his influence on policy and public opinion
beyond traditional limits of parliamentary debate. For example, Lugar is
credited with helping generate crucial political and public support for
U.S. military action in the Persian Gulf War by leading the national debate
with several bold policy statements-prodding the public, (Congress and the
Bush Administration) to action.<p>
<h2>Democracy's Advocate</h2><p>
During the 99th Congress (1985,'86), Lugar served as chairman of the
Foreign Relations Committee, restoring its power and eminence. In 1986,
Lugar entered the crucible of the Philippines presidential election, where
he recognized Corazon Aquino as the legitimate winner and spotlighted the
corrupt activities of supporters of former President Ferdinanci Marcos
ultimately convincing President Reagan to back Aquino.<p>
In 1993, Lugar was named to the prestigious Intelligence Committee by
Senate leadership recognition of the value of his involvement in nearly all
aspects of U.S. national security.<p>
As a Navy ensign in the late 1950's, Lugar served in the highly sensitive
position of naval intelligence briefer. He rose at 2:30 am, memorized
overnight intelligence reports from around the globe and summarized them
verbally for the Navy chief, CIA director and others. Lugar also briefed
President Eisenhower in the White House.<p>
Starting in 1991, Lugar and Armed Services Chairman Sam Nunn, of Georgia,
forged an effective bipartisan alliance aimed at prompt dismantlement and
conversion of the post-Cold War Soviet nuclear stockpile.<p>
<h2>International Trade Adds Hoosier Jobs</h2><p>
Lugar also promotes U.S. political, diplomatic and military leadership in
world affairs as a critical factor in domestic politics. Hailing from a
state which ranks among the very top exporters per capita, Lugar advocates
the expansion of global trade. He has sponsored trade conferences in
Indiana, and encourages foreign leaders to buy Indiana products.<p>
<h2>Progressive Mayor of Major City</h2><p>
As the former mayor of Indianapolis and president of the National League of
Cities (1970-'71), Lugar is an expert in economic development, housing and
other urban issues. As the chief executive of his hometown from 1968-'75,
Lugar revolutionized the very form and function of the nation's 12th
largest metropolitan government by unifying Indianapolis' downtown and
urban neighborhoods with surrounding suburban communities.<p>
Lugar is a running enthusiast who promotes health and nutrition programs.
As Roll Call Magazine stated: "Lugar is more than fast. He is in remarkable
overall physical condition, as tough as the limestone for which his state
is famous."<p>
<h2>The Fiscal Conservative</h2><p>
In Congress, Lugar supports the pro-growth policies of low taxes and tight
purse strings; he is an advocate of a balanced budget amendment and line
item veto. Lugar is known by his colleagues for discipline and fiscal
prudence, having maintained a 98 percent voting attendance records and
having voluntarily returned more than $2.4 million in office funds.<p>

<h2>Biographical Chronology</h2><p>
Dick Lugar was born April 4, 1932 in Indianapolis, Indiana. He graduated
first in his class with straight A's, both at Shortridge High School and
Denison University, in Ohio. Lugar was co-president of the student
government at Denison with his future wife, Charlene Smeltzer. They married
September 8, 1956 and have four sons and six grandchildren.<p>
Charlene has established an endowment fund for fighting birth defects and
infant deaths, in part through prenatal care provided aboard the
"Mom-mobile," which tours urban neighborhoods. She has said that her goal
is "to make Indiana the safest place in the world to have a baby."<p>
Dick Lugar graduated from Denison in 1954, then became a Rhodes Scholar in
Pembroke College at Oxford University. Next he volunteered for active duty
in the Navy, in which he served three years and four months. In 1960, Lugar
returned from the Pentagon to Indiana to help manage his family's farm and
food machinery firm, Thomas L. Green & Company. Founded by his grandfather,
the small manufacturing concern on Indianapolis' near west side celebrated
its 100th anniversary in 1993.<p>
Dick Lugar succeeded in his first run for public office when he won a seat
on the Indianapolis Board of School Commissioners. Lugar then defied
odds-makers in 1967, winning the first of two mayoral terms. In 1976 Lugar
won a seat in the U.S. Senate, after an unsuccessful bid two years earlier.
After his reelection in 1982, he was elected to the Senate Leadership as
chairman of the National Republican Senatorial Committee. In 1985, the
Republican caucus picked him to be chairman of the Foreign Relations
Committee. Lugar was named the co-chairman of the Arms Control Observer
Group in 1985, and was appointed to the Intelligence Committee and
Congressional Reform Committee in 1993.<p>
<br>
<a href="http://www.iquest.net/lugar">Go to the Richard Lugar Home Page</a><br>
<a href="lugaspee.html">Richard Lugar Testimony on Tax Reform</a><br>
<a href="contents.html">Introduction</a>
</body>
