<html>
<title> THE FORGOTTEN CRISIS: S. 1120, WELFARE REFORM, AND ILLEGITIMACY -- Heritage </title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center><h3><i>THE FORGOTTEN CRISIS: S. 1120, WELFARE REFORM, AND ILLEGITIMACY</h3></i>
<p>
By Robert Rector <br>
Senior Policy Analyst<br>
Committee Brief No. 18<br>	
August 18, 1995<br></center>
<HR SIZE = 3 WIDTH = 30%>
<p>
	The Work, Family and Community Welfare Replacement Act, a legislative proposal by Senators Lauch Faircloth (R-NC), Phil Gramm (R-TX), and John Ashcroft (R-MO), contained eight provisions to address the crisis of rising illegitimacy. President Clinton and the Democratic leadership in the Senate are silent on addressing this issue. S. 1120, the Republican leadership bill, contains only one of these provisions:  findings about the ill effects of illegitimacy on society. (1) The remaining seven provisions to reduce illegitimacy which, though part of the Faircloth-Gramm-Ashcroft proposal, should be included in S. 1120 are:
<P><ol>
<li><b>Voluntary State Goals and Plans.</b> The Faircloth-Gramm-Ashcroft proposal required states to set numerical goals for their illegitimacy ratios for the next ten years. (The illegitimacy ratio is the ratio of out-of-wedlock births to total births within the state.) States also were required to develop plans to reduce illegitimacy, setting their own goals with no penalty if the goals were not met.
<p>
	The intention of the goals and state plans was to focus public attention on the explosive growth in illegitimacy. Liberal Republicans and Democrats in Congress have rejected this approach.
<p>
<li><b>The Illegitimacy Ratio Bonus Mechanism.</b> This provision would increase the amount of a state's Aid to Families with Dependent Children (AFDC) block grant if the state reduced its illegitimate birth ratio without an increase in its abortion rate.
<p>
	The National Right to Life Committee accepted this provision, while pro-abortion groups objected to it. It was excluded from S. 1120.
<p>
<li><b>Abstinence Education.</b> The Faircloth-Gramm-Ashcroft proposal set aside additional funds for abstinence education. 
<p>
	 S. 1120 is silent on this subject.
<p>
<li><b>Pro-Marriage Tax Credit.</b> Welfare punishes marriage and rewards illegitimacy. The Faircloth-Gramm-Ashcroft proposal attempted to offset partially the anti-marriage effects of welfare by creating a refundable pro-marriage tax credit. The credit would be available only to married couples with children where at least one spouse was employed. It would have a maximum value of $500 and would be available to families with earned income between $8,000 and $26,000.
<p>
	S. 1120 contains no pro-marriage provisions.
<p>
<li><b>Paternity Requirement.</b> The Faircloth-Gramm-Ashcroft proposal required that mothers establish paternity in order to obtain future AFDC benefits. The bill stipulated that to obtain federal cash assistance for a child born after January 1996, the mother would have to establish paternity. States would be free to exempt 25 percent of the relevant mothers from this requirement. In addition, mothers of newborn children who have not yet established paternity but were cooperating by providing father's name, address, and other identifying information could receive cash aid for the first six months of the child's life while the paternity process was being completed.
<p>
	S. 1120 is silent on this issue.
<p>
<li><b>No Cash to Unwed Teenagers.</b> The Faircloth-Gramm-Ashcroft proposal prohibited federal funds from being used for cash aid to girls under 18 who had children out of wedlock. States would be free to use their own funds to give cash aid to this group if they wished. 
<p>
	 S. 1120 merely permits states to restrict cash benefits to unwed teenage mothers; this provision is, at best, redundant since under a block grant a state has full authority to set eligibility. Thus, the bill offers little or nothing specifically to combat illegitimacy and actually may limit state efforts (see below).
<p>
<li><B>Family Cap.</B> The Faircloth-Gramm-Ashcroft proposal prohibited the use of federal funds to give increased cash aid to women who have additional children while already enrolled in AFDC. States would be able to use their own funds to increase benefits if they chose. 
<p>
	 By contrast, S. 1120 permits, but does not require, states to establish a family cap. Like the leadership's family cap on teenage mothers, this is redundant under a block grant. Moreover, states can obtain a waiver to implement the family cap under current law, so S. 1120 offers no real change from the status quo.
</ul><p>


<b>Provisions on Teenagers Residing at Home</b>
<p>
	S. 1120 states that for an unmarried teen mother to receive cash aid, she must reside in a supervised setting or with her parents or with an adult relative. This provision is virtually copied from the Clinton plan. The problem with it is that some 60 percent to 70 percent of teenage mothers on AFDC already reside with adult relatives. The bill simply replicates the status quo and calls it reform. Even worse, in many cases, the adult parent is the problem:  the adult parent of the teenage mother herself is most likely a single mother who had a child out of wedlock and became dependent on AFDC. Now the teenage daughter is repeating her mother's pattern by having a child out of wedlock and applying for welfare.
<p>
	This provision of S. 1120 would perpetuate and intensify multi-generational welfare dependence. To have any positive impact, it at least should be amended to provide that teenage mothers can receive cash aid only if they reside with adult relatives who themselves do not have a history of AFDC dependence. Otherwise the teenage mother should receive only non-cash aid or should be required to reside in a closely supervised group setting.
<p>

<b>Excluding Marriage From the State Performance Standards</b>
<p>
	There is a pervasive anti-marriage tone to the entire Senate leadership bill when compared with the House-passed H.R. 4. 
<p>
	 For example, H.R. 4 allows states full credit for reductions in caseload which occur because AFDC mothers have married and left the welfare rolls. Both H.R. 4 and the Faircloth-Gramm-Ashcroft proposal create a broad performance criterion to measure a state's success by its "caseload reduction."  States receive credit for caseload reductions that occur because of a decrease in out-of-wedlock births, because of an increase in marriage, or because of an increase employment of single mothers.
<p>
	This broad pro-marriage emphasis in H.R. 4 has been replaced with a narrow focus on employing single mothers under S. 1120. For example, under H.R. 4 a state is given equal credit if an AFDC mother gets off welfare through marriage or by getting a job. But under the leadership bill, the state receives credit only if the single mother obtains a job. The anti-marriage bias of S. 1120 can be corrected, in part, by replacing the narrow performance measure, with its emphasis on exits through employment, (2) with the broader measure of caseload reduction used in the House bill.
<p>

<b>Leadership Bill May Limit State Actions to Reduce Illegitimacy</b>
<p>
	Under the leadership bill, states have the authority, if they wish, to establish a family cap or to restrict cash aid to unmarried mothers under age 18. As noted, these provisions are redundant since, under the block grant, the states can set their own standards of eligibility. In fact, inserting these provisions into the block grant easily could be interpreted by the courts as a restriction barring a state from taking more forceful action against illegitimacy. For example, the S. 1120 provision allowing states to restrict cash aid to unwed mothers under age 18 might be interpreted as barring a state government from restricting aid to never-married mothers aged 18 and 19. The leadership provision, as worded, may create an entitlement to aid for never-married mothers over age 18. Legal aid offices certainly will argue that it does. To avoid this problem, the provision at least should be clarified to assert that no restriction on stronger state policies to reduce illegitimacy is intended.
<p>

<b>Conclusion</b>
<p>
	The Clinton and Senate leadership positions on marriage and illegitimacy currently are virtually identical. Both would have the effect of preserving a welfare system that actually promotes illegitimacy and destroys marriage, while making reforms that only tinker around the edges of current law.
<p>
<b>Endnotes:</b>
<p>
1. For a detailed discussion of the extent of the crisis, see Patrick F. Fagan, "Rising Illegitimacy: Amerioca's Social Catastrophe," Heritage Foundation F.Y.I. No. 19, June 29, 1994.
<p>
2. See Section 404(b), page 29, lines 1 and 2.<p>
<p><p>
