<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Let the Diamond Shine</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff">
<img src="/empower/easmall.gif">
<P>
<center>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>Let the Diamond Shine<BA>
</FONT></B>
<P>
Op-Ed by Jack Kemp and Kevin P. Chavous
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2>as printed in the Washington Post, May 5, 1996<BA>
</center>
</FONT></I>
<blockquote>
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; In the 1970's, the Kerner Commission report sparked a national debate with its assessment of America as two cities, one black and one white, permanently divided into two almost irreconcilable classes.  While the divide which the Kerner Commission exposed was, in so far as it goes, a real and significant problem for the nation, the Commission's diagnosis was, in our opinion, wrong.  America is not divided into two classes based on race; it is divided into two economies.   
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Our nation's macro economy is a democratic-capitalist economy, based on private property and rewards for productive human activity.  However, we also have a concurrent, micro economy that is almost a Third-World socialist welfare state that places barriers and impediments to productive human activity. This fact has become increasingly clear over the past two decades, and nowhere is it better illustrated than in our nation's capital, Washington, D.C.  
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; In Washington, dire financial problems coupled with one of the highest marginal income tax rates in the country and a consequent middle class exodus have only emphasized the dichotomy between two coexisting economies:  a democratic capitalist, market-oriented, entrepreneurial economy which rewards work, investment, saving and productivity; and a second near-socialist economy which, though set up with noble intentions, places barriers to productive human and social activity and has a virtual absence of economic incentive. 
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 1960, the population of the District has declined by 25 percent, as both black and white residents have escaped the burden of high taxes coupled with poor quality services and education.  This development simply compounds other economic and social problems in the capital city.    
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The reality is, the system in the District is in a crisis.  The capital city is in danger of falling victim to the inertia of the status quo.  And politically expedient, short-term solutions, while they may temporarily slow the decline in the capital's struggling economy, will not fix the underlying problem.   But in keeping with our national spirit of indomitable optimism, we view this crisis as an opportunity -- an opportunity for Democrats and Republicans, blacks and whites, conservatives and liberals, in both public and private sectors to work together to demonstrate incontrovertibly that freedom and free enterprise solutions work.
At this critical juncture in the District's history, the finger-pointing and acrimony over who's at fault for the various problems must end.  Virtually all parties, the Congress and the D.C. government, have had a hand in allowing the problems to escalate to this serious level.  And likewise, we must together find ways to heal and rebuild the District into a shining city on a hill for the rest of the world to see and emulate.
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Spending cuts and fiscal restraint must be an integral part of any plan to relieve the current financial burden and restore credibility to the nation's capital.  But we believe the most important step is for the District government and Congress to fully embrace the proposal to reinvigorate the District announced last month by Eleanor Holmes Norton, the District's non-voting delegate to the House of Representatives.  Ms. Norton has introduced the D.C. Economic Recovery Act, also known as a progressive flat tax plan, which will create much needed jobs, expand the tax base and serve as a great enticement to middle-class families to come back home to Washington.  
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Her plan, which would tax all individuals at a single, low rate with generous deductions for families would take low-income families off the tax rolls and at the same time promote working, saving, investing, and entrepreneurship -- all things of which the District is desperately in need.  Most of all, a zero capital gains tax on people and businesses in the city would attract both capital and people back into the city and would allow low- and middle- income people the access to the capital necessary to start their version of the American dream.
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Members of Congress on both sides of the aisle praised Representative Norton for her proposal.  In fact, one of the only reservations to surface was a fear that the District, which has a history of tax increases, would raise local rates to take advantage of the increase in after-tax income that Norton's bill would provide to the middle class taxpayer.  
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The obvious answer to that concern is to introduce a plan for the District's local tax system that would mirror the federal system proposed by Norton.  In other words, not only would D.C. residents and businesses have a low single tax rate at the federal level, they would also have a low single rate at the local level.  The result of the complementary plans would create a flood of capital and credit into the District which would dramatically expand the tax base, easily raise more revenues than the current systems and help attract the middle class back into the District.
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The out-lying suburbs in Virginia and Maryland, contrary to their fears, would also feel a positive impact from the District's recovery.  They must realize that economics in a free-market system is not a zero-sum game.  Economic activity in the area will pick up, more people will buy homes, create jobs, and consume goods and services.  Economic vitality will not stop at the borders of the District of Columbia, it will inevitably spill over. 
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The necessary reforms, including a thorough review of the fundamental structure of D.C. home rule, if undertaken with reason and given time and resources, will transform the District to the thriving capital city we all envision, attracting new residents and families rather than forcing them away.  Congress, the mayor, the council, the control board, local businesses, D.C. residents, and the outlying suburbs all have an important role to play in Washington's transformation, but all parties must lay aside previously held biases or ill-feelings for past transgressions or failings.  All stake-holders in the District's revitalization, including the president of the United States, must come together to begin forging a vision for the future of the District of Columbia.
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Despite sharp political and philosophical division, consensus can be reached on a way to obtain full representation for D.C. residents, improve management and oversight and increase revenues.  Unless the core issues that affect the city's foundation are honestly addressed, the underpinnings of Home Rule will remain tenuous.
<p>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; The budget and management problems faced by the city are not unique.  Washington is not the first city to require outside assistance to help resolve a complicated fiscal dilemma.  Other jurisdictions have met the challenge.  For a multitude of reasons, the District has not.  However, rather than assign blame, the prudent course of action is simply to keep the pressure on.  Somewhere amid the mire and misery is a diamond of a city, yearning to be uncovered so that it can shine as an example for others to follow.
<p>

<i>Jack Kemp is a co-director of Empower America.  Kevin P. Chavous is a member of the D.C. Council.</i>

</blockquote>  
</BODY>
