<html>
<head>
<title>Kemp:  A Pro-Growth Compromise</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="/empower/easmall.gif">
<p>
<center><h2>A Pro-Growth Compromise</h2> 
By <a href="kemp.html">Jack Kemp</a> 
<P><i>November 19, 1995</i><P></center><hr>
<P> 
<blockquote>
We live in an extraordinary era -- when two former mortal enemies throughout half of 
this century can meet in cooperation hundreds of miles overhead.  If American astronauts 
and Russian cosmonauts can forge a partnership in space, surely the leaders of the 
preeminent institution in the history of the world can do at least as well on <i>terra 
firma</i>.  And they <i>can</i>.  The current impasse between Congress and the White 
House can be broken with a pro-growth tax policy which will allow both sides to declare 
a win.  It is no secret that the holdup between President Clinton and the Republican 
Congressional leadership has been over whose economic model would be used in passing 
a budget.  The White House preferred their own Office of Management and Budgets', 
which paints a moderately rosy picture of the economy over the next seven years, while 
the Congressional leadership favored the more non-partisan Congressional Budget 
Office's bleaker outlook which required bigger cuts and more fiscal restraint in order to 
get the budget in balance by 2002. 
<P> 
Up until the president vetoed the Budget Reconciliation yesterday (?), the Republican 
leadership was bound to hold fast to the economic assumptions of the Congressional 
Budget Office.  The arduous process of reconciling the budget disallowed any adjustment 
to CBO's predictions on economic growth without starting the long budget process over 
again at square one.  In other words, if the GOP had blinked in their negotiations with the 
president last week, they would have placed the entire year's work on the reconciliation in 
jeopardy.  Now that the budget has been vetoed by the president, it can be altered without 
the cumbersome rules governing the reconciliation. 
<P> 
The problems last week came when the president understandably tried to negotiate with 
the GOP on their budget language attached to the Continuing Resolution, which would 
have averted the partial governmental shutdown.  But, due to the importance of passing 
the reconciliation on Friday, the GOP had no room to compromise.  Even a non-binding 
compromise at that point would have undermined the hard-fought cuts, passed in large 
part due to the GOP's freshman class, and thus threatened final passage on the budget.  
And not only were the long term benefits of a balanced budget and restrained spending at 
stake, the real crown jewels of the budget, which are the pro-growth, pro-family tax cuts 
from the Contract With America, were at risk. 
<P> 
Furthermore, the GOP would have been ill-advised to break their promise to balance the 
budget made during the electoral sweep of 1994.  Therefore, they still cannot venture 
away from the CBO numbers or their budget will be labeled as a deficit building 
proposal.   
<P> 
Now that the budget is back in the hands of Congress and can be revised, there is an 
obvious solution to the stalemate which will save the Republican's balanced budget while 
still giving the President some elbow room on spending restraints he can live with.  And 
most importantly of all, this solution will afford the American economy the opportunity 
to grow and flourish during the next seven years -- which is a benefit neither of the 
current proposals have yet to promise. 
<P> 
Congress has been using CBO's very conservative growth predictions which were 
calculated in April of this year.  Again, because they started the process with these 
numbers, they could not change them mid-stream without beginning the entire process 
from scratch.  Since CBO updates its predictions throughout the year, there already exists 
a considerably more optimistic set of assumptions approved in August.  Congress can 
now alter its baseline predictions for the budget to the new CBO numbers and have a lot 
of room to negotiate without losing their "balance".  The CBO's January 1996 numbers 
are expected to be even more positive. 
<P> 
The August CBO numbers give Congress $29 billion dollars more to work with in the 
first two years, and this does not account for the additional amount made available with 
next January's adjustment.  This will theoretically be more than enough room to give the 
president his measure of "victory" in the form of more spending on education, Medicare, 
and other programs near and dear to his heart.  Better yet, it could also leave enough 
money to pay for, in my view, the Contract With America's most important provision -- 
the indexation of capital gains.  Clearly a win for both sides of this standoff and certainly 
a win for the American electorate. 
<P> 
Moreover, if the GOP can reach an agreement on the balanced budget that includes the 
indexation on capital gains they will have won a double victory for the American people.  
For, while the CBO and the OMB consider the indexation as a net cost due to their 
mostly static model, in actuality, indexation on capital gains will provide a boon to the 
economy and, subsequently, an increase in federal revenue.   
<P> 
It works like this:  (1) high tax rates discourage entrepreneurship and investment which, 
in turn, prohibits growth in the national economy; (2) without indexation, the already 
high capital gains tax rate is effectively escalated, leaving entrepreneurs to pay taxes on 
inflated gains; (3) indexation of capital gains would result in a lower effective tax rate 
than a straight cut in the tax rate itself would (assuming a 3% real rate of return, the 
current CPI rate of about 3% carries a real tax rate of 56%--even reducing the nominal 
rate to 19.5% with no indexing would mean a real capital gains rate of nearly 40% at 
current rates of inflation.); (4) therefore, instituting the indexation on capital gains would 
remove or diminish existing barriers to entrepreneurship and investment and thereby free 
up capital in the economy.  This would create a more efficient and liquid capital market, 
drawing capital to low-income and high-risk entrepreneurial ventures. 
<P> 
The president and Congress must reach an agreement soon.  The American people will 
not stand for an on-going stalemate.  None of the parties involved, though, will concede 
defeat on one of the most watched budget debates in our history.  President Clinton, 
Speaker Gingrich, Senator Dole, and their ranks must move quickly to take advantage of 
this unique opportunity to both balance the budget and spur tremendous economic growth 
as we enter the twenty-first century. 
 
<P><P>
</blockquote>
<center>[ <a href="/empower/welcome.html">Empower America Home</a> 
]</body></html> 
 

