<html>
<head>
<title>Letter to Strom Thurmond re: ABM Treaty and SDI</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
August 1, 1995
<br>
<br>
<p>
<p>
The Honorable Strom Thurmond<br>
United States Senate<br>
Washington, DC  20510<br>
<p>
Dear Chairman Thurmond:
<p>
We are really pleased that you are addressing the most important issue in defense policy for our times:  the capacity of America to defend itself.  As you and other members of the Senate Armed Services Committee have determined, our nation needs a ballistic missile defense program.  For most of our history, what George Washington described as "our blessed location" made us invulnerable to attack by hostile nations.  But because technology overcame the security of location, we are no longer invulnerable.  Today, we lack the capacity to defend ourselves against ballistic missiles.  But most Americans do not yet understand our vulnerability to attacks by ballistic missiles.  Most Americans do not yet understand that for the first time in our history, when we speak of defense, we must now include our capacity to defend our country.
<p>
It dismays us, then, that instead of focusing on our current needs, opponents of ballistic missile defense worry about outdated arms control treaties with countries that no longer exist.  They argue that moving to develop needed defenses and modifying the ABM Treaty will jeopardize the possibility of Russian ratification of the START II Treaty.  American security should not be sacrificed in a vain effort to preserve the ABM Treaty.  The ABM Treaty, designed for a bipolar world, always had dubious value.  It is now wholly outdated.  It's only relevance to the contemporary world is not how it influences the START II Treaty, whose ratification by Russia, in any case, is uncertain irrespective of any action on the ABM Treaty.  The only relevance of the ABM Treaty to the contemporary world is to hamper an effective effort to defend America.
<p>
The development of missile defenses today is technologically and economically feasible.  We can speak and act with confidence in the world only when we can defend ourselves.  Our allies, adversaries and friends -- including the Russians -- all understand this.  It is time for the United States to defend the American people.
<p>
Sincerely,<p>
<br>
Jack Kemp<br>
Jeane Kirkpatrick
<p>
<br>
[ <a href="i-ps-lc.html">Letters to Congress</a> | <a href="welcome.html">Home</a> ]
