<html>
<head>
<title>Letters to Congress from Jack Kemp on the B-2</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
July 31, 1995
<br>
<br>
<p>
<p>
Dear Member of Congress :
<p>
The House of Representatives will soon vote on the FY96 Defense Appropriations Bill.  The vote to continue production of the B-2 bomber is one of several significant national security decisions the House will make this year.  The B-2 bomber is an essential system for current and future defenses for our nation.
<p>
When the B-2 becomes operational in the very near future, the United States will have the unprecedented capability to deliver precision-guided munitions to any point on the globe from the continental United States with the confidence that the aircrew will return safely.  For example, had the B-2 been available in 1987, only one or two B-2s would have conducted the raid on Libya.  Moreover, the need to obtain permission from allies to overfly their territory and the costly and vast network of support and crews that placed hundreds of Americans at risk would have been unnecessary.  Because of the widespread recognition that the B-2 can stop aggressors in their tracks, conventional deterrence will be greatly enhanced.  And as the Heritage Foundation has suggested, in the future, the B-2 will also allow us to effectively attack mobile missile systems, thereby increasing U.S. offensive abilities.
<p>
Thus far, the post-Cold War era has been characterized with promise, opportunity, challenges and dangers.  The United States must have the capability for forceful and independent action and our advanced weapons systems are an essential element of that capacity.  The B-2 represents a significant breakthrough technology that will give us a singular and unparalleled military ability to act.  Systems such as the B-2 are vital to our role in a changing world.  The United States must be strong in order to lead; no one can do it but us.  I urge you to support continued production of the B-2 bomber program
<p>
Sincerely,<p>
<br>
Jack Kemp
<p>
<br>
[ <a href="i-ps-lc.html">Letters to Congress</a> | <a href="welcome.html">Home</a> ]
</body>
