<head>
<title>"The Pete and Jesse Show"</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center>
<h1>Wilson, Jackson swap sound bites<br>
in sparring over affirmative action</h1>
</center>
<br>
By SCOTT THURM<br>
Mercury News Staff Writer<p>
 Call it ''The Pete and Jesse Show.''<p>
   Gov. Pete Wilson and the Rev. Jesse Jackson -- representing 
polar opposites in the national debate over affirmative action 
-- sparred by satellite across two television networks Sunday, 
bringing far more heat than light to the difficult question of 
how America should treat women and minority groups.<p>
   Neither man said much new as they contested the fallout of 
Thursday's decision by the University of California regents to 
abandon considerations of gender, race and ethnicity in 
hiring, promotions and admissions.<p>
   Instead, each seemed to take perverse delight in 
antagonizing the other, all the while trying to score sound 
bites that might be aired on still other news shows.<p>
<h4>"Ethnic cleansing"</h4>
    Jackson called Wilson ''corrupt'' because several regents 
are among his largest campaign contributors. And he accused 
the governor of ''ethnic cleansing'' for pursuing policies 
that studies have shown will reduce the numbers of blacks and 
Hispanics at the university's nine campuses.<p>
   In response, Wilson chided Jackson for ''childish name-
calling'' and accused the civil-rights leader of 
''demagoguery'' in a ''pathetic effort to divert attention 
from the real issue.''<p>
   In fact, each was using the other as a convenient foil 
while addressing different audiences: Wilson is seeking 
support among Republicans for his presidential campaign; 
Jackson wants to rally defenders of civil rights, while 
encouraging speculation about his own presidential ambitions.<p>
<h2>Suited for each other</h2>
    ''No two people in America need each other more now than 
Jesse Jackson and Pete Wilson,'' Sam Popkin, a political 
science professor at the University of California, San Diego 
said last week. ''United they rise, and united they fall.''<p>
Amid the shouting, several Clinton administration officials 
said Sunday they will examine whether the UC system would 
violate federal law by dropping its affirmative-action 
programs.<p>
   Privately, federal officials have said they don't foresee 
any action, because federal law generally permits government 
agencies to use race, gender or ethnicity as a factor in 
hiring, promotion and admission decisions but does not require 
they be considered.<p>
   Wilson made that point on Cable News Network's ''Late 
Edition,'' where he criticized the Clinton administration for 
''shameful threats'' against the university.<p>
<h4>1996 ballot measure</h4>
    In his most sweeping statement to date, Wilson said Sunday 
that as president he would favor eliminating all federal 
programs that consider gender, race or ethnicity for hiring, 
promotions or contracts. Wilson supports a proposed 1996 
ballot measure that would abolish those considerations in 
California.<p>
   As Wilson and Jackson stake out the extremes, President 
Clinton may win favor from the public for his plea last week 
to repair the excesses of affirmative action while maintaining 
efforts to help women and minorities overcome centuries of 
discrimination.<p>
   Even Wilson concedes that discrimination still exists. But 
he claims that affirmative-action programs -- which Wilson 
supported for more than 20 years -- now divide Americans along 
racial and ethnic lines, penalizing whites and stigmatizing 
successful women and minority groups. The United States should 
achieve gender and racial diversity ''on the natural,'' Wilson 
argues, by improving health and education programs for 
everyone.<p>
<h2>Clinton on Jackson's side</h2>
   But Jackson -- and Clinton -- maintain that women and 
minority groups still need a helping hand from government to 
overcome ''glass ceilings and closed doors.'' For example, 
Jackson noted Sunday that Hispanic women with college degrees 
earn less than white men who have never been to college. And 
they contend that critics of affirmative action, like Wilson, 
are trying to divide Americans for selfish political reasons.<p>
It's ''divisive, hurtful and irresponsible,'' said the 
assistant attorney general for civil rights, Deval Patrick, 
who joined Wilson and Jackson on ABC's ''This Week with David 
Brinkley.''<p>
<br>
<a href="http:www.sjmercury.com/wilson.htm">Go to the Pete Wilson Home Page</a><br>
<a href="wilsbio.html">Pete Wilson Biography</a><br>
