<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>Alan Keyes: Statement of Purpose</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY> 
<center>
<h2>Alan Keyes: Statement of Purpose</h2>
</center>
<br>
<HR>
<BR>
These days almost everyone acknowledges that the root of most of America's
problems lies in the decline of our nation's moral identity.  Crime,
rampant illegitimacy, the deteriorating environment for education in too
many of our schools, even the cost pressures in our health care system can
be traced to bad actions and habits that result from the decline of respect
for decent values in our society.  Yet when our political leaders address
these issues, most still run away from their fundamental moral dimension.<p>
In a <cite>USA Today</cite> interview, for example, one Republican presidential
aspirant, Senator Phil Gramm of Texas, addressed the welfare problem.  He
spoke of the need to put time limits on welfare and to encourage welfare
recipients to work.  He even addressed the issue of orphanages.  Not once
did he mention marriage.  Yet a significant portion of the welfare burden
comes from single, unwed mothers.  For forty years or more, the government
pursued welfare policies that mass-produced fatherless children.  If today
we impose work requirements without promoting marriage, we will turn the
fatherless children into <em>de facto</em> orphans.  Yet Senator Gramm is oblivious
to the need to make promotion of marriage a policy objective.<p>
We can no longer afford to follow leaders for whom the moral challenge this
nation faces is an afterthought, when it ought to be the primary objective
of national policy.  That's why the leaders who want to finesse or run away
from the issue of abortion are not good enough either.  Today the spirit of
violence in our society is so great that our children are literally killing
one another.  What else should we expect in a nation where mothers have been
granted the spurious "right" to kill their offspring at will?  The
mother-child relationship is the wellspring of trust and love in a society.
The paradigm of all peace and security  should be the peace of the unborn
child in the womb.  The pro-abortion doctrine poisons the wellspring.  As
long as our courts sanction murder in the womb, they will be filled with
the consequences of violence in our streets, schools, workplaces and homes.
Politicians who run from the issue of abortion declare by that moral
cowardice their unwillingness to confront the killing spirit of our times.<p>
We need leaders who are willing to confront the moral identify crisis in
our nation, who are able to articulate and discuss the vital questions of
principle that will determine the kind of people we are and want to be.
Yet in domestic affairs, too many of our leaders seem willing to surrender
America's identity without a fight.  That was the real significance of the
obscene haste with which a "lame duck" Congress passed the GATT/WTO
agreement.  Many Americans feel that this agreement grants excessive
authority to an international organization on terms that violate
fundamental American tenets of political legitimacy.  They feel that it
embodies a threat to our national independence and identity.  Yet our
supposed leaders stigmatized such concerns as evidence of "extremism," and
embraced an agreement that bore all the marks of the Clinton
Administration's negotiating incompetence.<p>
Others have criticized the voters of California for demanding, through
Proposition 187, that the integrity of residence and citizenship within our
borders be supported with effective enforcement of the distinctions between
legal and illegal immigration.  They have implied that this demand is
evidence of bigotry, intolerance and racism.  Since when is it racist to
insist that laws, which no one denies our right to make, be enforced
against foreign citizens who violate them?<P>
<a href="http://sandh.com/keyes/index.html">The Unofficial Alan Keyes Home Page</a><br>
<a href="keyesbio.html">Biography of Alan Keyes</a><br>
<a href="contents.html">Introduction</a>
</body>
