<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff">
<blockquote>
<img src="discussi.gif"><hr>							

<h2><i><center>Aspen96 Panel Discussant Information</center></i></h2>
<P>
<font face="arial" size=+1>
<b>Fritz E. Attaway</b> is Senior Vice President for Government Relations and Washington General Counsel for the Motion Picture Association of America, Inc.   
<P>
<b>Tom Barry</b> is Senior Vice President-Federal Relations for SBC Telecommunications, Inc., a subsidiary of SBC Communications, one of the world's leading diversified telecommunications companies.
<P>
<STRONG>Edward J. Black</STRONG> is President of the Computer & Communications Industry Association, a trade association representing a broad cross-section of firms in the information technology industry.
<P>
<STRONG>William W. Burrington</STRONG> is Director of Law and Public Policy at America Online, Inc.  Bill is co-author of the 
<i>Interactive Marketplace Regulatory Handbook</i> and is a frequent speaker on emerging cyberspace legal and public policy issues.
<P>
<STRONG>Daniel Farrell Burton, Jr.</STRONG> is Vice President for Government Relations of Novell, Inc.  Dan has edited three books, most recently 
<i>Vision for the 1990s: U.S. Strategy and the Global Economy</i>. 
<P>
<STRONG>Peter Choy</STRONG> is Deputy General Counsel for Sun Microsystems primarily responsible for intellectual property policy.
<P>
<STRONG>Roger J. Cochetti</STRONG> is Program Director, Policy and Business Planning of IBM's Internet Division.   Roger is the author of numerous articles and a book on telecommunications topics.
<P>
<STRONG>W. Bowman Cutter</STRONG> is Managing Director of the venture capital firm of Warburg, Pincus. He was formally Deputy Assistant to the President for Economic Policy.
<P>
<STRONG>Russell Daggatt</STRONG> is President of Teledesic Corporation of Kirkland, Washington.  He is co-author of the book <i>The Global Negotiator  Building Strong Business Relationships Anywhere in the
World 

</i>.
<P>
<STRONG>Rhett B. Dawson</STRONG> is President of the Information Technology Industry Council, a trade association promoting the global competitiveness of leading information technology companies.
<P>
<STRONG>Kimberly Jenkins</STRONG> is founder, Executive Director and Chairman of Highway 1, a non-profit, Washington, D.C.-based corporation created to enhance communication between government and the people.
<P>
<STRONG>Kenneth R. Kay</STRONG> is a Principal of Podesta Associates, Inc., a Washington, D.C. based government affairs and public relations firm.
<P>
<STRONG>Larry Kenswil</STRONG> is Executive Vice President, Business and Legal Affairs, for MCA Music Entertainment Group.
<P>
<STRONG>Ellwood R. Kerkeslager</STRONG>  is Vice President of Technology and Infrastructure for AT&T.  He is responsible for developing policy in the areas of Computers, Data Communications, Wireless and Core Technologies.
<P>
<STRONG>Robert C.  Kirkwood</STRONG> is Director of Government Affairs for Hewlett-Packard and is responsible for working with HP managers worldwide and with state and federal legislators, government officials and industry associations on public policies affecting the interests of HP.
<P>
<STRONG>Gerry Kovach</STRONG> is Senior Vice President of Government Relations for MCI Communications.  Prior to joining MCI in 1985, Mr. Kovach was Chief of Staff and Chief Counsel of the U.S. Senate Commerce, Science and Transportation Committee.
<P>
<STRONG>Robbin F. Laird</STRONG> is Chief Partner of International Communications and Strategic Assessments and specializes in public policy issues with a special interest in Europe and Russia.  Most recently he has completed a study entitled "The New Information Society and the Evolving U.S. National Security System at the Turn of the Century".
<P>
<STRONG>Barbara Lawton</STRONG> is Deming Professor of Management at the University of Colorado, Boulder, and an Adjunct Fellow at The Progress & Freedom Foundation. 
<P>
<STRONG>Larry F. Martinez</STRONG> is an Associate Professor of Political Science at the California State University at Long Beach.  His book, <i>Communications Satellites: Power Politics in Space</i>, examines the political, technical and legal aspects of outer space.
<P>
<STRONG>Dennis McKenna</STRONG> is CEO and Editor-in-Chief of "Government 
Technology", a national monthly publication covering information technology applications and public policy at the state and local level. 
<P>
<STRONG>Richard E. Nohe</STRONG> is Director of Corporate Affairs for NTT America overseeing research and government relations.
<P>
<STRONG>Suzanne Richardson</STRONG> is Partner and Managing Director at Friedman, Billings, Ramsey & Co., a Washington, D.C.-based investment bank, research and brokerage firm.
<P>
<STRONG>Quincy Rodgers</STRONG> is a Vice President of General Instrument Corporation with responsibility for public and government affairs.
<P>
<STRONG>Art Sackler</STRONG> is Vice President, Law and Public Policy of Time Warner, Inc., where he is responsible for issues relating to intellectual property, trade, marketing and the on-line environment generally.
<P>
<STRONG>George Spix</STRONG> is Chief Architect in the Commercial Products Division for Mircosoft Corporation responsible for end-to-end solutions for consumer appliances and public networks.
<P>
<STRONG>Kent D. Stuckey</STRONG> is Director of Business Development and Vice President of CompuServe Ventures Incorporated.  Kent is author of  <i>The Business and Legal Aspects of the Internet and Online Services</i>.
<P>
<STRONG>John Sullivan Wilson</STRONG> is Vice President for Technology Policy at the Information Technology Industry Council in Washington, D.C., and a visiting fellow at the Institute for International Economics. 
<P>
<STRONG>Edward D. Young, III</STRONG> is Bell Atlantic's Associate General Counsel and Vice President for External Affairs.  He also serves on the Board of Directors for the U.S. Telephone Association and the U.S. Technical Training Institute.
