<html><head>
<title>Senator Bill Bradley Profile</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="discussi.gif">
<hr>
<blockquote>
<font face="arial"> 
<center>
<img src="bradley.gif" align="left">
<h1>Senator Bill Bradley</h1>
<h2>A Profile</h2>
</center>
Bill Bradley is the senior U.S. Senator from New Jersey. A Democrat, he was elected to his third term in 1990. From the day he arrived in the Senate in 1979, Bradley has devoted himself to building a more secure future for Americans by creating a strong and growing economy, providing new educational opportunities, and bridging the gaps between people of different races and nations. He serves on the Senate Finance Committee, the Energy and Natural Resources Committee, and the Special Committee on Aging.
<P><br>
<b><center>Tax Relief, Economic Priorities and Deficit Reduction</center></b>
<br>
Senator Bradley is widely known as the author of the proposed Fair Tax, which eventually becarne the Tax Reform Act of 1986. His tax reforms were based on the principle that people of equal incomes should pay equal taxes. Despite a widespread belief that special interests would prevail, Bradley succeeded in sharply reducing tax rates for all Americans by eliminating most corporate and individual loopholes-in the tax code. It required taxpayers who had avoided paying taxes to pay their fair share, gave tax relief to families, and insured that six million low-income working people would pay no federal tax.
<p>
As a member of the Finance Committee, Bradley has continued to fight for fair tax policy, honest budgeting, and economic policies that enhance competitiveness and growth.
<p>
Bradley has centered his attention on the federal government's debt and deficit crises. He believes that the United States will not be able to compete in the world economy in the next century without significant reductions in both. The first, and most important step that can be taken on the road back to fiscal responsibility, is to dramatically reduce unnecessary government spending.
<p>
Bradley believes that the government spends too much taxpayer money, and often for the wrong purposes. To bring reason to our spending priorities, he has proposed two principles to guide all federal funding decisions: one, the proposal must be in the general interest and essential to public life; and two, taxpayer funding must be the most cost-effective way to finance the proposal.
<p>
Bradley's actions follow these principles. In 1994, the bipartisan Concord Coalition ranked Bradley third among all Senate Democrats for his anti-spending votes. And in the 103rd Congress alone, he offered amendments to appropriations bills that would have saved nearly 600 million taxpayer dollars.
<p>
Bradley is the author of the enhanced line-item veto proposal, a measure which grants the President authority to remove wasteful spending from both appropriations and tax bills. He is also an advocate of major budget reform, which would remove many of the obstacles Congress has erected to real spending reductions.
<p><br>
<b><center>A National Rebellion Against Crime and Violence</center></b>
<br>

In 1994, Senator Bradley issued a call to arms - against the crime and violence that are ravaging our lives and our neighborhoods. In a compelling speech, Bradley demanded a national rebellion against violence, a new commitment by individuals, communities and government against the destruction that is threatening our democratic freedoms.
<p>
Bradley breaks through the clutter of anti-crime rhetoric by arguing that there is no single, simple solution to our crisis of violence. No political posturing will solve it, and no progress will be made unless we all make a contribution. The answers lie closer to home than to Washington, D.C. When only 5% of all crimes are federal crimes and the federal government controls just 13% of the crime-fighting resources, local communities must actively engage in the rebellion. Bradley knows they can -- he has spent many hours in New Jersey communities, hearing about and working with local residents who are involved in their neighborhoods to stop the violence.
<p>
Bradley has successfully fought for innovative new measures to help the federal government assist these efforts. He wrote legislation, adopted in the 1994 Crime Bill, to greatly expand community policing and to help put 100,000 new police on the street nationwide. These community policing forces can forge valuable ties to the neighborhood residents they serve and detect trouble before it turns into crime. The Crime Bill also includes Bradley's Community Schools program, a bold new venture that encourages schools to stay open after hours, on weekends, and all summer to help community leaders provide at-risk children a safe place to learn and play.
<p>
Bradley has also emerged as an advocate of tough, common-sense gun control. He is the author of new legislation which will stop the flow of illegal handguns. By requiring national handgun ID cards, registration of private handgun transfers, greatly increased gun dealer licensing fees, and a limit on purchases, Bradley believes gun violence can be markedly reduced.
<p><br>
<b><center>Race and the American City</center></b>
<br>

Senator Bradley has been described as one of the most eloquent and prophetic speakers on the issue of race relations in our country. He has established himself as a serious voice in the national dialogue on racism, pluralism, and discrimination. Senator Bradley has criticized both political parties and challenged every American to confront the reality of racial prejudices by asking each of us, "When was the last time you talked about race with someone of a different race? If the answer is never, you're part of the problem."
<p>
From a socioeconomic standpoint, he has stressed that by the year 2000, only 57 percent of the people entering the workforce will be native-born whites. In his keynote speech at the 1992 Democratic Convention, he reiterated his strong conviction that "we will all advance together, or each of us will be diminished."
<p>
Senator Bradley sees a critical link between tense race relations and the decay of American cities. He advocates significant national investment and increased personal responsibility in order to halt the deterioration of urban America. Inspired by "leaders of awareness" in churches, schools, businesses, and neighborhoods, Bradley believes we can rebuild our urban communities.
<p>
Bradley's vision for renewal is unique. It is based on successful initiatives designed by local communities themselves. Their leadership is behind Bradley's eight-point Urban Community-Building Initiative, a comprehensive assault on the three crises plaguing urban America: joblessness, violence, and family disintegration. His goal is to expand ideas already working at the local level and help city residents help themselves with programs that provide police, jobs and job training, crime prevention, banking services, and family support.
<p>
Bradley has been remarkably successful in turning this vision into reality. Virtually all of his Urban Community-Building Initiative was enacted into law in 1993-94. Three components - Community Policing, Community Schools, and Community Banking - were approved either in full or more broadly than originally drafted. Four others - Entrepreneurship Training, Mobility for Work, Individual Development Accounts, and Residential Parenting Centers, were included in legislation creating Urban Empowerment Zones.
<p><br>

<b><center>Education: Investing in People</center></b>
<br>
Bradley believes that a college education is invaluable. But he also knows that the cost of higher education has exploded out of reach for too many families.
<p>
In response, Bradley has designed a new way to pay for college. Available at the beginning of the 1994 school year, Bradley's Self-Reliance Loans give all students, regardless of age or income, the chance to borrow money directly from the federal government. Self-Reliance Loans also give students the option of repaying their loans based on income they earn after they graduate.
<p>
The program was available at several colleges in New Jersey and throughout the nation in 1994, and dozens of others will participate in 1995 and beyond. Bradley's initiative will help families who don't qualify for traditional financial aid, and students who cannot afford huge monthly loan repayments immediately after graduation. By eliminating the expensive and unnecessary role banks play in student loans, the program saves taxpayer money. ' And, in an economy that demands highly skilled workers, the program offers everyone the opportunity to go back to school for the training they need to compete in the labor market.
<p>
Senator Bradley has also worked for years to improve elementary and secondary education through the Family-School Partnership Act, and programs for Gifted and Talented students. He hosts several annual events in New Jersey to honor the achievements of young students. Thousands of New Jersey high school students have participated in events such as High School Leadership Seminars and Student-Athlete Conferences over the last 14 years.
<p><br>
<b><center>The Health and Well-Being of Families</center></b>
<br>

Bill Bradley is deeply concerned about the burden of health care costs on America's families. He supports national health care reform that would reduce costs, increase coverage, and ensure quality care for every American.
<p>
Calling domestic violence "America's dark litle secret," Bradley has launched a major effort to respond to the tragedy of spousal abuse. It is a social sickness, and women and children are its most common casualties. Bradley has spoken out forcefully on the need to confront domestic violence, and to make sure its victims get the help they need: protection, counseling, and education about their rights.
<p>
Bradley believes we need comprehensive welfare reform that promotes personal responsibility, and has spearheaded the overhaul of child support collection in New Jersey and the nation. And for families caring for disabled and elderly relatives at home, he is seeking to expand a successful New Jersey project that offers respite services to family caregivers.
<p><br>
<b><center>Rethinking American Leadership</center></b>
<br>
Senator Bradley believes that American leadership in the future will depend more on our economic productivity and the force of our values, rather than on our military might.
<p>
Bradley is a leading proponent of international free trade. He was one of the champions of the North American Free Trade Agreement, working tirelessly in 1993 to ensure passage of a plan he defined as a "historic moment" on America's path toward global economic growth. He advocates an open trading system worldwide, and co-authored the report that served as the blueprint for the Uruguay Round of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, which Congress passed in late 1994.
<p>
Bradley, well known as an expert on the former Soviet Union, considers investing in people and the values of democracy the best way to build lasting security and peace in the post-cold war era. Based on these principles, he authored and passed the 1992 Freedom Exchange Act, the largest U.S. educational exchange initiative in history. Already, more than 10,000 "Bradley kids" have come to the U.S. from the former Soviet Union to study and absorb the lessons of freedom, democracy, and a market economy.
<p><br>

<b><center>Protecting the Environment</center></b>
<br>

Bradley entered the Senate in 1978 with a strong commitment to protect the environment. In 1980, he helped draft the Superfund toxic-waste cleanup bill. Since then, he has pursued legislation to track medical waste in our oceans, prevent oil spills, restore and preserve beaches, rivers, and wildlife, and ban toxic lead from the environment. Most recently, Bradley secured passage of the South Jersey Wild and Scenic River Act. This landmark legislation will protect a 35-mile stretch of the Maurice River and its tributaries, guaranteeing that future generations can enjoy the waterway in its current pristine condition.
<p>
As chairman of the Water and Power Subcommittee, Bradley also passed the Omnibus Water Bill of 1992, the most important piece of water legislation in a generation. The bill's most significant component requires a major overhaul of the nation's largest water project, the Central Valley Project of California. This law cuts wasteful subsidies to agriculture special interests, redistributes water resources to city residents who suffered a seven year drought, and protects endangered wildlife.
<p><br>
<center><b>Scholar, Athlete, Author</b></center>
<br>
Before his successful Senate race in 1978, Bill Bradley had achieved distinction in academics and athletics. He was born on July 28, 1943, in Crystal City, Missouri, the son of Warren and Susan Bradley. In 1965, he graduated from Princeton University with honors in American history. He was awarded a Rhodes Scholarship to Oxford University, where he earned a graduate degree after studying politics, philosophy, and economics.
<p>
As an undergraduate, Bradley was a three-time basketball All-American and won the Sullivan Award as the country's outstanding amateur athlete. In 1964, he was captain of the U.S. basketball team that won the gold medal at the Tokyo Olympics.
<p>
After returning from Oxford in 1967, Bradley joined the New York Knicks and played professional basketball for ten years. In 1970 and 1973, the Knicks won the National Basketball Association championship with Bradley as a starting forward. Bradley's book about his decade with the Knicks, <i>Life On The Run</i>, was published in 1976 to wide acclaim.
<p>
Bradley served in the Air Force Reserve from 1967 to 1978, attaining the rank of first lieutenant.
<p>
Bradley's second book, <i>The Fair Tax</i>. was published in 1982 and helped popularize the ideas that eventually became the Tax Reform Act of 1986.
<p>
Bill Bradley and Ernestine Schlant were married in 1974. Ernestine Schlant Bradley is a professor of German and Comparative Literature at Montclair State College. The Bradleys have one daughter, Theresa Anne, and Mrs. Bradley has an adult daughter from a previous marriage. The family lives in Montclair, New Jersey.

</font>
</body></html>
</DOC>
