<HEAD>
<TITLE> Diamond </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="discussi.gif">
<hr>
<blockquote>
<font face="arial">
<h2>EDWIN DIAMOND</H2>
Edwin Diamond is a Professor in the Department of Journalism at NYU, where he has been teaching since 1984.  Diamond's "Behind the Times: lnside The New New York Times," was published by Villard Books, a division of Random House, in 1994. The University of Chicago Press brought out the paperback edition, with new epilogue 1995.  In 1995 too, MIT Press published Diamond's "White House to Your House: Politics and Media in Virtual America."  The co-author, Robert Silverman, began the book with Diamond while an undergraduate at NYU.  MIT Press has also published five of Diamond's 10 books, including "Sign Off: The Last Days of Television," (1982), "The Media Show," and "The Spot: The Rise of Political Advertising on Television" (third edition, 1992).<p>
During the 1994-96 academic years, Diamond was a visiting Fellow at the Annenberg Washington Program in Communications Policy Studies, Washington, D.C., researching a new book on the Internet.  In February, 1996, he began the weekly column Medium Cool for politicsusa.com (the website owned by Times Mirror Corp. of Los Angeles).  Medium Cool is posted every Thursday night, and has a caucus room and archive.<p>
Diamond was a writer and, later, senior editor at Newsweek for 12 years and has worked for newspapers, wire services and television stations in Chicago, Washington, Boston and New York.  From 1984 to 1994, he was the media columnist for New York magazine.  Before joining the NYU faculty, he was a Visiting Professor in the Department of Political Science at MIT. He has won awards for his newspaper reporting, his magazine editing, his critical writings, his columns, books, and his classroom teaching (at both MIT and 
NYU).  In 1994, the Alumni Association of the University of Chicago gave Diamond its  Professional Achievement Award.<p>
Diamond was born in Chicago, where his father was a newspaper writer covering boxing. Diamond was a member of Rogers' Raiders, U.S. Army, in Europe during World War 2 and was a military intelligence officer with the U.S. Army during the Korean War. His military decorations all earned before his 20th birthday, include the Bronze Star Medal with Oak Leaf Cluster (and "V" for Valor devices), The ETO Ribbon with two battle stars, the Combat Infantry Badge, and the Purple Heart.  He completed his undergraduate and graduate work at the University of Chicago on the G.I. Bill. He lives in New York City. </blockquote>
</font>
</BODY>
</HTML>
