<html>
<head>
<title>Biography:</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<img src="discussi.gif">
<hr>
<blockquote>
<font face="arial">
<h2>George Gilder</h2>
<p>

George Gilder is presently a Senior Fellow at the Discovery Institute
in Seattle.

<p>
<img src="gilder.gif" align=right hspace=5 vspace=5>
<p>

Mr. Gilder has authored nine books including: Life After Television,
Microcosm, The Spirit of Enterprise (just reissued in an updated
editions as Recapturing the Spirit of Enterprise), Wealth and Poverty,
Visible Man, Men and Marriage, and The Party That Lost Its Head (with
Bruce Chapman).  He is also contributing editor of Forbes and Forbes
ASAP (Forbes' new technology supplement) as well as a frequent
contributor to a wide range of publications, including the Wall Street
Journal, American Spectator, National Review, and a variety of
electronic business publications.  He is currently working on a new
book on computers entitled Telecosm.

<p>

In his major work, Microcosm, Mr. Gilder explains the quantum roots of
the new electronic and communications technologies and maintains that
the law of the microcosm requires decentralization of both business
and government, in data processing, manufacturing, telecommunications,
and even defense.

<p>

Mr. Gilder pioneered in the formulation of supply-side economics when
he served as chairman of the Lehrman's Institute's Economic
Roundtable, as Program Director for the Manhattan Institute, and as a
frequent contributor to A.B. Laffer economic reports.  Since the
publication of his book Wealth and Poverty, he consulted regularly
with key figures in the Reagan and Bush administrations and with
leaders of America's high technology businesses.

<p>

In addition to his experience as the chairman of a small business,
Mr. Gilder serves on the board of directors of several high technology
companies. Through the Leigh Bureau of Princeton, N.J., Mr. Gilder has
also given several hundred speeches around the world to major
corporations and to conferences on business, technology, and
telecommunications.

<p>

Mr. Gilder is a graduate of Harvard University where he majored in
government, studied under Henry Kissinger, and later taught as a
Fellow at the Kennedy Institute of Politics.

<p>

In 1986, Mr. Gilder was lauded by President Reagan with a White House
award for Entrepreneurial Excellence.

</font>
</body>
</html>

