<head>
<title>Biography for Jerry Jasinowski</title></head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<img src="discussi.gif">
<hr>

<font face="arial">
<blockquote>

<h2>Jerry J. Jasinowski<br>
President National Association of Manufacturers</h2><p>
<img src="jasino.gif" align="left">


Jerry Jasinowski is president of the National Association Manufacturers and one of the nation's most frequently quoted authorities on the economy and the vital role manufacturing plays in America.
<p>
He has addressed audiences across the country -- from The Commonwealth Club of California to the National Press Club in Washington, D.C. -- in his role as:
<ul>
<li>an economist who can assess the rapid changes creating a new economy 

<li>an astute analyst of the impact of federal policies on business 
</uL>
<ul>
<li>an articulate spokesperson on the importance of modern manufacturing to technology, productivity, international competitiveness and economic growth, and how to improve the living standard of America's workers co-author of <i>Making It In America: Proven Paths to Success from 50 Top Cornpanies</i> (Simon & Schuster, March 1995) 

<li>industry's "most powerful advocate on Capitol Hill," according to <i>Washingtonian</i> magazine
</ul><p>
Under Jasinowski's  leadership, the NAM has beein hailed as Wasington' s most influential and respected business group, helping to shape national policy on a broad range of issues from taxes to trade. He is currently calling for a national strategy to boost economic growth by dramatically downsizing and reforming government, particularly in the areas of taxes, regulations and legal burdens, and by encouraging private sector educational improvements, technological programs and export expansion.
<p>
Jasinowski is widely quoted in the media and has appeared on almost every major national network and public affairs program, including ABC's 
<i>Good Morning America</i>, NBC's <i>Today</i> and 
<i>Meet the Press</i>, CNN's <i>Crossfire</i> and <i>Moneyline</i>, John McLaughlin's 
<i>One on One</i> and the evening network news shows. His opinion editorials have run in <i>The New York Times</i>, <i>Chicago Tribune</i>, <i>Harvard Business Review</i>, and other major publications.
<p>
Jasinowski became president of the NAM in January 1990, after serving as the association's executive vice president and chief economist for ten years. The NAM is the largest broad-based industrial trade association in the United States. Its more than 13,500 member companies, including approximately 10,000 small firms, are in every state and account for roughly 85 percent of U.S. manufactured goods.
<p>
A one-time factory worker, Jasinowski joined the U.S. Air Force as intelligence officer serving in the Far East in the mid 1960s. He went on to become assistant professor of economics at the U.S. Air Force Academy. In the early 1970's, Jasinowski came to Washington to manage research and legislative activities for the Joint Economic Committee of Congress. In 1976, he served as director of the Carter Administration's economic transition team for the departments of Treasury, Commerce, Labor, the Council of Economic Advisors and the Federal Reserve. He later was appointed assistant secretary for policy at the U.S. Department of Commerce.
<p>
A native of LaPorte, Indiana, Jasinowski received his B.A. in economics from Indiana University, his master's degree in ePonomics from Columbia University, and is a graduate of the Harvard Business School's Advanced Management Program. He serves on the board of directors for Phoenix Home Life and Atwood Richards.
<p>
Jasinowski has three children and resides in Washington, D.C. with his wife, vice president of government relations for The Goodyear Tire & Rubber Company.

</body></html>
