<head>
<title>Biography:  Peter Pitsch</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<img src="discussi.gif">
<hr>
<blockquote>
<font face="arial">
<h2>Peter Pitsch </h2>       
<p>

Peter Pitsch is the author of the newly released book on telecommunications and convergence, "The Innovation Age," published jointly by The Progress & Freedom Foundation and The Hudson Institute.
<p> 

Peter Pitsch is an adjunct fellow at The Progress & Freedom Foundation specializing in telecommunications law and economics.  He is also an adjunct fellow at the <a href="http://www.hudson.org/hudson">Hudson Institute</a> as well as an adjunct professor of law at Georgetown University Law Center.  Pitsch has represented telephone, cable, cellular and other interests on a wide variety of communications issues.

<p>
<img src="pitsch.gif" align=right hspace=5 vspace=5>
<p>

Prior to founding his own telecommunications consulting firm in 1989, Pitsch served as chief of staff to chairman Dennis R. Patrick at the Federal Communications Commission from 1987 to 1989.  From 1981 to 1987, he was chief of the FCC's Office of Plans and Policy.

<p>

Pitsch has also worked as a senior attorney at Montgomery Ward Inc., and as an attorney-advisor to commissioner Calvin J. Collier of the Federal Trade Commission.  He has delivered numerous speeches to industry groups and written widely on leading communications issues.

<p>

Pitsch received his J.D. from Georgetown University in 1976 and holds a B.A. in Economics from the University of Chicago.

</font>
</body>
</html>

