<HEAD>
<TITLE>Strossen</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="discussi.gif">
<hr>
<font face="arial"> 
<blockquote>
<h2>NADINE STROSSEN</h2>
<h5>(Photo by Joanne Savio)</h5>
<img src ="stross.gif" align=left>
Nadine Strossen, Professor of Law at New York Law School since 1988, has written, lectured and practiced extensively in the areas of constitutional law, civil liberties and international human rights. In 1991, she was elected President of the American Civil Liberties Union, where she had been National General Counsel since 1986. She is the first woman to serve as ACLU president. In 1991 and 1994, the <i>National Law Journal</i> included Professor Strossen in its triennial special section, ''Profiles in Power: The 100 Most Influential Lawyers in America." She is also listed in <i>Who's Who in America</i>.<p>
Strossen graduated Phi Beta Kappa from Harvard-Radcliffe College (1972) and magna cum laude from Harvard Law School (1975), where she was an editor of the <i>Law Review.</i>  After clerking for the Supreme Court in her home state of Minnesota, she practiced law at private firms in Minneapolis and New York. In 1984, Strossen began her academic career as Supervising Attorney of the Civil Rights Clinic at NYU School of Law. In 1988, she moved to New York Law School, where she teaches constitutional law.<p>
In 1986, Strossen became one of the first three women to receive the U.S. Jaycees' "Ten Outstanding Young Americans" Award; she also was the first American woman to win the Jaycees International's "The Outstanding Young Persons" Award. In 1992, she received Honorary Doctor of Law Degrees from the University of Rhode Island and the University of Vermont, and was given the "Women of Distinction" award by the Women's League for Conservative Judaism, an international organization. In 1994, Strossen received The Media Institute's Freedom of Speech Award.<p>
Strossen has given numerous lectures and speeches all over the U.S. (including at more than 200 college and university campuses since 1991), and in many foreign countries (including Australia, Great Britain, Hong Kong, Israel, Japan, New Zealand, the Philippines, Portugal, South Africa, Spain, Switzerland, and Taiwan). She also has commented frequently on legal issues in the national media, including the following TV shows: <i>CBS Sunday Morning with Charles Kuralt, The Charlie Rose Show, Crier and Company, Crossfire, CNN Prime News, Good Morning America, Larry king Live, The MacNeil-Lehrer NewsHour, The Montel Williams Show, Nightline, Nightwatch, Politically Incorrect, Pozner and Donahue, Sonya Live, This Week with David Brinkley, </i> and the <i>Today Show</i>.<p>
Strossen's writings have been published in many law reviews, magazines, and newspapers (more than 100 publications).  Her article in the 1993 <i>Free Speech Yearbook</i> was awarded the first Richard S. Arnold Prize for Distinguished Scholarship in Freedom of Expression by the Speech Communication Association.<p>
Strossen recently authored a book, <i>Defending Pornography: Free Speech, Sex, and the Fight for Women's Rights</i> (Scribner 1995) (which was named a Notable Book of 1995 by the <i>New York times Book Review</i>); and co-authored a second book, <i>Speaking of race, Speaking of Sex: Hate speech, Civil Rights, and Civil Liberties</i> (N.Y.U. Press 1995) (which was named an Outstanding Book on Human Rights in North America by the Gustavus Myers Center for the Study of Human Rights in North America).<p>
Strossen has served on the boards of directors of many human rights organizations, including: Article XIX, The International Centre Against Censorship; Civil Liberties Trust (Great Britain): Feminists for Free Expression; Human Rights Watch; National Coalition Against Censorship; National Coalition for Public Education and Religious Liberty; and the ACLU's Reproductive Freedom Project.  She is also a member of the Council on Foreign Relations.<p>
Strossen is married to Eli M. Noam, Professor at Columbia University's Graduate School of Business and Director of the Columbia Institute for Tele-Information.  They have residences in Manhattan and in Carmel, New York.
</font>
</BODY>
</HTML>
