<html>
<head>
<title>Biography: Alvin Toffler</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<img src="discussi.gif">
<hr>
<p>
<h2>Alvin Toffler, Ph.D.</h2>
<p>

Alvin Toffler, Ph.D., is one of the world's preeminent futurists.  As
the co-author of War and Anti-War, Dr. Toffler sketches the emerging
economy of the 21st century, presenting a new theory of war and
revealing how changes in today's military parallel almost precisely
the changes now taking place in business.

<p>
<img src="toffler.gif" align=right hspace=10 vspace=10>
<p>

Along with his wife and co-author Heidi Toffler, Dr. Toffler describes
their latest book as a suprising departure from their past work--one
made necessary by the new dangers that confront America and the world
at the edge of the 21st century.  These include tens of thousands of
tactical nuclear weapons in the strife-torn former Soviet Union and
what they call "the civilianization of war," the spread of civilian
products and technologies that can be converted to military use.  In
War and Anti-War, the Tofflers picture the runaway proliferation not
merely of weapons, but of advanced technologies with which to make
them.

<p>

This is not the first time the Tofflers have created controversy in
high places.  In 1988, when the Tofflers drove through the high red
walls fo the Zhangnanhai compound in Beijing for a meeting with Zhao
Ziyang, then China's Communist Party leader and the man behind its
dramatic economic reforms, it was an important moment.  And when Zhao
was later ousted by hardliners during the Tiananmen Square events, it
stirred deep memories for the Tofflers.  Consequently, their
best-selling books, including Future Shock and The Third Wave have
been banned in the People's Republic of China.

<p>

In Powershift, the final book of the trilogy which begins with Future
Shock and The Third Wave, the Tofflers focuses on the power struggles
to come--in business, in politics, and in global affairs--as a new
"system of wealth creation" clashes with today's vested power blocs.
In its central thesis, the Toffles propose that power is shiftein from
its traditional basis in violence and wealth toward a new dependence
on knowledge, and especially "knowledge about knowledge."  This shift
in the nature of power, the Tofflers suggest, is about to touch off
tremendous upheavals in existing power relationships as individuals,
companies and countries scramble for control of the new knowledge
resources.

<p>

In a first step toward the legalization of organized democratic
dissent in the Soviet Union, the Tofflers met with Mikhail Gorbachev
and other Western intellecuals such as Arthur Miller and James Baldwin
to launch the Issyk-kul Forum, the first citizen-initiated
non-communist, non-governmental organization to be permitted in the
country since the 1917 Revolution.  The efforts of the Tofflers and
their colleagues have made huge headlines in Pravda, Izvestia, and
Literaturnaya Gazeta as a milestone in the history of perestroika.
        


<p>
<p>

</body>
</html>

</DOC>
