<html>
<head>
<title>Click Here for Jobs -- PFF</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<center>
<h2>Click Here for Jobs: <br>
Information as a Substitute for Welfare?</h2>
By Tracy Westen
</center>
<p>
<p>

You're in trouble.<p>

You're 23, you had your first child at 15, you dropped out of school in 8th grade and you've been collecting welfare checks on and off ever since.  You've tried a few jobs, but they didn't last.  Your skills are minimal, you don't have a high school diploma, you don't have a good job history.  <p>

And, frankly, you're scared -- scared to ask for a job from people you don't know, scared to be rejected by employers who might look down on you, scared to leave your neighborhood to look for work in unfamiliar places, scared that you might get a job you can't handle, scared that co-workers might ridicule you for not knowing simple things, for not wearing the right clothes, for . . .  almost anything.  <p>

What can you do?<p>

It's 1995, and you're options are limited.  Either you swallow your fear and look for work.  Or you sit at home and wait for your monthly welfare check.  Sometimes sitting and waiting for that check is easier.<p>

<h3>Jobs On-Line</h3>

Now fast forward to 1999.  <p>

The "information superhighway" is well under construction.  You tap the screen of an Info Kiosk at your post office or super-market, or you pick up the "mouse" of an on-line computer, or you grab the remote control to your TV and:<p>

<i>Click:</i>  You pick the "jobs" icon and see of a list of available jobs.  GTE is looking for a "customer service representative."  What is a "customer service representative"?  Does it take a high school diploma? <p>

<i>Click:</i> You see a short video.  A young woman, who looks a little like you, says, "Hi, I applied for this job 6 months ago.  I wasn't sure I could handle it, but it's really OK.  A 'customer service representative' or 'CSR' is someone who answers the phone and helps the company's customers with their service problems.  Now let me show you where I work, let me introduce you to my co-workers, and let me bring over my boss."  <p>

This doesn't seem too bad.  You've always been good on the phone, you like to help people, and this job doesn't take a lot of writing.  But what does it pay, how far away is it, do they have day care for your kids, and what are the people there really like -- friendly or rude?<p>

<i>Click:</i> The "salary" icon says you'll start at $9.50 an hour, will get a raise to $14.00 an hour in 6 months and will work from 4 to 11 p.m.  <i>Click:</i> The "benefits" icon says they have day care.  <i>Click:</i> The "co-workers" icon lets you see videos of some of the other CSRs who work there (they look OK, maybe even nice). <i>Click:</i> You watch a sample interview.  You might do OK, it doesn't look too fancy, your clothes seem to be acceptable for this job. <i>Click:</i> You examine a bus route to GTE's offices -- it looks pretty convenient. <i>Click:</i> A voice comes on the line and asks if you would like a job interview tomorrow?  You hesitate, then, "Sure, I'll be there at 11:00 a.m."    <p>

And a few years later, who knows, perhaps the job interview will be conducted by desk top video conferencing.  Instead of arranging an appointment, a GTE employee's picture appears in the upper left hand corner of the screen.  "Hi," he says, are you interested in being a customer service representative?  Let me tell you about the job."  You see a picture of yourself at the upper right hand corner of the screen.  You talk for a few minutes, he likes what you say, you've got the job.  You start next week. <p>

Fanciful?  Not at all.  The technology to make this scenario a reality is being designed and put in place today.  Interactive multimedia, video on demand, two-way desk top video conferencing -- all these are now being planned, and even installed in their earliest stages, for video games, home shopping, movies on demand, even lotteries. <p>

But will these technologies be available to help us solve our social problems?  Consider other plausible scenarios.<p>

<h3>Health Care</h3>

You're 17 and pregnant.  You go to the nearest terminal and choose the "Healthy Babies" icon.<p>

<i>Click:</i> You see a list of choices -- What You Should Eat, Alcohol Advice, Drug Dangers, Cigarette Warnings , Exercise Options, Vitamins, Where to Get Free Medical Care, Regular and Emergency Room Services, AIDS Prevention, Family Planning, Caring for Your Child in the First Six Months.<p>

<i>Click:</i>   A video appears of another 17-year-old pregnant woman.  She says,  "I got pregnant when I was 16, but I found this local clinic, and they helped me have a healthy baby (scenes of the clinic are shown on the video).  If you want to see the most important things I learned to help take care of myself and my child, then click the buttons below."  A menu appears.  <i>Click</i>  "Alcohol" and you learn about fetal alcohol syndrome.   <i>Click</i> "Vitamins" and you learn about calcium and bone development. <i>Click</i> "Neighbors" and you see the pictures of other pregnant women, neighbors in  your area who have agreed to chat with you by video conference -- to share what they've learned, to get together and support each other, just to talk.   <i>Click </i>one of the "Neighbors" pictures, and you find yourself talking on a video screen with someone a lot like you -- about babies, diet, friends, where to get support.<p>

<h3>Politics</h3>

You're a father, and your kids have to walk to school past drug dealers transacting business in the open.  You're scared for their safety, and scared they'll be attracted to drugs.  The cops are never there, or they never do anything about the drug dealers. You pick up the remote control to the TV set.<p>

<i>Click:</i> You select "Drug Prevention Hotline" under Local Government.  You report the location of the drug transactions to the police. <i>Click:</i> The screen tells you the name of your City Council Member, and you dial his office.  Why isn't he doing anything about your child's safety?  When is he up for reelection?  <i>Click:</i> You check the videotaped statement by his opponent in the upcoming election on drug prevention.  His opponent is calling for more police on the streets.  Would that work?  You think it might.<p>

<i>Click:</i> You review TV, radio and newspaper stories on the drug problem. You learn that other communities are having similar problems, but they're organizing and putting pressure on their city councils to get action. <i>Click:</i> You check the video bulletin boards under "drugs" and find out other neighbors are complaining about drug sales on the streets, too.  <i>Click:</i> You discover there's a local organizing meeting on drugs, and you attend.  <i>Click:</i> Your group asks you to testify by video conference from your home, before a City Council hearing, and you explain the dangers of drug deals in your neighborhood.  You even show a homemade videotape of drug dealers making sales --and the video is seen by the City Council and everyone else watching in your community.<p>

<h3>Communications Technology and Social Reform</h3>

Consider the implications of these scenarios:  A welfare recipient is motivated to find a job, using on-line information to overcome her fear at reaching out and trying something new.  A pregnant teen-ager finds medical and psychological support from doctors and neighbors, helping her to have a healthy baby.  A father helps organize his community to fight drugs in his neighborhood. <p>

Are these scenarios simplistic?  In part, yes.  It may take more than information to help people find jobs in communities where jobs do not exist.  Some drug abusers may be too far gone to help themselves and may need more direct forms of intervention.  Community organizing is not always easy -- neighbors are sometimes fearful, sometimes apathetic.<p>

But these scenarios also have considerable power and truth as well.  And they all share an important link -- that access to modern communications technologies can help some individuals help themselves.   The need for direct welfare payments is lessened.  Health care is improved.  Citizens are empowered to help themselves. And the government saves money by investing in communications infrastructure.  <p>

We do not know, of course, what percentage of welfare recipients would improve their levels of employment, health, education and political participation if given access to easy, inexpensive, modern communications technologies. But what is important is that we find out.  We have before us the opportunity to undertake one of the most dramatic social experiments in generations: to discover whether, and to what extent, information can begin to substitute for direct welfare grants.<p>

The need for such experimentation is compelling.  Without it, we risk exacerbating the plight of the "information underclass,"  many of whom already lack even the most basic element of modern information technology, the telephone.  <p>

Seven percent of American households are still without telephone service, most of that 7 percent accounted for by low income-minorities.  In some low-income communities telephone penetration is 66.4 percent.  And as the sophistication of technology increases, so does the information gap.  The United States Census found that only 15 percent of families earning an annual income of $20,000 or less had a computer at home compared to 74 percent of households with incomes of $75,000 or more. <p>

It is critical that we use technological advances to empower citizens, instead of allowing it to drive deeper wedges between social and economic groups and  further entrench the cycles of poverty.  Rampant poverty among our citizens is among the most pressing social problems our nation faces.  In the home of the United States Capitol, the District of Columbia, nearly a third of its 600,000 residents are on some form of public assistance, and the number of jobs available has dropped by 70,000 over the last three years.  Such devastation is not without its consequences. The facts are chilling:  Washington, D.C., jails more young black men every year than it graduates from high school. Whatever our politics, we can ill afford to ignore their plight.  Rapidly growing numbers of citizens requiring public assistance is a devastating drain on our collective financial, social and cultural resources.<p>

Providing homeless people with voice mail accounts is an example of how information technology can allow people to help themselves.  Giving the homeless access to a phone number with their own voice message attached gives them a home base to communicate with potential employers or landlords, as well as friends and family.  Such a program is run by Central Neighborhood house, a Toronto community agency.  After five months of participation, 30 people were surveyed about voice mail's effects: of the 30, five were able to find jobs and five to find housing.  Several others were awaiting job interviews and making housing arrangements.  <p>

In Los Angeles, an experiment is underway which will test the usefulness of home delivery of pertinent information to inner city residents. Connect LA, a project of the non-profit Center for Governmental Studies, in planned partnership with local government, community organizations and industry groups, will construct and operate an experimental new interactive network of video, voice and textual information to selected low income homes and schools in Los Angeles.  The project will determine whether, and to what extent, communities will benefit from on-demand multimedia information regarding employment, health care, education, political participation and cultural affairs. <p>

Connect LA will be carefully monitored and analyzed to determine whether access to such information and services is instrumental in helping families raise their levels of income, health and education; improve overall community economic conditions; and, spur more active community participation and pride.  Favorable results might encourage us to make interactive multimedia technologies available more widely and illustrate the value in overcoming the problems of the "information poor" as we enter the coming century.<p>

We must aggressively support this wave of experimentation and create an environment in which creativity will flourish.  Partnerships among public, private, and non-profit entities can produce a wide array of prototypes: social laboratories in which to conduct experiments in improved communication.  Encouraging the proliferation of such prototypes will allow the greatest variety of information, services, training and incentives to be provided, therefore alerting decision makers to which combinations work best for specific populations.  <p>

To be sure, there will still be instances in which people will need money, temporary housing or substance abuse treatment.  But now it seems in our power to give the others something of more enduring value:  the power to improve their own circumstances.  This kind of assistance can change lives and benefit society as a whole.<p>

It is time for government to realize what the business and non-profit world have already acknowledged:  that there is a world of advantage, both financial and social, to be gained from encouraging developments in communications.  We all have an enormous stake in getting people off welfare, beyond saving tax dollars.  More significantly, information technology can help renew our political culture and empower citizens to help themselves. <p>

 Providing the information poor with access to the technological vocabulary necessary to participate in the new information economies makes good sense, as it makes for visionary public policy.  But in the fulfillment of this potential, we must be more than sensible.  We must be aggressive, creative and explosive.  We must roar into the next century with a ferocious commitment to innovation, equality and democracy which befits the unprecedented opportunity which has been presented us.<p>

<p>
Tracy Westen is president of the Center for Governmental Studies.<p>

[ <a href="/pff/amciv/ac-july/i-ac0795.html>July Index</a> ]
<p>
