<html>
<head>
<title>CPS:  The Key to Effective Compassion -- PFF</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<center>
<h2>CPS:  The Key to Effective Compassion</h2>
<p>
By Marvin Olasky
</center>
<p>
<p>
Many Americans know the meaning of the letters CPR.  They know that when a heart has 
stopped beating, cardiopulmonary resuscitation can restore normal breathing.  Dictionary 
definitions of the term list its three elements: heart massage by the exertion of pressure, clearance 
of air passages to the lungs, and the use of appropriate medications, when available.
<p>
Many Americans also know that the heart of our country's compassion toward the poor is 
ailing.  Citizens tired of increased governmental welfare spending are demanding cutbacks.  
Tales of extravagant spending by the former head of the United Way increased cynicism about 
philanthropic management.   Average household contributions to social welfare charities are 
dropping.
<p>
We know that emergency treatment to resuscitate charity is needed, but we have not 
received training in how to render effective compassion.  For too long we have been told to prove 
our sincerity by writing checks or passing legislation, without too much thought about 
consequences.  Yet, when it comes to changing lives, it's not just the thought that counts.  When 
people see that money is wasted, the springs of charity dry up and more lives are destroyed.
<p>
The good news is that we know how to do better, if we stop relying on either 
governmental or philanthropic bureaucracies to do the work for us.  In the 1890s, volunteers in 
New York (United Hebrew Charities), New Orleans (Charity Organizing Society), and hundreds 
of new neighborhoods helped millions of Americans to escape poverty.   In the 1990s, human-
scale charities throughout the United States -- from Clean and Sober Streets in Washington, D.C. 
to CityTeam in San Jose, California -- are having similar success.
<p>
Past and present show that there are three keys to effective compassion: It should be 
<b>challenging</b>, it should be <b>personal</b>, it should be <b>spiritual</b> -- CPS for short.  (Those three letters 
also begin the three syllables of the word "com-pas-sion.")  Just as CPR can save individual 
lives, so CPS training can help Americans to be discerning in their commitment of time and 
money. 
<p>
<h3>Challenge</h3>
<p>
Think of the first element of CPR: Heart massage by the exertion of pressure.  A person 
using CPR does not press down faintly on the chest of a person close to death.  The first element 
in CPS is <b>challenge</b>, and it is important here also that the push be hard.
<p>
A century ago homeless shelters were not enablers that maintained alcoholics and addicts 
in their lifestyles and asked little or nothing of them.  When an able-bodied man came to a 
homeless shelter, he often was asked to chop wood for two hours in return for food and shelter; 
in that way he could provide part of his own support and also help those unable to chop wood.   
Women typically would do their part in sewing rooms.
<p>
Those who worked hard through this initial challenge would be helped to find jobs.  
Those who could work but refused to were not entitled to aid.  The work test, along with teaching 
good habits and keeping away those who did not really need help, also enabled charities to teach 
the lesson that those who were being helped could help others.
<p>
Today,  we need to stop talking about "the poor" in abstraction and start distinguishing 
once again between those willing to struggle and those just looking for an enabler: Entry-level 
jobs are available in every major American city, and employees who prove their reliability do not 
stay at the entryway for long. Americans should support programs that emphasize work, not 
make-work or excuses.
<p>
Alcoholics, addicts, and drifters must be challenged to change their lifestyles. Americans 
should support programs that emphasize challenge, not handouts that perpetuate self-destructive 
behavior.  
<p>
<h3>Personal</h3>
<p>
Consider the second element of CPR: Clearance of air passages to the lungs. An intense 
image may come to mind: The volunteer performing mouth-to-mouth resuscitation, occasionally 
stopping for a second to half-mutter, half-pray, "Breathe... Breathe."
<p>
Effective compassion needs a level of personal involvement almost as great.   The second 
letter of CPS stands for <b>personal</b>:  In many poverty-fighting situations lives  and values also 
have to be resuscitated, and people learn more from an individual they respect (and perhaps love) 
than from a textbook.
<p>
A century ago, charity volunteers usually were not  assigned to massive food-dispensing 
tasks, but were given the narrow but deep responsibility of making a difference in one life over 
several years.   A typical magazine story revealed how one "demoralized" woman was helped: 
"for months she was worked with, now through kindness, again through discipline, until finally 
she began to show a desire to help herself."  For months: Breathe! Breathe!
<p>
Today, we cannot buy the level of personal involvement that is needed to be next to an 
addict as he is going through withdrawal pains, or next to an unmarried, pregnant teenager who is 
going through the pain of abandonment by a boyfriend amidst crisis.  The costs of placing 
professionals in each of those situations would bankrupt governments.
<p>
But at anti-addiction organizations that banish bureaucracy, a person who has recently 
gone through detox himself, and wants to help one other person do the same, is by an addict's 
bedside.  In programs run by crisis pregnancy centers around the country, a married couple with 
compassion for a pregnant teenager is giving her a room in their home and a place at their dinner 
table. Successful experiences like that suggest some other strategies to adopt: Mentoring and 
tutoring projects that bond volunteers and the needy work best.   Americans should support 
programs that emphasize one-to-one approaches. 
<p>
Bonds that already exist, even if torn, should not be overlooked.  Americans should 
support programs that attempt to reunite aid-seekers with families and  friends.  As history shows 
and Psalm 66 states, "God sets the lonely in families." 
<p>
<h3>Spiritual</h3>
<p>
The third element of CPR is use of appropriate medications.  The idea is to take what is 
of proven effectiveness and apply it immediately.  No one doing CPR goes to a medicine cabinet 
and tries whatever the snake-oil salesman of the week has peddled.
<p>
The third letter in CPS stands for <b>spiritual</b>, and there's a strong reason for that:  "True 
philanthropy must take into account spiritual as well as physical needs," poverty-fighters a 
century ago noted, and the same is true today.  Successful anti-poverty work, past and present, 
has given the poor self-esteem not by offering easy, feel-good praise, but by reminding them that 
a wonderful God made them in his image and has a purpose for their lives.
<p>
The federal War on Poverty in the 1960s, however, was a trip to the medicine cabinet.  
Religious teaching, instead of being embraced by bureaucrats at least as a way of helping 
roaming individuals to think about their purpose in life, was excluded by judicial decree and 
administrative design.  Instead, a variety of experimental social programs came in, none of which 
touched the pessimistic core values of the welfare mentality.
<p>
 Anti-drug programs without a spiritual base, for example, have success rates in the single 
digits.  Such programs contrast with those that provide religious medication and do not merely 
cover up wounds.  Victory Fellowship is one example:  Freddie Garcia through God's grace beat 
heroin addiction; he then opened a combination church and half-way house in San Antonio; the 
program now has spread to 60 churches in Texas and New Mexico, with a 60% success rate in 
beating addiction, yet the Texas Drug and Alcohol Commission asked Reverend Garcia to stop 
referring to his ministry as "drug rehabilitation" because it did not conform to the usual 
standards.
<p>
In a pluralistic society, of course, there are many different beliefs, but that is not a 
problem as long as all have equal opportunity to develop and fund programs. Let's let  Christians, 
Jews, Moslems, Buddhists, and others compete in doing good, and over time we will see who is 
the most successful -- and if atheistic groups develop programs, let them try also.
<p>
If we focus not on weaknesses but on strengths,  the heart of American compassion can 
be saved.  The government of Washington, D.C., has a financial crisis, but volunteer-based 
programs that are enormously effective cost very little: My favorites so far are Clean and Sober 
Streets, where ex-alcoholics and ex-addicts help those still in captivity; the Gospel Mission, 
which fights homelessness by offering true hope; the Capitol Hill Crisis Pregnancy Center, 
where teenage moms and their children, born and unborn, are cared for; and Children of Mine, an 
after-school program in one of the city's poorest sections, Anacostia, run by a mature, crusty 
woman, Hannah Hawkins.
<p>
Other groups are making a difference all across the country:  One of my favorite Texans 
is Kathy Dudley, a young woman who began Voice of Hope in Dallas by walking down an inner 
city street with a soccer ball under her arm and inviting children to play, learn about God through 
Bible studies, and work at rehabbing deteriorated homes in their neighborhood.  During the past 
decade, crime rates among the boys she works with and pregnancy rates among the girls are 
much lower than in the surrounding community.
<p>
The bottom line is not money, since many of these effective programs cost far less than 
the failed but still fund-eating approaches of the Great Society.  The line that truly threatens 
American charity is a straight horizontal line, similar to that visible on the heart monitor when 
CPR fails.
<p>
<h3>Government vs. Private Charity</h3>
<p>
We need to change our methods of fighting poverty, but we need to be clear about the 
reasons for change.  Governmental welfare programs should be fought not because they are too 
expensive -- although, clearly, much money is wasted -- but because they are inevitably too 
stingy in what is truly important: treating people as human beings made in God's image, not as 
animals to be fed and caged.
<p>
Private charities can do a better job than government, but only if they practice CPS.  Here 
is where one word common in the 19th century, "discernment," needs to be revived.  New 
Orleans poverty-fighters declared in 1899 that, "Intelligent giving and intelligent withholding are 
alike true charity."  They gave an example: "If drink has made a man poor, money will feed not 
him, but his drunkenness."
<p>
Poverty-fighters a century ago trained volunteers to leave behind "a conventional attitude 
toward the poor, seeing them through the comfortable haze of our own intentions."  Bad charity 
that handed money to those who did not work could demoralize those who did.  Bad charity 
could create uncertainty among givers as to how their contributions would be used, and thus lead 
to less giving over the long term:  It was important to "reform those mild, well-meaning, tender-
hearted, sweet-voiced criminals who insist upon indulging in indiscriminate charity."
<p>
When charity is challenging, personal, and spiritual,  then anti-poverty work can be 
effective.  The crisis of the modern welfare state is a crisis of government, but it is more than 
that.  Too many private charities dispense aid indiscriminately and thus provide, instead of points 
of light, alternative shades of darkness.  A century-old question -- Does any given "scheme of 
help... make great demands on men to give themselves to their brethren?" -- is still the right one 
to ask.
<p>
Some will have more time to give; some will have more dollars; but everyone can do 
something that will help and not hurt.  We need to learn how to apply CPS, and we need to 
become involved personally.  Involvement can vary in intensity all the way from tutoring a child 
for one hour a week to adopting a child, and  from counseling a young, unmarried pregnant 
woman to giving her a room in your home.  But everyone can do something.
<p>
Each of us should take a triple pledge based on CPS:  Com-pas-sion that is challenging, 
personal, and spiritual.  First, we should examine carefully the principles and practices of 
government programs or private charities that we might consider supporting.  Second, we should 
not support governmental programs or private charities that do not contain CPS elements.  Third, 
we should commit our time and money to those that do.
<p>
<p>
Marvin Olaksy is a senior fellow at PFF. His most recent book is "The Tragedy of American Compassion."
<p>
[ <a href="/pff/amciv/ac-july/i-ac0795.html">July Index</a> ]
<p>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
</html>
