<html>
<head>
<title>Who Lost Japan? Mickey Kantor.  An Interview with Alvin Toffler -- PFF</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<h2>Who Lost Japan? Mickey Kantor.<br>
An Interview with Alvin Toffler</h2>
<p>
<Font Size="-1">American Civilization discusses with Alvin Toffler, co-author of "Creating a New 
Civilization: The Politics of the Third Wave," whether or not he is a Marxist, the decimation 
of middle management, the future of representative government and Japan bashing.</font>
<p>
<p>
<B>AmCiv:</B> Information Age or Knowledge Age are often used as synonyms for Third Wave. Isnt 
there a clear difference between knowledge and information, and with so much information out 
there, wont people need others to filter information, be it an editor or "electronic agent?"
<p>
<B>Toffler:</B>  Raw data is just that, raw.  It frequently isn't very useful, even if it's accurate, which it 
frequently isn't, particularly in political discourse, where it's been massaged by various parties for 
their own benefit, or selected in particular ways.
<p>
I think well need both electronic agents and editors.  Electronic agents to do a kind of first 
cut, and then humans to apply more idiosyncratic, more customized, more interesting filters to the 
material, and then to help synthesize.
<p>
The synthesis of data into information, and from information into something that might be 
called knowledge, is absolutely the critical function.  The more information there is floating around, 
the more we drown without that function.
<p>
In organizations with traditional bureaucracies, that synthesizing and selecting function 
was served or carried out by the middle management, collecting information from several 
departments, synthesizing it, and then either moving it up the hierarchy or sitting on it and refusing 
to send it up.
<p>
What has happened is the introduction of computer technology into business; it has wiped 
out large swatches of the middle management, because it's no longer necessary.  But what makes it 
possible to do away with all those intermediaries are information systems that permit the individual 
at the bottom of the hierarchy to cross into other departments and other cubby holes containing 
information almost at will.
<p>
In every large scale bureaucracy two assumptions were made, one publicly and oone 
tacitly.
<p>
The explicit assumption was that the people on top, because they were getting more 
synthesized information, could see the whole picture, whereas the people on the bottom could only 
know what was in their department. Therefore, the people on top not only had power to make larger 
decisions, but they had the information appropriate to that power.  That is what we all heard.
<p>
What we never heard was that in the very act of designing the organization, of sketching a 
table of organization, there was implicit in that the assumption that the people on top knew enough 
to determine what the people down below needed to know.
<p>
When they set up an organizational frame that separated marketing from engineering, they 
were implying that the people in marketing don't need to know what the engineers are doing and 
vice versa.  So the implicit rule was that we on top know better than the people down below what it 
is they need to do and what they need to know.
<p>
The discussion of "empowerment" today in big business and large scale enterprise and in 
government bureaucracies to the degree that you even hear that, is a result of the fact that the people 
on top do not know and cannot know what the people down below need to know, because the rate 
of change is too rapid, and the complexity is too great.
<p>
The result is, that if you want to get any job done, you have got to let the people down 
below decide to what information that they will have access.  Otherwise they can't do it.  When we 
talk about empowerment, this is not a matter of noblesse oblige.  This is, you can't get the job done 
without it.  That is the democratization in a certain sense of the workplace.
<p>
I believe there's a lost power and authority at the top in all of our institutions.  There is an 
enhanced empowerment of individuals down below, who are also demanding more and more 
freedom to access information and to utilize it.
<p>
Now is that all good?  Not necessarily. It also means that the neo-Nazis and other crazies 
have access to very dangerous information.  Can you have an absolutely open information 
system?  No, we could not survive.  At the same token, you want to have a maximum open 
information system.  But you have to understand that there are risks entailed in that.
<p>
<B>AmCiv:</B> You have written that we're on the edge of a great democratic leap forward.  What does 
this portend for the government structure?
<p>
<B>Toffler: </B> I do not argue that we are going to have a great leap forward in democracy.  I argue that 
our current forms, our current concept of democracy are themselves reflections of a mass industrial 
society.  That mass democracy is the political expression of mass production, mass consumption, 
mass media, mass education, mass everything else.
<p>
It was appropriate that at the dawn of the machine age, we would create a political 
structure based on concepts like checks and balances, that we would create the party structures 
which were almost conceived of as machines and called machines, public machines.  That the 
function of the parties was to aggregate votes, and thereby transform an individual, transform a 
candidate into an electoral machine by the amassing of larger and larger numbers of votes.
<p>
All of that presupposed or went hand in hand in the less democratic countries with mass 
movements, the Nazis, Communism, Russia.  But it was the massness of the political structure that 
reflected the massness of other aspects of life.
<p>
Now, we're moving into a period of de-massification.  One of the implications of our 
theory of chain of history and one of the reasons we use the metaphor of waves of change, which 
makes what we say considerably different than a lot of social analysts, is that you can have more 
than one wave of change rolling at the same time.  So you can see certain processes still massified 
in the society, while other tendencies are gaining force, demassifying in the society.
<p>
<B>AmCiv:</B> Do you think that we are stuck with a Second Wave elite that fundamentally does not get 
what is happening in the world?
<p>	
<B>Toffler:</B> It doesn't matter.  Elites that don't get what is happening in the world do not survive.
<p>
New elites are emerging.  You'll find them, as you might expect me to say, in Silicon 
Valley and in Austin, Texas, and around Washington, D.C., and so forth and so on. These are new 
kinds, frequently based on new industry, but it may not even be just business; it can be in civil 
society and elsewhere.
<p>
We think that what happens is those sort of second wave structures, the elites that govern 
the second wave structures, either they get with the program or they get brushed away. The 
question is how civilly that occurs.  It can happen in a very unpleasant way.
<p>
<B>AmCiv: </B> With all of this decision off-loading, is there a role for any middle-management?  Im 
specifically thinking about representative government.
<p>
<B>Toffler:</B>  I believe -- and we have written and we have been radically misinterpreted again, 
primarily by Ross Perot.  He introduced the word electronic town hall and shook everybody with 
the silliness.
<p>
We do not believe in a sort of single ballot electronic town hall.  You make a decision and 
push the button and that's it. We believe that you need a representative layer, between that.  
Between the popular participation, electronically or otherwise, and the decision.  So we favor 
representative government.  However, there are ways to combine those in ways that we do not now 
do.
<p>
<B>AmCiv: </B> Do you think it should be created by modifying the Constitution?
<p>
<B>Toffler:</B>  I think it's inevitable that the Constitution will be modified.  The only question is whether 
that will be done in a reasonable and thoughtful way or as a result of some crisis.
<p>
Whether that happens in 10 years or 20 years, who knows.  I don't know.  But it seems to 
me that it is all in our interest to get as wide a civilized discussion going in the United States about 
what does the 21st century government require.  What do we as a people who want democracy 
mean by democracy in a demassified society, not just a society made up of mass movements.
<p>
It seems to me the political problem faced by politicians is to lace together thousands of 
different groupings with thousands of different interests from smoking bans, to abortion, to taxes, 
nukes, no nukes, do you commit genetic foods into the marketplace or don't you.  There are 
thousands and thousands of issues.  People line up multi-dimensional on all of these multiple 
spectra.
<p>
Moreover, most of these groups don't last more than 10 minutes.  They are constantly 
dying and regenerating.  So you have a very fluxing political field in which the old rules no longer 
apply.
<p>
The reality here is that nobody today will represent.  Minorities do not feel represented.  
Majorities don't feel represented.  The Christian Coalition doesn't feel adequately represented.  I can 
tell you that people I know who are multi-zillionaires feel that they are not represented.  So there is 
a widespread, deep, deep feeling in the country that the system doesn't match the assumptions on 
which we've all been taught to take for granted.
<p>
<B>AmCiv:</B> If politicians can no longer count on stable coalitions of interests, maybe we should try to 
strengthen representative government, where people no longer run on the issues but on how well 
theyd make decisions.
<p>
<B>Toffler:</B>  In fact, I don't think that that is completely ignored by the electorate even now.  When 
they vote for somebody and we get into personality and character, that is one of the issues that 
people are thinking about.  Is this a guy who is going to be a menace in the case of war?  Is this a 
guy who can handle tough decisions?  Is this a guy who is too slightly or too light-weight?  And so 
forth and so on.  So I think that it does play somewhat.  But the question you raise I think is a really 
good one.
<p>
<B>AmCiv:</B>  Let me ask you a question about your intellectual processes. <i>The New Yorker</i> and others 
have called you a Marxist.  Certainly youve come to different conclusions from Marx, but you 
both seem to draw on Hegels dialecticalism.
<p>
<B>Toffler:</B> Heidi and I were Marxists, but the notion that we're still Marxists is a funny kind of Marx. 
 The supra structure is more important than the base.  It's actually more Hegelian than it is Marxist. 
 But I think that they weren't up to making distinctions.
<p>
Look, Marx was no dummy.  Marx was a very smart guy. He taught that things are 
interconnected, that technology is important for change and has social consequences.
<p>
More important, in my own intellectual thought, Marxism was a model.  It is a model.  
That is what is valuable.  Not whether the model was right or wrong, but that there is such a thing, 
that there are such things as models.
<p>
Now, I could then say that model is wrong.  I can either try to correct the model or I can 
dump the model entirely and create another model.  But the early life insight that there's such a 
thing as a way to organize masses and masses of information into some kind of coherent model was 
very powerful for us. Lots of thinkers and institutions put out models.
<p>
Id go to school and be showered with facts which didn't make a lot of sense.  You had a 
chronology of history.  You had individual bits and pieces.  Suddenly, I found a bunch of people 
who could put those bits and pieces together into pattern.  That was wow, came as a great 
awakening.  As I say, it could have been some other model, but that was one of them.
<p>
If you read our books carefully, you will see that there are models in these books.  They 
are not explicit.  We never start the way an academic would and say here is the way the model 
works.  But in fact, we couldn't synthesize the stuff that we do without some kind of models.  I 
believe that we have various different models and that they are basically compatible with one 
another.
<p>
There would be no way for me to make sense of the morning newspaper if I didn't have 
some kind of framework.  Not all of it.  The best news articles are the ones that don't fit the model.  
They are the ones that force you to think.
<p>
We have got a research file of more than 3,000 categories.  Periodically something appears 
for which we simply don't have a file.  That is the best.  That just gets put on my desk.  It lives in 
my tray for months at a time.
<p>
<B>AmCiv:</B> You are talking about those things that don't fit.  They ground you as to why that model 
does or does not reflect reality.
<p>
<B>Toffler:</B> They either tell you that you have got to extend the model in some direction that you 
haven't attempted before, or they say you have got to rethink some chunk of it.  Maybe some part of 
it doesn't really operate that way and you've got to leave room, in which case we do.
<p>
I think we leave room for chance.  We are not historical determinists.  But these are the 
patterns that seem to be emerging, but that can be derailed.  This whole place could go up in smoke 
tomorrow.  Who knows?  The world is a very chancy place.
<p>
<B>AmCiv:</B>  The "Big Change" were going through seems capable of causing tremendous 
dislocations. It is, after all, changing our whole fabric of life. Are you worried about civil disorder?
<p>
<B>Toffler:</B>  Look at the rest of the world, see how instantaneously the Soviet system simply came 
apart.  Now we're better off because were are more decentralized.  But we're not immune. I believe 
that the militias are incipient separatist movements. I think that if Western Europe can have 
Basques and Corsicans blowing up police stations and so forth and so on, that we may be just 
moving into that cycle.
<p>
I am not vaguely one sided or pessimistic, but I certainly am not blindly optimistic.  I 
think we are moving into a period in which there is a lot of danger and risk.
<p>
<B>AmCiv:</B>  What about international affairs?  What concerns you there? 
<p>
<B>Toffler:</B> Japan bashing.  It overlooks the degree to which the Japanese economy and the American 
economy are in fact already integrated. This assumption that there's a national line and a need to 
balance some accounting is nuts.  It is obsessively focused on trade in response to a very narrow 
special interest, which overlooks the larger danger of destruction of the Asian Pacific economy.  
Not to mention the possibility of war.
<p>
I think that at the end of World War II, there was some very unpleasant talk about how we 
lost China.  I guess you know history in this period.  But in five years, 10 years, I expect to be 
hearing who lost Asia.  The answer would be Micky Kantor.
<p>
<B>AmCiv:</B> Bill Clinton.
<p>
<B>Toffler:</B>  What it seems to me they are doing is pushing Japan to pulling out of here and putting all 
their investment in Southeast Asia, which then becomes the Greater East Asian co-prosperity 
sphere. We are sitting there with a time bomb ticking away in China.  If we want to maintain any 
stability in the Asian Pacific region, the basis of that stability lies in Japan.
<p>
<p>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
