<html>
<head>
<title>Privatize the Postal Service -- PFF</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<center>
<h2>Privatize the Postal Service</h2>
<p>
By Thomas M. Lenard
</center>
<p>
<p>
<p>
The U.S. Postal Service  provides a traditional industrial age service -- the delivery of messages in hard-copy form -- which is being challenged by a variety of new information age communications alternatives.  These alternatives already have eroded the Postal Service's share of the communications market, and will continue to do so in the years ahead.
<p>
The erosion of the Postal Service's core business leaves customers contending with rising rates and inadequate services.  This situation will only degenerate as new technologies eat into the Postal Service's markets and undermine its financial viability.
<p>
The Postal Service's status as a government-owned monopoly makes it virtually impossible for either the Service or its customers to adapt to rapidly changing technology.  It is therefore imperative that we seek to replace the way America's postal services are structured.
<p>
<h3>Competition to the Postal Service</h3>
<p>
As a government-owned enterprise protected from competition in the major markets in which it operates, the Postal Service occupies a unique place in the American economy.  The Private Express Statutes give the Postal Service a monopoly over the carriage of "letter mail," which covers all first-class and most third-class mail.  Together, these two classes comprise over 80 percent of the Postal Service's business.
<p>
The principal argument against permitting competition in the delivery of mail is that the Postal Service is a natural monopoly, able to provide mail services at a lower cost than if it shared the market with other firms. Yet we know that private firms can effectively compete with the Postal Service, when permitted.  United Parcel Service and FedEx are well known success stories.  The fact that the Postal Service faces as much competition as it does, both in terms of service quality and price, from a great variety of sources, in spite of its statutory monopoly, is indicative of the high costs of maintaining the status quo.
<p>
<h3>Private Mail Delivery Firms</h3>
<p>
While it is clear that large firms such as UPS and FedEx are strong competitors, there is evidence of the viability of other technologies.  There is a small, private mail carrier industry that operates today, subject to the constraints of the letter-mail monopoly.  These private carriers deliver unaddressed advertising mail and periodicals that may be addressed.
<p>
All Postal Service mail is required to carry a written address, even if it is delivered to all addresses in an area. Advertising circulars that are delivered to most or all of the addresses in an area (i.e., are not selectively delivered) are considered unaddressed and therefore may legally be delivered by private firms.  Periodicals -- second-class mail -- and most books and catalogues also fall outside the definition of "letter mail" and may be privately delivered.
<p>
The small firms that make up the private mail delivery industry have been offering a variety of services in connection with the basic delivery service, many of which are not offered by the Postal Service.  For example, private carriers offer selective coverage based on various demographic characteristics; guaranteed delivery on a specific day; coordination with printers; and, Sunday and holiday delivery service.
<p>
None of these services is offered by the Postal Service. These are small mom-and-pop operations.  To the extent that economies of scale and scope are important in this market, the Postal Service should enjoy advantages that are unavailable to the private carriers -- especially the small firms that operate in this market.  The fact that they can compete suggests either higher costs or mispricing on the part of the Postal Service.
<p>
In recent years the private sector delivery service has grown dramatically. For example, private delivery services are now offered by more than 38 percent of the daily newspapers; 
five years after Publishers Express was founded in 1989 by Time Inc., it delivered about 60 million magazines and catalogues and about six million "ride-alongs"; and, about 70 percent of the nations 100 million households are now covered by private mail delivery.
<p>
Nevertheless, the extent to which private delivery can penetrate the market is obviously limited -- by the letter monopoly and by the letter box restrictions.
<p>
<h3>Competition From Electronic Transmission</h3>
<p>
In the long run, the Postal Service is probably more vulnerable to competition from electronic forms of transmission, which can completely bypass the existing legal restrictions. This electronic competition has been foreseen for years and is not new, but its intensity is growing.  There are, for example, now about 9 million installed fax machines and increasing use of computer-generated fax transmissions.
<p>
The market for on-line services is expanding as well, with companies like Prodigy, CompuServe and America On-line providing home shopping, banking, electronic mail and a variety of interactive information services.
<p>
There is little the Postal Service can do to forestall these new technologies. It is important that the Postal Service have the ability to respond and adapt to new circumstances, which it is unable to do operating as a rate-regulated statutory monopoly.  Otherwise, the Service will represent an increasing financial burden on those of its customers who have limited alternatives and on the taxpayer.
<p>
<h3>Redesigning the Postal Service</h3>
<p>
Given the interests of current stakeholders, how can we achieve a real redesign of the system?  The most obvious group with a stake in the current system is postal labor, but there are others as well, including the Postal Service's competitors, and individuals and businesses in high-cost service areas who fear they will be disadvantaged by a more competitive system.
<p>
As a nation, we put a high premium on the ability to choose.  This is apparent in the in the changes taking place in the telecommunications industries, where we have facilitated choice in long-distance service, and are moving in that direction in local and cable TV.
<p>
A plan to redesign the Postal Service should:  (1) provide the flexibility for the Postal Service to survive and for mailers to have a sufficient array of service alternatives and (2) avoid the service disruptions and taxpayer bailout that are likely if nothing is done.  A plan that meets these objectives should be based on the following premises:
<p>
<ul>
<li>The government's monopoly over the carriage and delivery of mail should be abolished.  There is no benefit to customers in being forced to rely on a high-cost provider of service, and the monopoly deprives mailers of needed alternatives and the USPS itself of the freedom and flexibility it needs to adapt to the nation's changing mail service and communications needs.
<li>The Postal Service should be able to compete in new markets on a level playing field, enjoying no explicit or implicit advantages relative to its private competitors.
<li>Whatever the exact nature of the organization, this implies a new Postal Service should have transferable ownership shares, because this type of organization promotes efficiency.
</ul>
 <p>
We know what a more efficient Postal Service would look like, but we don't have much experience concerning how to get there.  One way to approach the problem would be to undertake the transformation in stages, rather than all at once.  In a transition to a new system, we need to take account of the interests of individuals that made investment and other decisions under the assumption that the current rules of the game would continue, including Postal Service employees, mailers and competitors.  One way or another, however, change is coming to the Postal Service, and it behooves all those with an interest in the system to try to make the transition as smooth as possible.
<p>
<p>
Thomas M. Lenard is a senior fellow and director of regulatory studies at PFF.
<p>
[ <a href="/pff/amciv/ac-july/i-ac0795.html">July Index</a> ]
<p>
