<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>	How the American Media are Betraying the American Public -- PFF</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<center>
<h2>How the American Media are Betraying the American Public</h2>
<P>
By Arianna Huffington
</center>
<P>
<p>
<p>
 What's wrong with the American media?  The first major problem
with the American media is not its liberal bias, as conservatives
have been complaining.  It's much more fundamental than that.
 It's a cynical bias, a debunking bias, a nihilistic bias, a bias
to believe the worst about us.  It usually finds expression in
a hip, irreverent journalistic style -- an attitude of casual
disdain, and even casual cruelty.  Indeed, most journalists will
eagerly throw their ideological affiliations overboard for the
opportunity to burst your bubble, rain on your parade or shatter
what they believe to be your illusions.
<P>
 In his important article, "A Generation of Vipers,"
for the <I>Columbia Journalism Review</I>, Paul Starobin, wrote: "Even though it is understandable, a migration from skepticism
to cynicism has not served the cause of journalism well.  Cynicism
can be a lazy substitute for curiosity, and in its most corrosive
form, it can produce journalists who have a diminished view of
their profession and of themselves.  Worse, it can damage readers
and viewers and thus, democracy."
<P>
<B>Trivializing the Important</B>
<P>
 The second thing wrong with the American media is that they are
cheating the American public out of a critically important conversation
on the direction of the country. A classic example of this was
the way the media treated the whole debate over welfare reform
and reduced it to footage of interest groups waving school lunch
trays, and to soundbites about a "war on children" and
about "cutting school lunches to give tax breaks to millionaires."
 Now, whichever side of the welfare debate or the school lunch
debate you were on, all of us know that this "cutting-off-school-lunch-for-starving-kids-to-fund-capital-gains-cuts-for-the-rich"
debate in the media was only a macabre parody of what was going
on -- macabre, because the real victims of this are the ten million
children that right now go hungry under the very programs that
have suddenly been turned by the media into untouchable sacred
cows. 
<P>
 If we all can agree that welfare needs to be reformed, and we
all can agree that we need to have a serious conversation about
the way in which it needs to be reformed -- then why is the media,
with its sensationalism, trivialization and fear-mongering, continuing
to make a real debate impossible?
<P>
 We have reached a turning point in American history.  Whether
one is liberal or conservative, Republican or Democrat, we all
recognize that something has gone wrong in America, that our traditional
approaches to our problems aren't working, that by doing more
of what we're already doing we're not going to get a different
result.  We're going to have to make some real fundamental changes
in this country in terms of policy, in terms of our civil institutions,
in terms of our values, our relationship to the state and our
relationship to each other.
<P>
   At present, 70 percent of the American people think that the
media is getting in the way of these solutions.  And they are
getting in the way by cheating the American public out of the
conversation we need to have.
<P>
<b>Betraying the People</b>
<P>
 The third thing wrong with the American media is that the very
important role that the Founding Fathers intended for them is
very seriously threatened by the breakdown of trust in them by
the American people.  In the last <I>Wall Street Journal/NBC</I>
poll, only 21 percent of Americans rated the news media as honest
and trustworthy.   And, when you remember that 37 percent consider
the President honest and trustworthy you realize how dangerously
low they have sunk in the public esteem.
<P>
 Remember the balmy days in 1979 when a Gallup Poll found that
51 percent rated the media as trustworthy.  And remember the even
balmier days in 1971 when a poll showed that a member of the media,
Walter Cronkite, was the most trusted man in America?  Our reverence
for him at that time was something like the reverence tribal people
must have once felt for the village explainers -- wise men who
made plain the world and wonders around us.  But what seems to
have happened over the past 20 years is that the village explainers
have turned into the village harranguers and the village debunkers.
  <P>
 The American people don't hate the media; betrayal would be more
apt.  Americans have always had a special reverence and affection
for the explainers in our culture.  But as the explainers turned,
first hot and heavy, and then loud and shrill, a sort of sacred
trust was breached.  What is it that we feel towards the village
debunker?  We still listen, but we are compelled to guard our
most precious valuables: our hopes, our dreams, our values and
ideals.  Because they are but ignoble ambitions full of hot air
and base motives to the village debunker.
<P>
<b>Off on the Wrong Track</b>
<P>
 So, how did things get to be so bad?  If the media is off track,
where did they go wrong?  Here are the three main reasons I believe
they went so wrong.
<P>
 First of all, members of the media have an insatiable hunger
for the approval of their peers.  There is this tremendous fear
of being uncool -- a tremendous need to appear jaded and sophisticated.
 It's a fear of being caught playing the ingenue, the innocent.
 It's almost a neurosis -- a fear of being seen as the nerdy kid
in the civics class, the one with the pocket protector and Buddy
Holly glasses.  But today's attitude-driven journalism provides
a refuge from all that, a way to submerge all reflection and thoughtful
analysis behind brash headlines and irreverent assumptions.  
<P>
 The search for peer sanction functions a bit like hemline fashion
and W's In and Out column.  One season Clinton is all the rage
-- next season no one would be caught <I>dead</I> writing a good
article about him.
<P>
 The second reason why so much has gone wrong with the American
media is that at some point in the last thirty years the media
decided to play God and obsess not about people's actions but
about their motives.  At some point in journalism we shifted from:
"These are Gingrich's ideas, and here's why they're wrong
for America" to "These are Gingrich's ideas, and he's
a mean-spirited S.O.B. who doesn't care about children" --
a commentary that was portrayed in fact on the cover of <I>Time</I>
magazine, when Gingrich was pictured not just as Scrooge, but
with the stub of Tiny Tim's broken crutch clutched in his menacing
fist.
<P>
 This obsession with people's motives expresses itself as an almost
religious certainty that behind every conviction lives a secret
agenda, and behind every proposed solution lurks a base motive.
 I've got two words for the media on this subject: Lighten up.
 This game has become ridiculous.  Freud once said that sometimes
a cigar is just a cigar.  Well, sometimes an answer is just an
answer -- sometimes people actually mean what they say.  In fact,
the media often acts as a "clean air filter" in reverse.
 Someone will say something with pure intentions, but after the
purity is filtered through the media, what they said becomes polluted.
<P>
 <I>New Republic</I> editor Michael Lewis was recently quoted
saying, "Do I believe that a lot of people's motives are
base?  Yes.  If you dig, you usually can find a selfish motive."
 Fine.  Why don't we start with the premise that no one's motives
-- except perhaps Mother Theresa's -- are 100 percent pure, and
go on from there, to also assume that this is not the end of the
story.  Yes, we all have selfish motives, but also we all have
the better angels of our nature that Lincoln so valiantly tried
to evoke.  If we don't believe that, then we simply end up with
nothing more than reductive hit pieces of the kind that <I>Nation</I>
columnist Christopher Hitchens wrote on Mother Theresa in <I>Vanity
Fair</I>, pegging her as "The Whore of Calcutta.";  I
had always been puzzled by the fact that only 70 percent of Americans
approved of Mother Theresa.  I was wondering where the thirty
percent that disapproved of her were to be found.  Now I know.
<P>
<b>Whose Values?</b>
<P>
 The third reason why the American media has lost the trust of
the American public is that they are so completely out of touch
with them and with their values.  They basically despise their
so-called middle-class values, values like faith and family.
<P>
 A dramatic example of this insensitivity is found on an April
cover of the <I>New Yorker</I> -- an Easter Bunny in a business
suit being crucified against the background of a 1040 tax form.
 This is the <I>New Yorker's</I> choice of a cover for their Easter
issue, enabling them to simultaneously offend millions of Christians'
faith in the miracle of the Crucifixion and the Resurrection,
ridicule middle America's cry for lower taxes and even take a
stab at our children's beloved Easter Bunny.  But no matter. 
Tina Brown will no doubt be greeted with bouquets of "How
brilliant!"  "How inspiring!"  "How daring!"  "How Clever!" at the next New York dinner party she
attends.  And increasingly that's all that seems to matter in
the insular, incestuous world of the media establishment.  The
thrill of pushing the last envelope, shocking the last sensibility,
breaking the last taboo until there is nothing sacred left.  Call
me uncool, but I find this mockery of the crucifixion no more
inspired or inspiring than I did the recent decision by one acclaimed
fashion designer to dress his models in the uniforms of Nazi concentration
camp prisoners and march them down the runway -- no more inspiring
and no less grotesque.
<P>
<b>Where do we Go from Here</b>
<P>
 Now let's move from the examination and diagnosis to the prescription.
 What are the three most important things the media can do to
regain the trust of the American public and help engage them in
the necessary debate over the direction of our country?
<P>
 First, the media must again see the world as it is, not just
as the cynics would have them see it.  I'm not talking about a
Hallmark card version of the world or a Pollyannish -- I'm talking
about a <I>complete</I> version of the world, one which includes
both the crucifixion and the resurrection, one which includes
both the darkness and the light.
<P>
 The challenges we are facing today will require profound change.
 And cynics don't change things.  Believers change things.  Idealists
change things.  Romantics change things.  People who  think things
could be better than they are now change things.  And the media
needs to suspend its chronic disbelief and provide forums and
straight reporting of an urgently needed conversation between
American leaders -- in our political and in our cultural lives
-- and the American public.  In other words, they need to grow
up and stop smirking and jeering at everything from the sidelines.
<P>
<b>The Good things in Life</b>
<P>
 My second suggestion for the media is to focus a little less
on our pathologies and a little more on our potential.  In a world
where the media is only on the constant lookout for trouble-makers,
can they truly be helpful in the search for problem-solvers? 
In a world where the media is on a constant treasure hunt for
failures, can they be truly helpful in spotlighting our successes?
<P>
 Sadly, up to now the media has been content with seeing its role
as one of ripping up all our delusions, deflating all our myths,
exposing what's wrong with every idea and initiative.  Where has
this left us as a culture?  It's left us wandering around dazed
and depressed, overwhelmed by our problems and oblivious to the
solutions within our reach.  If we are to survive as a civilization,
this spiral of nihilism and negativism cannot continue.  
<P>
 Whether you agree with the concept of public journalism or not,
it's a movement gaining ground precisely because it's based on
the assumption that the media have a stake in their communities
and in citizens being able to solve community problems.  During
the Civil Rights movement, many journalists saw their role as
educating the public and moving the country toward policies aimed
at racial justice.  They offered opportunities,  over years of
discussion, for politicians and for the country to come to a democratic
moral conclusion over the inadmissibility of segregation.  Today,
in a  country that has always prided itself on looking at problems
and seeing opportunities, the media looks at opportunities and
sees only problems.
<P>
 My third suggestion for members of the media is to remember that,
as that great Greek Pericles, said, "Courage is the knowledge
of what is not to be feared." The great journalists of the
future will not be found among those fearful of losing the approval
of their peers.  It's a law of nature that no great journalist,
no great political leader, no great artist, no scientist was ever
born by looking over one's shoulder for approval.  Anwar Sadat
wrote in his memoirs that he was only able to think of bold moves
for peace in the Middle East when he stopped looking for acclaim
-- closing his ears to the roar of the crowd and craning, instead,
for the small, still voice within.
<P>
 In the final analysis, the American people deserve more from
the media than pious preaching and abuse from television anchors
when they fail to live up to their standards of maturity.  Yes,
they do deserve to be informed, but information is a two-way street.
 A little listening to what actual Americans believe might do
the media an awful lot of good.  And once we sweep away the broken
shards of cynicism, perhaps the media can return to where it started,
look on America with new eyes, and see both the fullness of the
world as it is and the promise of the world as it could be.
<P>
<p>
Arianna Huffington is a member of the board and a senior fellow
at PFF.
<p>
[ <a href="/pff/amciv/ac-may-jun/i-0695.html">May/June Index</a> ]
