<HEAD>
<title>Karl Marx's Revenge
 -- PFF</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<center>
<h2>Karl Marx's Revenge</h2>
<P>
By Michael Rothschild
</center>
<P>
<p>
<p>
<blockquote><I>"No matter how simple at the start, an income tax inexorably
evolves to hideous complexity, political corruption, and public
cynicism."</I></blockquote>
<P>
 Dick Armey a Marxist?  No way. Long before it became fashionable,
the House Majority Leader was an unabashed champion of economic
freedom.  Yet, in the coming struggle over tax reform, Mr. Armey
has inexplicably lined up on the Left.  
<P>
 Rather than wipe out the income tax and replace it with a non-regressive
National Sales Tax, Mr. Armey's so-called Flat Income Tax proposal
is designed to rescue a tax system first promoted in the Communist
Manifesto.  Second only to the "abolition of property,"
Marx listed "a heavy progressive income tax" as essential
to the demise of capitalism.
<P>
 Marx viewed an economy as a zero-sum game.  Like a thundering
steam engine, Marx's economy could only run so fast and produce
so much.  For me to win, you had to lose.  Win-win outcomes were
impossible.  Income -- the accumulation of wealth -- was inherently
evil, because it could only be gained by grabbing it from the
weak.  All profit came from exploitation.  The income tax would
right this wrong, returning wealth to its creators.  
<P>
 Today, we know better.  Or at least we should.  Though zero-sum,
class war rhetoric still shapes the mindset of Liberal Democrats,
the Information Age economy is a positive-sum game where win-win
outcomes are the norm.  New wealth flows from higher performance
at lower cost, a phenomenon driven by technological innovation.
 More like a rapidly evolving rainforest than a steam engine,
the economy is a complex, living system whose growth is limited
only by human creativity and the availability of capital needed
to turn new ideas into reality.  
<P>
 With the dawn of the Information Age, and the worldwide collapse
of socialism, one might assume that the last vestiges of Marx's
misbegotten policies had disappeared.  But there it is -- the
federal income tax -- America's most crucial economic law; a bearded
German policy wonk's remedy for the evils of 19th century capitalism.
 Ironically, now that Dick Armey finally has the power to turn
rhetoric into law, he's trying to revive Marx's tax instead of
leading the charge to eradicate it.
<P>
 As Mr. Armey would certainly point out, he is not pushing for
a "heavy progressive income tax."  Indeed, his Flat
Income Tax would have just one rate.  After taking a standard
exemption, a 17 percent tax would be applied to income regardless
of the amount.  Mr. Armey promises a system so simple that the
1040 Form will shrink to postcard size.  
<P>
 History teaches otherwise.  When first enacted in 1913 as a 1
percent levy on incomes over $4000 (about $70,000 in 1995 dollars),
the federal income tax was a simple, flat tax.  But ever since,
the law's complexity has grown without limit.  Today, the Internal
Revenue Code and regulations weigh in at one million words and
5,000 pages.  On average, the law is "reformed" once
every 1.3 years. Since 1986, 4,000 sections have been added.
<P>
 Evil special interests, their Gucci-shod lobbyists, and PAC hungry
politicians take the blame for punching loopholes in the tax code.
 But these folks are merely acting out roles made inevitable by
a tax system based on the concept of "income."
<P>
 Because income is not inherently evil, anyone can make a reasonable
case as to why at least some of their income should not be defined
as taxable "income" or why some of their expenses ought
to be deducted from the calculation of "income."  Is
it fair to treat as taxable "income" money saved for
retirement?  What about "too much" savings?  How much
is "too much?"  What about mortgage interest?  Or college
tuition?  Or business lunches?  
<P>
 No matter how flat or simple when it starts out, an income tax,
by its very nature, inexorably evolves into hideous complexity,
political corruption and public cynicism.  Year after year, the
loophole-ridden income tax law erodes the public trust on which
our democracy is founded.
<P>
 Setting a tax rate is easy.  The hard part is defining precisely
to what that rate should apply.  That's why virtually every word
in the tax rules attempts to distinguish "taxable income"
from "non-taxable income," supposedly ill-gotten gains
from honest earnings.  Rules and exceptions.  Exceptions to exceptions.
 This is the shadowy domain inhabited by tax accountants, tax
lawyers, tax lobbyists and Congressional staffers, who pour over
IRS texts, contorting the language to free their clients from
tax hell.
<P>
 No such massive waste of human talent plagues the sales tax.
 Forty-five states, home to 98 percent of all Americans, already
rely on sales taxes and not one state has suffered from creeping
definitional complexity.  Every final retail purchase triggers
a known tax.  Cash registers figure it out and merchants send
it in.  "Ripping out the income tax by its roots," and
replacing it with a National Sales Tax, as proposed by House Ways
and Means Chairman Bill Archer would mean no more 1040 forms.
 No more late nights.  No more tax accountants.  No more tax lawyers.
 And no more IRS.  
<P>
 This is precisely the kind of profound, transformative change
that the new Republican majority in Congress promised the American
people.  No matter how well-intentioned, any "reform"
of the income tax -- whether its labeled flat, simplified or consumption-based
-- will come back to haunt those who champion it.  Back in Gorbachev's
time, such economic reforms were called "half-measures."
 Rather than face up to the need for genuine change, these so-called
"reformers sought to rescue the destructive system
they had inherited.  
<P>
 But if an NST is so dramatically superior to any form of income
tax, why are so many otherwise clear-thinking people like Dick
Armey afraid of it?  Simply put, because they see no way to avoid
the harsh impact that sales taxes typically impose on low-income
families.  Since lower-income families spend virtually all their
earnings on basic consumption, critics contend that an NST would
be severely regressive, taxing away a larger share of the income
of the poor than of the rich.
<P>
 But this problem easily solved with a universal rebate.  Assuming
a family of four spends $25,000 on basic consumption, at a 20
percent rate, the NST would cost them $5,000.  But that $5,000
would be rebated in quarterly payments of $1,250.  Simply listing
their names and social security numbers on a postcard would qualify
a family for a rebate adjusted by its size.  Regardless of income
level, every family would get a rebate that makes their basic
consumption tax free.  
<P>
 The universal rebate eliminates regressivity and the need to
calculate and report on income, consumption, or savings.  Your
taxes would be based on your demonstrated ability to pay.  If
you splurge on that $80,000 Mercedes, you'll pay $16,000 in NST,
while I pay just $2,000 on my $10,000 Plymouth Neon.  With elegant
simplicity, the NST punishes the playboy while rewarding the miser.
 <P>
 Rejecting Marxist envy, the moral message conveyed by the NST
is, "No matter how rich you get, if you save and help grow
the capitalist rainforest by financing new technologies and jobs,
you pay no tax.  You only pay when you take resources out of the
economy and consume above a basic level."
<P>
 If Republican leaders, like Dick Armey, mean it when they promise
Americans a new "Opportunity Society," they should begin
by eradicating the federal income tax.  Notwithstanding Karl Marx,
there is no shame in getting rich.  There is only shame in "reforming"
an income tax designed to prevent all Americans from doing so.
<P>
<p>
Michael Rothschild, president of The Bionomics Institute in
San Francisco, is the author of <B>Bionomics: Economy as Ecosystem</B>.
<p>
[ <a href="/pff/amciv/ac-may-jun/i-0695.html">May/June Index</a> ]
