<html>
<head>
<title>The Myth of the Coming Balanced Budget Recession -- PFF</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<center><h2>The Myth of the Coming Balancing Budget Recession</h2></center>
<p>
<center>By John E. Berthoud</center>
<p>
<p>
<p>
The recent Balanced Budget Amendment debate, along with renewed pledges from the Congressional leadership for a budget resolution that will put the federal government on a glide path to zero deficit, have spurred numerous denouncements from economists of the idea of budget balance.  While granting that eliminating the deficit may help with long-term economic growth, many prophesy short-term disaster. Laura Tyson, new Director of the National Economic Council, has long warned that cutting the deficit too fast could greatly harm the economy.
<p>
Will the gut wrenching fiscal decisions required to bring our federal budget into balance lead us into recession?  International experience indicates that such gloom-and-doom projections are off the mark.  There are numerous international examples which show that balancing the budget, far from hurting an economy, might actually be an integral part of economic resuscitation and growth.  The United Kingdom, Australia, Ireland and Denmark all clearly show this to be the case.
<p>
Throughout the 1980's, Margaret Thatcher made huge cuts in public spending in the 
United Kingdom to achieve budget balance.  Between 1980 and 1992, public sector employment fell by 26 percent, largely through substantial privatization efforts.  The government also made cuts in social welfare spending which had ballooned in the preceding decades.  What were the economic results?  Budget balancing seems hardly to have been detrimental to economic growth.  There was an almost-inverse relationship between bringing the budget into balance and the unemployment rate.  From 1981 to 1989 the UKs budget deficit fell steadily going from a deficit 
of 4.7 percent of GDP in 1981 to a surplus of 1.2 percent of GDP in both 1988 and 1989.  During the same period, the unemployment rate fell from 10.5 percent to 7.3 percent and GDP, which as a percent of GDP shrank by 1.3 percent in 1981, was in 1988 and 1989 growing at 5 percent and 2.2 percent respectively.
<p>
Interestingly, there was an outcry from economists in the UK similar to what we are 
hearing now in the United States.  At the beginning of Thatchers austerity efforts, 364 
economists wrote a letter to The Times denouncing her for balancing the budget, claiming it would destroy the economy. Their gloomy projections obviously did not pan out.
<p>
Australia is another country which brought its budget into balance with no apparent 
negative economic consequences.  In the 1980's the government pursued a policy of balance through large cuts-in social welfare spending along with cuts in aid to the states.  The budget, with a deficit which-peaked at 4.1 percent of GDP in 1984 fell and went into surplus by 1988.  The unemployment rate fell from 8.5 percent in 1984 to 6.8 percent in 1988 and 5.7 percent in 1989.  GDP growth was strong in these years as well, growing at 4.8 percent and 3.0 percent of GDP respectively.
<p>	
Some of the most in-depth work on this question has been done by two Italian economists, Francesco Giavazzi and Marco Pagano.  Contra Keynes, their analysis of European fiscal policies and economics shows a clear relationship between decreases in government spending and increases in private domestic demand.  Denmark and Ireland are, however, the two most striking cases of "expansionary stabilizations" in Europe.  In Denmark, the fiscal reversal turnaround of 1982 was followed by a very strong expansion over the next four years.   In Ireland a fiscal 
stabilization in the late 1980's led to economic growth, although a similar effort in the early 80's had led to recession.  Interestingly, throughout Europe cuts in spending have a simulative effect, but Giavazzi and Pagano find that there is a negative correlation between increasing taxes and private consumption which they note is consistent with the predictions of Keynesianism.
<p>
Denmark, which had seen spiraling debt in the early 1980's (public debt as a percent of GDP-grew annually by 10.2 percent from 1979 - 1982) elected a Conservative government in late 1982 which-opted to largely slash spending to restore fiscal balance (although taxes were also raised). Complementary monetary and exchange rate policies were also adopted.  As a result of these efforts, the debt to GDP ratio started declining.  While this contractionary fiscal policy was underway, real-GDP grew by an average of 3.6 percent over the years 1983-1986.  Other measures also jumped upwards-including consumers confidence, private consumption and total 
real wealth.  Interestingly, consumer-confidence rose markedly when taxes were being raised and public services cut.
<p>
Ireland faced a similar situation to Denmark in the early 1980's.  In 1981, public debt as a 
percent of GDP was 87 percent.  A policy of fiscal austerity was adopted.  As with Denmark, monetary policy and exchange rate policies complemented the fiscal policy retrenchment.  Also like Denmark, after initial devaluation, Ireland pegged its currency to the Deutsch Mark and liberalized capital flows. Initially in 1982, fiscal retrenchment caused economic slowdown.  Private consumption fell 7.1 percent in 1982 and remained flat for two years.
<p>
But in 1987, the new government led by Charles Haughey enacted another series of 
retrenchments cutting the deficit substantially and causing the debt to GDP ratio to start declining for the first time in almost twenty years.  Economic growth was relatively strong during this second retrenchment.  What was the key difference from the first period of austerity?  While there were-several differences, the most significant was that the deficit was reduced largely through spending cuts rather than tax increases.  And while some (although very little) of the budget balancing in the second instance was done through increases in taxes, these revenues only came 
from broadening the base, not from raising any rates.  Marginal rates in fact actually fell slightly during this period.
<p>
In Denmark, the combination of fiscal and monetary policy changes led to a decline in 
interest rates and thus there was a wealth effect increasing consumption.  But the wealth effect cannot fully explain the changes in consumption.  The remaining increase was due to cuts in government spending. In Ireland, disposable income appeared to be the key factor driving consumption and thus there was a Keynesian contraction in 1982.  But in 1987, when contractionary fiscal policy was conducted largely through cutting spending and there was a liberalization in the credit market, Irish private consumption boomed.
<p>
How can cuts in government spending prove to be simulative to the economy?  After all, didnt Keynesian economics teach us just the opposite?  Giavazzi and Pagano believe their findings prove the theories of the German Council of Economic Experts who have argued that cutting spending leads to private sector expectations of lower taxes in the future, thereby leading to a simulative impact on the economy.  In Europe, economic actors have realized that a reduction of government spending and borrowing today will mean lower taxes and a more robust economy tomorrow.  Thus, cuts in government spending and deficits are quite logically accompanied by coincidental expansions in private consumption and strong overall growth.
<p>
The empirical lessons from Europe and Australia are clear: the coming federal government retrenchment does not necessarily mean hard economic times for the United States.  Critical to our economys future growth, however, is for the Republican Congress to make good on its promises and balance the budget through cuts in spending, not increases in revenues.
<p>
<p>
John E. Berthoud is vice president for research at the National Taxpayers Union Foundation.
<p>
[ <a href="/pff/amciv/ac-april/i-ac0495.html">April Index</a> ]
<p>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
