<head>
<title>Common Sense Welfare Reform Act -- PFF</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff/"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<center><h2>Common Sense Welfare Reform Act</center></h2>
<center>By Joe Knollenberg</center>
<p>
<p>
<p>
On February 9, 1964, President Lyndon Johnson stood before a joint session of 
Congress and announced: "This Administration today, here and now, declares 
unconditional war on poverty in America."  With this simple statement, the U.S. 
government embarked upon one of the largest expansions of domestic social spending in the nations history.  Literally hundreds of new federal programs were created to provide Americas less fortunate with financial assistance, housing, food, education, health care and jobs in the hope that poverty could be eliminated once and for all.
<p>
Yet 30 years and nearly $5 trillion later, there are more people living below the 
poverty line than when we started -- even though we now spend 5 percent of GDP on 
welfare!  
<p>
Adjusting for inflation, we have spent more on the War on Poverty than we did 
to win both World Wars combined.  In fact, if viewed strictly from a budgetary 
perspective, there should be no poverty in America.  Presently, the federal and state 
governments combined spend over $300 billion on welfare payments and other anti-
poverty programs -- money that if simply divided among the poor, is three times enough to lift every welfare recipient in America above the poverty line.
<p>
Clearly, the amount of money is not the problem; it is the delivery system.  
Americas welfare delivery system has become a de facto government monopoly.  It is 
woefully expensive, overly bureaucratic, preoccupied with "process,"  and client-ignorant.  
<p>
It was originally created to assist neighborhood charities, but now it undermines them.  For example, neighborhood charities often find it difficult to condition aid on getting a job or quitting drugs when prospective recipients can walk down to the local welfare office and pick up a government check with no strings attached.  It is also no coincidence that the portion of charitable giving in this country devoted to alleviating poverty has declined by a shocking one-third since 1960.  As government (with taxpayer money) took more and more responsibility for caring for the poor, it fostered an "I gave at the office syndrome" that sapped Americas spirit of community involvement.
<p>
This year, Congress is finally taking up the issue of welfare reform.  We will 
consolidate overlapping federal programs, give states more flexibility to experiment, and enact measures to encourage work and discourage out-of -wedlock births.  But while these are all good ideas, none of them are aimed at fundamentally changing the method by which we deliver aid to the poor.
<p>
Thats why Congressman Jim Kolbe (R-AZ) and I have introduced  the Common 
Sense Welfare Reform Act of 1995.  Our bill would create a "Choice in Welfare" tax 
credit, designed to give individual citizens a voice in how this country fights poverty.  
"Choice in Welfare" means that every taxpaying American would be free to direct up to 
$2500 of their federal income taxes to a charitable organization in their community (or 
anywhere in their state) that is engaged in anti-poverty efforts.  Each time a taxpayer 
claims this credit, federal welfare spending would be lowered by the same amount.
<p>
By getting taxpayers into the act, welfare decision-making would no longer be 
solely in the hands of government bureaucrats and politicians.  Indeed, every taxpaying  American would be able to choose whether their tax dollars are spent on public programs ike AFDC, Food Stamps and public housing subsidies, or spent on private organizations like the Salvation Army, Habitat for Humanity, and Project Hope.
<p>
This bill seeks to reward private charities for doing what they have traditionally 
done best:  giving prompt, temporary assistance to those in need.  Private charities view assistance as a tool by which to change behavior -- not as a right or a way of life.  They stress personal responsibility and provide hands-on management for recipients.  Public welfare requires nothing from the recipient except eligibility.  It is inconceivable that a family could subsist for generations on the local soup kitchen, food bank or shelter -- as many now do on welfare.
<p>
The reforms Congress is currently considering are a good start, but Americas War 
on Poverty will never be won by simply tinkering with the current government-run system.  We must create a new system that puts neighborhood charity above government payments and caring individuals over a faceless bureaucracy.  Only when this is accomplished will we finally be able to address poverty in a truly effective and meaningful way. 
<p>
<p>
Joe Knollenberg is a Member of the U.S. House of Representatives from Michigan.
 <p>
[ <a href="/pff/amciv/ac-april/i-ac0495.html">April Index</a> ]
<p>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
