<html>
<head>
<title>The American Idea and American Promise -- PFF</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<center><h2>The American Idea and American Promise</h2></center>
<center>By Everett Carll Ladd</center>
<p>
<p>
<p>
The American Idea is an enormous resource.  Since this is demonstrably so -- and has been for two centuries -- its more than a little surprising that so few political leaders have recognized the extent of the resource, or the extent to which it can be helpful to them in moving the country in large and constructive ways.  Some have recognized it, of course, and they have been our great leaders.
<p>
More on that in a bit.  First, we need to understand just what the resource is.  It begins 
with the fact that America is a "creedal nation."  G. K. Chesterton, one of Britains great
all-purpose men of ideas, grasped it nicely when he wrote that the United States "is the only nation in the world that is founded on a creed."  He went on to observe that this foundation-creed "is set forth with dogmatic and even theological lucidity in the Declaration of Independence....It enunciates that all men are equal in their claim to justice, that governments exist to give them justice, and that their authority is for that reason just."
<p>
The American Creed or Idea is indeed the promise of the Declaration, but it is more than this.  It is nothing less than an insistence on permitting all who strive to realize their fullest individual promise.  Its a uniquely far-reaching individualism -- in this sense of the ideal of the fullest individuality.
<p>
Some critics at every period want to diminish the ideal by observing that we have not 
always honored it and have never fully realized it.  We havent.  But while it is true, this criticism is also silly.  On this planet, ideals are never fully realized.  The important question about them is whether they are real, vital and in some substantial way operative as the standard goal driving the society along.
<p>
As is true with so much of the American political heritage, Abraham Lincoln grasped the special role played by Americas founding Idea.  This knowledge governed his entire political approach after 1856.  He put it best, I think, in his June 26, 1857 speech on the Dred Scott decision, delivered in Springfield, Illinois.  Lincoln gave many memorable addresses, but this one is, I believe, easily his greatest.  All his essential political judgments appear fully formed in it.
<p>
Lincoln told his audience that June evening that the ideals of the Declaration and, in 
general, of the countrys founding Creed comprised our only substantial claim to nationhood.  These ideals had not, Lincoln surely understood in the midst of the slavery crisis, always been 
honored.  But to abandon them, as Chief Justice Taney in effect proposed in his majority decision in Dred Scott, would be to utterly destroy this creedal nation.  Lincoln observed that the Founders surely did not think people were each the same, but that they did view each citizen as having an essential equality of moral claim:  "They defined with tolerable distinctness, in what respects they did consider all men created equal -- equal in certain inalienable rights, among which are life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness.  This they said, and this they meant.  They did not mean to assert the obvious untruth, that all were then actually enjoying that equality, nor yet that they were about to confer it immediately upon them.  In fact they had no power to confer such a boon."
<p>
Nonetheless, what they did was of overriding importance:  "They meant to set up a 
standard maxim for free society, which should be familiar to all, and revered by all; constantly 
looked to, constantly labored for, and even though never perfectly attained, constantly 
approximated, and thereby constantly spreading and deepening its influence, and augmenting the happiness and value of life to all people of all colors everywhere."  This, then, is the American Idea, the constituent basis of American nationhood, to be constantly striving for a far-reaching promise of full individuality as the only tenable goal for the nation.
<p>	
The great Progressive intellectual, Herbert Croly, founder of The New Republic, also 
understood this well.  Croly discussed it in his great book, The Promise of American Life.  The promise was nothing less than the fullest opportunity for each citizen to realize his or her highest 
possible level of achievement.  Crolys book is badly misunderstood these days because discussion of it focuses on only one of its parts.  Writing in 1909, he indeed believed that more government intervention was needed to redress excessive concentrations of private power and extend individual opportunity.  Whether Croly would advocate more government today is, of course, unanswerable, but I think there is good reason to suspect that he would not.
<p>
The central thesis of The Promise of American Life is that each age must harness the 
Creed and find its own ways to extend the promise.  Croly believed that Washington, Hamilton 
and the Federalists made that contribution best in the founding years, that Lincoln was its 
principal exponent during the slavery crisis, and that Theodore Roosevelt came closest to playing the role in the early 20th century.  Each of these leaders or movements used very different approaches, given differing challenges.
<p>
We are left to find, in our own time, ways of harnessing the enormous moral energy of the 
Creed to extend the promise of American life.  While this does not involve, in my view, disdaining 
government as such, it surely does not include a principal reliance on governmental action.  In so many sectors, excessive growth of the state has come to threaten, not enhance, the realization of the nations promise.  But, again, the core of that promise has always come back to the individual -- the demanding and frustrating, but ultimately rewarding enterprise, through which individual citizens join together in a thousand separate ways to advance their common purposes.
<p>
We must all understand clearly and cleanly the role of ideas in this creedal nation.  We 
must understand, too, the great energy available if we harness Americans deep commitment to their nations special promise.  Today, we are groping for the successful articulation of the Idea in our own time.  But, fortunately, we dont need new answers, only appropriate applications of our old answers to new circumstances.  As in every previous era, our challenge is finding fresh means of achieving an ever fuller and more fulfilling individuality.
<p>
<p>
Everett Carll Ladd is professor of political science and director of  the Institute for Social Inquiry at the University of Connecticut. He is also the executive director and president of the Roper Center for Public Opinion Research. 
<p>
[ <a href="/pff/amciv/ac-april/i-ac0495.html">April Index</a> ]
<p>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
