<html>
<head>
<title>Misunderstanding Microsoft -- PFF</title>
<head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<center><h2>Misunderstanding Microsoft</h2></center>
<center>By Stan Liebowitz</center>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Did you know that the American way of life is in jeopardy? Not from international communism.  Not from radical terrorists. Not even from our inadequate educational system. Instead, according to a  remarkable document submitted to the courts, our freedoms are apparently imperiled by the Microsoft corporation. This document was crafted by individuals who believe that our market based economy has led  
us to type on the wrong keyboards, tape with the wrong videorecorders, and drive the wrong cars. If you  think I exaggerate, read on.  
<p>
Our strange story begins with the recently completed Justice Department investigation of  Microsoft. Microsoft and Justice came to an agreement whereby Microsoft consented to make certain changes in its business practices that Justice believed were anticompetitive.  
<p>
But the agreement has been overturned by U.S. District Judge Stanley Sporkin. It is widely thought that he was heavily influenced by a group of lawyers and economists who prepared a written submission to the court. This group relied on economic theories suggesting that markets sometimes get stuck using a "wrong" product. These economic theories concluded that we may need the government, in its wisdom, to choose our products for us. These authors repeat their arguments in another court submission in opposition to Microsoft's friendly purchase of Intuit, a maker of personal finance and tax software.  
<p>
Although many dreadful scenarios are discussed by these authors, the most frightening is this: "It  is difficult to imagine that in an open society such as this one with multiple information sources, a single company could seize sufficient control of information transmission so as to constitute a threat to the underpinnings of a free society. But such a scenario is a realistic (and perhaps probable) outcome."  Consumers, according to this theory, will be so locked-in to Microsoft's technology that they will be compelled to purchase Microsoft products even when those products are far inferior to rival products. And as a result, Microsoft will gain control over every market it enters, eventually dominating all the information technology.  
<p>
With no less than the destruction of our freedoms being put forward as a probable outcome, it is  
perhaps not surprising that Judge Sporkin was reluctant to approve the proposed Microsoft-Justice settlement.  
<p>
But before we march on Microsoft headquarters with our pitchforks and torches to destroy the  
apparent monster that Bill Gates has created, and before we hand over to some government bureaucrat our right to choose the products that we consume, we might want to ponder the basis of these economic theories.  
<p>  
<b>Unsupported Theories  </b>
<p>  
Theories are acceptable only when they are capable of explaining actual events or behavior. Even in economics, we have a long history of testing theories with empirical evidence in order to verify their validity. Yet when we carefully examine the empirical support for the theories used to derail the Justice-Microsoft agreement, we find no support for their alarming conclusions.  
The single overriding example that is used to support these theories is the rather quaint yet well-known example of the typewriter keyboard.  
<p>
If you look at the upper left hand keys of your keyboard, you will see that they form the letters  
QWERTY. One commonly hears the claim that to keep the old-fashioned mechanisms from jamming on the early typewriters, the mechanics who created the keyboard adopted a design that actually slowed down typing speed! Thus the QWERTY design is reputed to be far inferior to the "scientifically" designed Dvorak keyboard which claimed a 40 percent increase in typing speed. Supposedly, the Navy conducted experiments during the Second World War demonstrating that the costs of retraining typists on the new keyboard could be fully recovered within ten days!   
<p>
This example appeared to be a perfect case to support the claim that consumers and markets get stuck with the wrong product. Yet upon investigation, this claim turns out to be false.   
In an article published in the Journal of Law and Economics in 1990, Stephen Margolis and I  
demonstrated that this story was a myth -- a myth based largely on wishful thinking and on a shoddy reading of the history of the typewriter keyboard. The QWERTY keyboard, it turns out, is just about as good a design as the Dvorak keyboard, and was better than most competing designs that existed in the late 1800s when there were many keyboard designs maneuvering for a place in the market.  
<p>
We discovered a set of experiments conducted under the auspices of the General Service  
Administration in the 1950s comparing QWERTY with Dvorak that disproved the claims of Dvorak's superiority. Many, if not most, of the claims to the contrary were made by the patent owner of the competing keyboard design, Professor August Dvorak. The wartime Navy study turns out to have been conducted under the auspices the Navy's chief expert in time-motion studies -- Lt. Commander August Dvorak, and the results were clearly fudged.    
<p>
Yet in spite of our five year old paper, which has not been factually disputed, the QWERTY  
keyboard remains the leading example put forward to support the theory that markets get stuck with wrong products. One could hardly find better evidence of a theory's lack of empirical support than the continued use of a result that is known to be incorrect.  
<p>
Another supposed example often put forward to support these theories is our use of VHS when  
we supposedly should be using Beta videorecorders instead. It is claimed that Beta was a better format and that VHS only won because it luckily got a large market share early on in the competition with Beta. But this story turns out to be just as inaccurate as the keyboard story. In an article forthcoming in the Journal of Law, Economics and Organization, Margolis and I demonstrate that Sony had previously shared its patents and secrets with the creators of VHS; that Sony had offered and demonstrated the Betamax and its innovations to the owners of VHS; and that the two formats were so similar that Sony engineers considered the VHS machine a copy of the Betamax. The one crucial difference was the size of the videotape cassette. The Betamax cassette was smaller than the VHS cassette and allowed at first only one hour of recording capacity -- too short to record many movies. The larger size of the VHS cassette provided longer recording time for any quality of picture, and was capable of recording movies or football games. So, once again, the markets did not get stuck with the wrong product. In fact, since the Betamax appeared first, yet was overcome by VHS, directly contradicts the conclusions put forward by these theorists.  
<p>
One of the economists who helped prepare the submission against Microsoft has argued that we might be stuck with gasoline powered engine when steam might have been a superior choice. If you believe that we would be better off driving Stanley Steamers.  I guess you might also believe the dire predictions of these theories. In that case, however, I have a bridge I would like to sell you.  
 <p> 
<b>Implications  </b>
  <p>
This does not mean that the Microsoft acquisition of Intuit or the Justice Department settlement  
should not be scrutinized. But before we engage in hysterical hyperbole, we had best check whether the theories being put forward to influence public policy have any validation out there in the real world.  Instead of sounding alarms about Microsoft jeopardizing our freedoms, we should worry about relying on those technical wizards in the judiciary and government to choose our technologies for us. Do we really need policy police receiving their marching orders from professors who cannot seem to get their facts straight? Abridgments of our freedoms are far more likely to come from government which can compel our behavior, than from corporations that require, for their own survival, our voluntary purchases of their products.  
<p>  
<p>
Stan Liebowitz is a Professor of  Economics in the Management School of the University of Texas at  Dallas.
<p>
[ <a href="/pff/amciv/ac-april/i-ac0495.html">April Index</a> ]
