<html>
<head>
<title>Condemning the Successful -- PFF</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<center><h2>Condemning the Successful</h2></center>
<center>By Michael Rothschild</center>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
No matter how fervently we profess our devotion to the principles of American free-
enterprise, when it comes down to the specifics of Bill Gates and Microsoft, most of us get a bit wobbly in the knees.  Instead of standing up for Americas most successful entrepreneur in his 
struggle with the Federal Government, we stand back and let Bill Gates fight alone.  
<p>
Jealousy and sloppy thinking have worked their magic.  I dont know about you, but just a 
tiny sliver of Gates billions would set me up for life.  To get that rich, by means fair and square, 
doesnt seem possible,  does it?  Just like the Robber Barons of old, Bill Gates must have crossed 
the line from brilliant entrepreneur to craven monopolist, from good capitalist to bad.  And now, 
of course, he deserves his comeuppance at the hands of Federal officials.
<p>
Or so, at least, goes the morality tale framing Microsofts current travails.  Egged on by 
Microsofts also-ran competitors, the Federal Trade Commission, then the Department of Justice, 
and now U.S. District Judge Stanley Sporkin have taken their shots.  The specific allegations keep 
changing, but every attack on Microsoft is based on the same assertion: namely, that Microsoft is 
a "monopoly" or "near monopoly" that must be stopped before it consolidates its stranglehold 
over the global software industry.
<p>With Microsofts guilt presumed by virtue of its "monopoly" position, the lawyers quickly 
move on to the assessment of penalties.  Should Microsofts "monopolistic" business practices be 
restricted?  Should the company be broken up?  Should Microsoft be blocked from acquiring 
Intuit (maker of the wildly popular Quicken home bookkeeping software)?  Or should Microsoft 
be prevented from entering the on-line services industry?  Before long, the Supreme Court may be 
asked to sort things out.  But ultimately, even the High Court cant solve the fundamental issues 
causing Microsofts current woes.  Only Congress can decide whether Americas first great 21st 
century company deserves to be punished or whether our 19th century antitrust laws needs to be 
changed.  
<p>
<b>Setting Standards</b>
<p>
<p>
Congress might begin rethinking antitrust by asking a simple question --whether the 
concept of "monopoly" still makes sense in an Information Age economy.  Consider the brief 
history of the personal computer industry.  IBM launched its first personal computer, the IBM-
PC, in 1981.  Bogged down by a vast internal bureaucracy that had taken power during the 
companys endless struggle with the FTC and the Justice Department, IBM simply couldnt move 
fast enough to enter the explosive new market created by Apple Computer and other PC upstarts.  
Desperate to catch up, IBM abandoned its tradition of internal development and assembled its 
first PC from components made by outside suppliers.  Among the pieces IBM pulled together was 
an operating system, called DOS, made by an unknown Seattle pip-squeak.  
<p>
Backed by IBMs enormous prestige, its PC instantly became the industry standard, the 
safe choice in the confusing new world of personal computing.  Sold by the millions, each IBM-
PC carried a copy of Microsofts DOS operating system.  The operating system is the layer of 
software that translates commands from software applications like word processors, spreadsheets, 
and games into signals that the hardware can understand.  
<p>
Like VHS, Morse Code, QWERTY keyboards, Number 10 envelopes, Group III fax 
machines, and 110 volts, Microsofts DOS became the de facto standard of the PC industry.  Such 
unsanctioned standards emerge in all technologically sophisticated industries.
<p>
The key is getting other independent companies to voluntarily make their products 
compatible with your proposed standard.  When IBM, then still master of the computing universe, 
selected DOS for its PC, it anointed the tiny firm with "IBM-ness," immediate industry-wide 
certainty that DOS had become the de facto standard, the language that everyone else had to learn 
to speak.
<p>
But given the torrid pace of change in the information economy, even a de facto standard 
like DOS is vulnerable to rapid obsolescence.  And by the late Eighties, as PC hardware became 
more capable, DOS was at risk of being displaced by an entirely new kind of operating system.  
Had Bill Clintons friend John Sculley, then CEO of Apple Computer, comprehended the 
fundamental economics of de facto standards, he would have licensed Apples superb Macintosh 
operating system to other hardware makers and created the standard for the next PC generation.  
<p>I
n failing to do so, Mr. Sculley committed the greatest single strategic blunder in modern 
business history and gave Bill Gates a second chance to hang onto industry leadership.  Microsoft 
responded by launching Windows, its Macintosh look-alike.  Had John Sculley made the right 
move, the Justice Department wouldnt be wasting its time on that "has been" Microsoft.  Instead, 
Apples attorneys would be the ones fending off allegations of monopoly power.  
<p>
Integrating disparate technologies into easy-to-use, seamless systems doesnt work 
without compatible interfaces among those technologies.  With technological specialties 
proliferating and the pace of innovation accelerating, the need for de facto standards will grow, 
not shrink.  Right now, vicious competitive struggles are raging to determine forthcoming de 
facto standards for compact videodiscs, Internet interfaces and electronic cash payment systems.  
The winners have not yet emerged.  But when they do, they will hold huge shares of their 
respective markets.  
<p>
By definition, if the industry leader holds much less than 90 percent market share, its de 
facto standard has not yet been established.  And without a clear standard, sensible investors, 
producers and consumers play "wait and see."  Technological progress slows and international 
competitiveness is undermined, along with job creation and economic growth.  But if a company 
has the technological prowess and business smarts to knock off rivals and capture 90 percent of 
its market, it will almost certainly be pilloried as a "monopoly" engaged in "exclusionary 
practices" under the antitrust laws.  In short, winning the 21st century business game condemns a 
company to losing the 19th century antitrust game.  This is the Catch-22 that Microsoft now finds 
itself in.
<p>
As a candidate, President Clinton pledged to review Americas antitrust laws -- principally 
the Sherman Antitrust Act of 1890 and the Clayton Act of 1914 -- to assess their impact on the 
global competitiveness of American companies.  It hasnt happened.  Now Congress should 
examine how laws based upon Machine Age economic theory are undermining our Information 
Age economy.  If Congress wants American companies to be world beaters, if it wants upstarts 
like Microsoft to grab market dominance in Japan and Europe, and create many thousands of 
high-pay, high-skill jobs here at home, then weve got to stop telling our companies to compete 
hard, but not too hard.  
<p>
Judge Learned Hand, a giant of American jurisprudence, once wrote:  "The successful 
competitor, having been urged to compete, must not be turned upon when he wins."  Now that 
the federal government has turned upon Bill Gates and Microsoft, who among the devoted 
supporters of American free-enterprise will stand up for principles in action?
<p>
Michael Rothschild, president of The Bionomics Institute in San Francisco, is the author of <b>Bionomics: Economy as 
Ecosystem.</b>
<p>
[ <a href="/pff/amciv/ac-april/i-ac0495.html">April Index</a> ]
<p>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
