</TABLE>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5 FACE="Arial">Introduction</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">A book entitled <U>Privatization in the United
States</U> would be very thin indeed.  It would be so partly because
America did not participate as extensively as most other countries
with this century's destructive experiment of government production
of goods more efficiently produced by the private sector. Unfortunately,
the book also would be thin because Americans have been less aggressive
and imaginative than countries from Great Britain to Bolivia in
withdrawing the national government from activities better carried
by the private sector.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The federal government currently operates businesses
like electric generation, passenger rail service, mail delivery
and air traffic control that other countries have privatized.
Yet Washington's only principal divestitures have been Conrail
in 1987 and the Great Plains Coal Gasification Plant in 1988.
The value of salable federal enterprises is estimated to be more
than $75 billion, and selling them would save taxpayers $6.2 billion
per year. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">This report proposes a politically viable plan
to expand privatization in America by selling three of the federal
government's Power Marketing Administrations. The PMA's, as they
are known to the cognoscenti, market power generated at dams owned
by the federal government. Currently, the federal government is
the nation's largest producer and transmitter of electricity.
 Yet whatever may have originally justified the government's involvement
in this area no longer exists. Areas that were once rural and
underdeveloped are now booming and thus do not need subsidized
electricity to encourage growth. The electric industry is now
entering an age of intense competition that undercuts its &quot;natural
monopoly.&quot;</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Last year, the House Resources Committee developed
a plan to sell one of the PMA's, the Southeastern Power Administration
(SEPA). A coalition of concerned interests, including bass fishermen
who were worried about how the sale would affect them, blocked
the plan. This episode is typical of what has happened, and will
continue to happen, as serious attempts are made to reduce the
size of the federal government. Each year, millions of Americans
make decisions about planting a crop, attending college, or starting
a business based on the expectation of some benefit from Washington.
When these beneficiaries feel that their &quot;entitlement&quot;
might be taken away from them - regardless of the net benefits
to society - they often become active opponents to change.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The plan outlined here provides a creative
solution to this problem. Through a warrant privatization scheme,
current beneficiaries of the subsidized power provided by the
PMA's are effectively compensated for any potential loss of their
subsidy. Through a river association scheme, the users of environmental
and other non-power benefits of federal dams are actually given
control of &quot;their&quot; dams, with an opportunity to enhance
their benefits. Although it might be debatable that beneficiaries
deserve to be reimbursed for the loss of their subsidy, there
is no doubt that compensation will turn opponents of privatization
into proponents. Similar plans in Great Britain, Central Europe
and Latin America have turned pensioners, laborers and students
into capitalists. Similarly, our plan can serve as a model on
how to harness the energy of ordinary Americans in support of
privatizing many government functions.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Not only does our plan reduce the size and
scope of the federal government, it also decentralizes the decision-making
process and returns power (no pun intended) to individuals and
local communities.  The birth of last year's plan to sell SEPA
was accompanied by a commotion of meetings, hearings, consultation
and lobbying in order to solve some very thorny issues.  What
was to be sold?  To whom?  At what price and under what conditions?
 Our plan will move these decisions as much as possible out of
committee rooms in Washington and give those decisions to people
who have a direct interest in the outcome.  Potential buyers of
the PMA's will have to woo consumers instead of sending lobbyists
to the Capitol.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">There is a broad consensus that the old, centralized
model of government is unsuitable for the future.  In both the
ends it achieves and the means it uses to achieve them, our plan
represents an innovative way to make the electric industry and
the federal government ready for the next century.</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5 FACE="Arial">PART 1</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5 FACE="Arial">THE PMA PROBLEM<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Arial">What are PMA's?</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Through the Tennessee Valley Authority and
five Power Marketing Administrations, the federal government produces
and markets about 9 percent of all electric power in the United
States. The PMA's are federal agencies within the Department of
Energy that market power produced by federal generation facilities
(mostly hydroplants). There are five PMA's in the Southeast, Southwest,
West and Alaska: Southeastern Power Administration (SEPA); Southwestern
Power Administration (SWPA); Western Area Power Administration
(WAPA); Alaska Power Administration (APA); and, Bonneville Power
Administration (BPA). This white paper deals with the privatization
of SEPA, SWPA and WAPA. (Alaska Power Administration is already
being defederalized; the Bonneville Power Administration and Tennessee
Valley Authority each present significantly different issues.)
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Southwestern Power Administration was established
by the Secretary of Interior under the authority of the President's
war powers in 1943. The authority to create permanent marketing
authorities was provided in 1944 with passage of Flood Control
Act. In 1950, the Secretary of Interior established Southeastern
Power Administration. Western Area Power Administration was authorized
under the Department of Energy Organization Act of 1977 when the
existing PMA's were transferred from Department of the Interior
to the Department of Energy. The purpose behind the PMA's was
to market electric power generated at federal water projects -
built primarily for the purposes of irrigation, navigation or
flood control - to provide for the repayment of these projects,
and to help supply households and businesses in certain areas
with inexpensive (subsidized) electric power  in order to promote
regional development.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Four of the five PMA's are funded annually
with appropriations, and receipts from their activities, such
as sale of electric power, are deposited in the Treasury as general
funds. BPA is an exception; in 1974, Congress stopped providing
Bonneville with appropriations and instead provided it with a
revolving fund maintained by the Treasury and permanent Treasury
borrowing authority. PMA's generally do not &quot;own&quot; and
operate the generation facilities (power houses and the dam structures
themselves). In case of SEPA, SWPA and WAPA, the generation facilities
are &quot;owned&quot; and operated primarily by the Corps of Engineers
or Bureau of Reclamation. The PMA's &quot;purchase&quot; power
from the Corps or the Bureau and then transmit and distribute
it through their transmission facilities (except for SEPA, which
does not own any transmission facilities and only markets power
through other utilities' transmission networks). The &quot;purchase&quot;
price that PMA's pay to the Corps or Bureau is not a market price,
but rather an administrative charge set  high enough to cover
the expenditures that the Corps or Bureau incur in investment,
operation and maintenance of power generation facilities. WAPA
and BPA are also required to cover in their administrative charges
costs of irrigation and other non-power activities that exceed
these users' ability to pay. (As both the generation and transmission
facilities are federally owned, we treat these transfers between
the PMA's and the Corps or Bureau as a budgetary issue. We assume
for the practical purpose of privatization that the firms consist
of the power generation equipment and the marketing organization.)
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The PMA's sell most of their power to &quot;preference
customers,&quot; so-called because the legislation establishing
the PMA's gave priority to certain classes of wholesalers.  For
example, the act establishing BPA states that, </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">&quot;<I>in order to insure that the facilities
for the generation of electric energy at the Bonneville project
shall be operated for the benefit of the general public, and particularly
of domestic and rural consumers, the administrator shall at all
times, in disposing of electric energy generated at said project,
give preference and priority to public bodies and cooperatives.&quot;</I></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">These preference customers, mainly cooperative
or municipal electric utilities (munies and co-ops for short),
generate their own power or purchase power from various sources,
including PMA's, and then distribute electricity to ultimate end
users in their service areas. State and federal agencies involved
in generation and distribution of electricity (e.g. state power
authorities, irrigation districts) also count as preference customers,
as do end users who are government entities, such as Air Force
bases. In recent years, the PMA's have begun contracting with
investor owned utilities (IOU's) to provide excess power to IOU
transmission network. The IOU's are not, however, considered to
be preference customers.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">PMA power is among the least expensive electricity
available in the country. In 1993, average wholesale price for
electricity in the Southeast was 3.11 cents per kilowatt-hour,
while SEPA sold on average for 1.89 &#162;/kWh.  The average wholesale
price in the Southwest was 2.76 &#162;/kWh as opposed to SWPA's
1.23 &#162;/kWh; the price in the West was 3.09 &#162;/kWh while
WAPA charged 1.81 &#162;/kWh. This data suggests that the PMA's
have succeeded in their mission of providing inexpensive power
in their marketing areas. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">How can the PMA's sell at such low prices?
 First, these PMA's market power generated at hydroplants, which
are, by their very nature, one of the cheapest sources of electric
power.  Second, legislation requires the PMA's to set their prices
at the lowest possible level consistent with sound business principles;
the PMA's goal is to generate revenue sufficient just to cover
their costs without making a profit or even adequate rate of return
on their investment. This means that the taxpayers are forced
to finance unprofitable businesses. Third, and perhaps most importantly,
the PMA's do not appear to recover all of the costs incurred 
in the production of electricity, directly contrary to the intention
of the legislation that created them. The reported costs do not
cover the real costs or, at least, postpone the recovery of these
costs to later periods. This problem is in part due to the fact
that the PMA's bookkeeping methods are not consistent with Generally
Accepted Accounting Principles (GAAP) as applied to private businesses.
Instead, the PMA's are subject to government accounting methods
and are audited under generally accepted auditing standards called
Government Auditing Standards. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">For example, WAPA depreciates its plants over
what appears to be an excessive period of 64 to 93 years (as opposed
to IOU's which use about 50 years). WAPA also uses the compound
interest method in which depreciation expenses are lower in the
earlier years of operation and higher in later years, which is
contrary to standard accounting practice. An analysis of WAPA's
1993 financial statements made by Deloitte &amp; Touche, LLP,
showed that using straight-line depreciation method over 50 years
(which appears to be close to actual depreciation) would result
in depreciation expense of $90 million, as compared to $34 million
reported in its financial statements. This implies that the true
costs of generating electricity are actually higher than the costs
reported by the PMA's.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Some costs of the federal hydro program are
not recovered due to the distorted allocation of costs for power
production and irrigation. For example,  with WAPA's Pick Sloan
Missouri Basin Program, part of power generation costs were to
be recovered from future irrigation project revenues. However,
many of originally proposed irrigation projects have not been
and probably never will be built. While common business sense
suggests shifting the allocation of these costs from irrigation
to power production with an increase WAPA's rates accordingly,
this has not happened. As a result, &quot;approximately $454 million
of the federal investment in the Pick Sloan Program's hydropower
facilities and water storage reservoir is unrecoverable unless
the project repayment allocations are revised&quot;.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Another reason for low rates are low costs
of borrowing capital from the federal government, which gives
the PMA's an implicit subsidy and an advantage not available to
all other utilities. The PMA's and the Corps or Bureau amortize
the federal investment in generation and transmission assets over
a period of 50 years with an average interest rate ranging from
2.7 to 4.6 percent (this contrasts with 8.1 percent average interest
rate on long-term debt held by IOU's in 1993). These interest
rates are actually lower than the interest rates at which the
federal government borrows money (average 6.9 % in 1995).<SUP>
</SUP> By lending to PMA's at lower interest rates than the rate
of borrowing from bondholders, the federal government cost taxpayers
an estimated $946 million during 1985-1994.  The artificially
low costs of capital allow PMA's to charge very low rates, rates
that would be unsustainable if they had to repay the investment
at market interest rates over a normal commercial amortization
period. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Another obvious, albeit implicit, subsidy for
PMA's is their exclusion from paying <I>any</I> federal, state
or local taxes. Such a subsidy costs taxpayers a significant amount
of money by shifting the tax burden normally assumed by the power
company shareholder and electricity ratepayer to the general taxpayer.
For example, in its bid for Phoenix Area assets of WAPA (this
area markets about 18 percent of WAPA power), Tucson Electric
Power Co. calculated that if the assets were sold to a taxpaying
entity, the U.S. Treasury would have received approximately $140
million in federal taxes, while the state of Arizona would have
received about $126 million in property taxes (the numbers are
in present value terms). The EOP Group study estimated the present
value of the federal income taxes paid by the privatized PMA's
would be $1.013 billion.</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Arial">Why Should the PMA's Be Privatized?</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">While all taxpayers subsidize the capital costs
of PMA's, it is only some consumers who receive the benefits of
PMA power in the form of lower electricity rates. It is not apparent
why people living in the Northeast should pay part of the electricity
bills for people living in the Southeast, or, at the extreme,
why the people on one side of Los Angeles (those who buy power
from Southern California Edison and pay 12.10&#162;/kWh) should
subsidize the electricity bills for people on the other side of
the city (those who buy power from the City of Los Angeles and
pay 9.85&#162;/kWh). The residents of Santa Clara CA (7.30&#162;/kWh)
and Palo Alto CA (5.46&#162;/kWh) receive an even better deal
from their municipal utilities distributing PMA power. Their neighbors
in San Francisco Bay Area pay 12.25&#162;/kWh to PG&amp;E which
has to bear full costs of capital and has no tax exemptions. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The federal power program (together with support
for rural electric cooperatives provided by the Rural Utilities
Service, formerly Rural Electrification Administration) was originally
intended primarily to serve farmers, households and small businesses
located in remote, rural, underdeveloped areas which investor-owned
utilities might not supply with power at reasonable prices. While
the ultimate consumers of PMA power are often rural households,
they are by no means their only customers. There are a number
of examples where the benefits of the federal power program now
flow to people who were not originally intended to receive them.
Places like Los Angeles, Palo Alto, Pasadena, Riverside, Sacramento
or Anaheim, California, Colorado Springs, Springfield, Missouri,
Lincoln, Nebraska and Kansas City have their own municipal utilities
that purchase power from the PMA's.  These communities can hardly
be called rural or poor or characterized as undesirable from the
IOU's perspective. Palo Alto, one of the richest communities in
the world, is a stunning example of governmental subsidies flowing
to the least needy people.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Many communities that may have fit the profile
of those intended to be aided by subsidized public power may once
have been rural, but over the years have become prosperous suburbs.
Still others have become popular resorts catering to wealthy clientele
(Hilton Head, South Carolina, Vail and Aspen, Colorado). </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Still other beneficiaries of subsidized public
power are huge corporations, especially in the extractive industries
such as mining, that gain an unfair competitive advantage based
not on merit but on subsidized power.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The electricity industry is undergoing unprecedented
change, moving from a tightly regulated industry to the competitive
one.  Eventually, consumers may be able to choose their electricity
supplier as they now do their long distance service provider.
But investor-owned utilities will find it difficult to compete
with companies whose power is cheaper <I>not</I> because they
are more efficient, but rather because they have access to government-subsidized
capital. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">It is not only subsidies that distort competition.
PMA's are also exempt from a variety of Federal Energy Regulatory
Commission (FERC) regulations. Under recently issued Order No.
888 on open transmission access, the PMA's are not required to
file open access tariffs like private utilities. They become subject
to the open access order only when they seek access to other utilities'
lines (the so called reciprocity provision). Because SWPA and
WAPA own substantial transmission systems, excluding these systems
from <I>full</I> open access requirements may actually chill wholesale
competition. By privatizing, the PMA's will be subject to the
same regulatory requirements as any other investor-owned utility
and will provide for a competitive marketplace. Privatization
of federal power assets is critical to creating a level playing
field for a competitive electricity industry in America. </FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">Technical Efficiency</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">It is commonly recognized that due to the lack
of profit imperative or risk of bankruptcy, government-owned enterprises
are usually less efficient than private firms. Even the Chairman
of President Clinton's Council of Economic Advisors begrudgingly
admits this in his recent book entitled <U>Whither Socialism</U>:
&quot;Yet I do think that the popular prejudice is, by and large,
correct: <I>Private sector activities, while not necessarily more
efficient, are on average so </I>[emphasis by the author]&quot;.
However, the empirical evidence relating to public power sector,
if interpreted superficially, may lead to the contrary conclusion.
Some studies find that the private power sector is not always
more efficient than the public sector. For example, William J.
Hausmann and John L. Neufeld: <U>Property Rights versus Public
Spirit, etc</U>., conclude that &quot;We constructed several measures
of productive efficiency&#133;We found that for every measure
examined, the municipally owned electric utilities were significantly
more efficient than their privately owned counterparts.&quot;
Or Lon L .Peters: <U>Attenuated Property Rights, etc</U>., state
that  &quot;almost all studies [in the utility industry] of costs
and efficiency found either no significant differences between
ownership types, or an advantage of some type in favor of publicly
owned publicly owned [nonprofit municipal] firms.&quot;</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">      Without addressing specifics of these
studies, we would like to emphasize that better performance of
publicly owned utilities is unlikely to be simply the result of
public ownership. Instead, together with others we would stress
the importance of <I>competition,</I> hard budget constraints<I>
</I>and the absence of government price <I>regulation </I>in shaping
the incentives for efficient performance of both public and private
firms. Indeed, rate of return regulation, as practiced in the
United States, has proven to provide very weak incentives for
managers of IOU's basically because it limits the rewards from
cost saving as well as the pain from inefficiency. It is not that
surprising that <I>unregulated</I> public utilities often do better
in this environment. Both public ownership and regulation dull
incentives and it is not surprising that in this choice between
two &quot;bads,&quot; public ownership at times turns out to dull
incentives less than cost of service regulation.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"> However, the U.S. electric industry is moving
away from regulation and toward competition.  In this new environment,
both public and private electric companies will be subject to
the same markets forces. On the question whether private or public
is better in this environment, it is appropriate to conclude with
Vickers and Yarrow that &quot;&#133;where competition is effective,
the available evidence suggests that private enterprise is generally
to be preferred on both internal efficiency grounds and, subject
to the qualification that other substantive market failures are
absent, social welfare grounds.&quot;</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Fortunately, the question of public/private
efficiency is less theoretical in the case of PMA's. Here we actually
have some limited data on the operations of hydro plants both
by the federal government and by privately owned utilities. Our
conclusion is that some federal government practices are clearly
less efficient than those of privately operated hydro plants.
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">Full Gate/Best Gate</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">PMA's power contracts are largely based on
capacity, and so it is advantageous to maximize output to avoid
the need to purchase capacity somewhere else. As a consequence,
the PMA/Corps plants are operated at Full Gate, which means that
water control gates in the turbine are opened to provide maximum
water flow and thus maximum output (in MW).  However, this is
less efficient than Best Gate, a regime normally used by investor-owned
utilities, in which the turbine water flow is set at the point
of peak turbine efficiency. This enables the highest possible
amount of potential energy in the form of accumulated water to
be turned into electric energy, while at Full Gate, some of the
water energy accumulated in the federal dams is wasted. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">A good example of this type of inefficiency
is suggested by a cursory analysis made of the four SEPA/Corps
of Engineers projects on the Alabama River Basin by Southern Company
(an investor-owned utility) to estimate the inefficiencies caused
by Full Gate operation. They found that, due to a loss of turbine
efficiency of about 7 percent,  the value of annual energy lost
is about $700,000. </FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">Outages</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Another inefficiency found in PMA operations
is their outage rates. The PMA's do not produce the maximum power
possible due to very long outages. Causes for this include the
added wear on units from continual Full Gate operations, generator
overheating and prolonged repair outages. The timing of these
outages is also inefficient. Unlike investor-owned utilities,
PMA's do not provide a reserve fund for major unit repair costs,
and funds for the repairs must come from Congress. Because of
this the PMA's cannot schedule their outages at optimal (i.e.
off-peak) periods. They are forced to make repairs when they receive
funds, often during summer peak periods. Non-optimally timed outages
represent an obvious loss of energy. They result in excess spillage
and increases in energy production from other, usually more costly
resources, in order to meet the peak load.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">At one point SEPA had about 800MW of hydro
capacity (or 26 percent of its installed capacity) either out
of service or forced to operate at less than full capacity because
of maintenance problems. This is in contrast to the industry average
outage rate of 8.7 percent for the past five years. As an extreme
example, unit #1 at Jones Bluff project was out of service from
March 1992 until August 1995, and unit #1 at Millers Ferry has
been out of service since June 1992. </FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">The Budget Impact</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Governments often privatize industries to receive
a quick &quot;windfall&quot; of cash to cover budget deficits.
For politicians, budgetary considerations may also be the driving
force behind privatization efforts of federal hydro assets. The
Clinton Administration's FY 1995 budget proposed to sell the PMA's
to their preference customers was clearly motivated by budgetary
factors. The Clinton proposal, because it involved selling the
PMA's to other governmental or quasi-governmental entities, was
unlikely to yield any of the efficiency gains true privatization
would confer, but it may still have had  favorable budgetary consequences.
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">With the sale of the PMA's, the government
would receive a lump-sum of revenue to help offset the budget
deficit and would be relieved from any future financial obligations
for the operation of PMA facilities. It would also receive corporate
income taxes from the privatized PMA's as well as income taxes
from their bondholders or shareholders.  The government would,
however, forego the revenue from the PMA's since the receipts
from PMA's deposited in the Treasury currently exceed the appropriations
as the PMA's are repaying their past debts. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The mathematics of the budgetary costs and
benefits is quite simple. Our estimate of the present value of
what the Treasury loses by privatizing is $3,386 million (the
assumptions we used tend to make this estimate higher than the
real number). If the privatization proposal described later is
adopted, the federal government will end up with at least $3,523
million from the sale of SEPA, SWPA and WAPA. The present value
of the stream of future taxes was estimated to be $1,013 million.
Thus the <I>net</I> budgetary benefit can be considered to be
$1,150. The fact that most of the benefit is realized in a lump
sum revenue makes privatization even more attractive to Congress
struggling with a deficit. It is also worth noting that, due to
the fact that the PMA's will be sold for a fixed price as a consequence
of the privatization mechanism described in Part 2, Congress has
an opportunity to adjust the revenue by simply moving the fixed
price up or down. </FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Arial">If There Are So Many Benefits,</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Arial">Why Haven't the PMA's Been
Privatized Yet?</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The first attempt to privatize the PMA's was
made by President Reagan in his FY 1987 budget proposal. As its
response, the 99<SUP>th</SUP> Congress imposed a prohibition on
the federal government to solicit or study any proposals to sell
the PMA's without specific congressional authorization. In its
FY1996 budget proposal, the Clinton Administration also suggested
divestiture of all PMA's except Bonneville. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The most recent effort to privatize the PMA's
was undertaken in September 1995 by the U.S. House Committee on
Resources. The Committee reported &quot;The Power Administration
Purchase Act,&quot; that would have eventually privatized SEPA
and its associated generation facilities to the highest bidder.
This effort apparently was stopped by traditional interest group
politics, including the objections of subsidized recreational
users of the water projects. The beneficiaries of the federal
hydropower program (i.e., the recipients of subsidized power as
well as beneficiaries of the other aspects of the water projects)
 have overridden the general interest of taxpayers - who paid
for the construction and operation of the dams, including the
assets of the PMA's, and who currently subsidize both power and
non-power benefits from the federal water projects. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The opponents of privatization usually make
three points. First, they point out that the PMA's traditionally
have been a source of inexpensive power and thus privatization
would lead to unjust rate increases that would hurt ordinary citizens.
While the likelihood of rate increases have been exaggerated (particularly
because there are surpluses of power throughout the country),
even if there were significant increases in PMA rates at the<I>
wholesale</I> level, the concern of privatization opponents over
rate increases at the consumer level is excessive. PMA power represents
a fairly small portion of all the  power distributed by co-ops
and munies to their ultimate customers - of all sources of power
used by preference customers in each market,  WAPA supplies only
12 percent, SWPA only 13 percent and SEPA only 5 percent.  Thus
increases in PMA rates would affect only a small portion of preference
customer's portfolios - which they could minimize by buying from
other suppliers. An EOP Group study for the Edison Electric Institute
estimated that the electricity bills of  93 percent of ultimate
residential buyers of SEPA power would not increase by more than
5 percent; increases no higher than 5 percent would be experienced
by about 73 percent of SWPA customers and 90 percent of WAPA customers.
From the data provided in the EOP Group Study, we have calculated
the average monthly bill increase for a household served by a
muni or co-op to be $1.50 for SEPA, $3 for SWPA and $1.10 for
WAPA. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Second, the opposition stresses that the PMA's
currently yield a positive return to the U.S. Treasury, and that
by privatizing the federal government would be deprived of a valuable
source of revenue. As mentioned above, the PMA's have been rather
an expensive venture because the interest on their debt is lower
than the interest on the national debt. However, even if we do
not take this into account, any privatization that brings revenue
higher than the present value of the expected PMA contributions
is desirable from the fiscal point of view. As we show in the
previous section, our privatization plan satisfies this condition.
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Third, the opponents of PMA privatization have
been stressing that federal water projects are multi-purpose and
that the new owners would fail to provide adequate irrigation,
recreation, navigation and fish and wildlife protection. What
the opponents conveniently fail to mention is that there are 366
hydroelectric projects throughout the country operated by investor-owned
utilities, plus 90 additional projects operated by private non-electric
entities, subject to FERC license, and that all of these, by their
very nature, provide benefits other than power. Table 2 presents
the extent of private hydroelectric production in four regions
of the United States. The private sector is able to build and
manage even large projects -  there are 77 private projects whose
installed capacity exceeds 50MW, and among them 7 projects with
capacity over 500MW. The non-power functions of private dams are
thoroughly scrutinized through the FERC licensing process, which
also applies to public non-federal entities. However the licensing
process may be in imperfect way to balance the power and non-power
interests.  It is important to point here that all relevant parties
(farmers, fishermen, boaters, public authorities) have input into
the licensing process and their concerns are included in the conditions
of license. There is no reason to believe that the new owners
of PMA/Corps facilities would do a worse job than the present
private dam owners.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
