</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">However, even if a large number of households
do not sell their warrants to the highest bidder or that the costs
of acquiring all of the necessary warrants this way are excessive
(there is no evidence that this would be the case), all is not
lost. As Table 3 indicates, a very large share of all warrants
will be held by commercial and industrial consumers. In fact,
in WAPA, if you take the combined share of commercial and industrial
warrant holders (who we assume are quite likely to sell to the
highest bidder) and the federal government (which will under our
plan have to sell to the highest bidder), the highest bidder could
potentially control over 58 percent without acquiring any warrants
from households. Also, because of uneven distribution of warrants
<I>inside </I>customer classes, it is sufficient in order to gain
a controlling interest to buy warrants from a relatively small
number of end users who have relatively large warrant holdings.
Both logic and experience suggest that the highest bidder will
not have a problem in gaining control of PMA assets.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The experience of the British privatization
program is particularly instructive on this point. One of its
objectives was to achieve more widespread stock ownership in Great
Britain. In some cases (British Telecom, Trustee Savings Bank,
British Gas and British Airways) the shareholders were encouraged
to retain their shares, typically by the promise of free bonus
shares after three years. Thatcher era privatization did increase
the number of individual shareholders enormously - from 5 percent
of adult population before privatization to 20-23 percent in 1987.
As for the concentration of ownership in particular companies,
the diffusion of ownership was less enduring. Within one year
after privatization the number of shareholders in Cable and Wireless
fell from 150,000 to 26,000, and in British Aerospace the number
had fallen from 158,000 to 27,000. Even corporations with incentives
for small shareholders to retain their shares experienced huge
drop shareholder numbers. When British Telecom was privatized
in 1984, it had 2.3 million shareholders. In 1987 it had only
1.4 million. More than one million people initially bought British
Airways stock while only three months after the sale it had 420,000
shareholders.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Like the Thatcher era privatization in Britain,
our privatization plan will create a large number of potential
shareholders and we expect a similarly rapid and dramatic fall
off in the number of shareholders after privatization. In fact,
since warrants will be distributed without any action being taken
by the warrant holders, many of these potential shareholders are
likely to be less interested in becoming shareholders than were
their British counterparts (who had to apply for their shares).
The distribution of warrants to many individuals who are only
marginally interested in stock ownership should make for an even
more active market in warrants than may be expected from the British
experience. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The capital markets in this country are very
well developed and creative, and it may be that advertisements
for warrants will develop even <I>before </I>the Congress approves
this privatization plan. If this were to happen it might prove
very useful since there is a chicken and egg problem in PMA privatization
- public power consumers are opposed to privatization because
they fear rate increases and do not see any offsetting gains.
Of course they cannot see any gains until they have their warrants,
which they cannot get because they are blocking privatization
proposals in Congress. The prospective buyers are able to cut
the Gordian knot by signaling to end users that they would make
money through PMA privatization. Advertisements for &quot;warrants
if issued&quot; might dramatically change the political dynamics
surrounding PMA privatization. It would foster an attitude that
privatization is something from which ordinary citizens can actually
gain.</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Rules Concerning the Rates Need to Be Made
Clear</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">If the end users are to receive the maximum
value for their warrants (or eventually their shares), potential
investors need to have a clear idea about how much the PMA's are
going to be worth. That is, they need to know what rates they
will be allowed to charge their wholesale customers after taking
control of the PMA's, or at least under what rules the rates will
be determined. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">This question of what rates to allow is a classic
dilemma facing every government that is considering privatizing
a regulated industry. The lower the allowed rates, the lower the
privatization revenue. The higher the rates, the less customers
gain from privatization. Fortunately, the warrant approach mitigates
the dilemma. Since warrants are exchanged at a fixed strike price,
government revenue is not effected by rule considerations as long
as the rates are high enough to assure that the value of the PMA
is higher than the strike price. However, higher rates for the
PMA's would enable the government to set higher strike prices.
The correlation between end users' well being and higher rates
is also weak since any rate increases translate to a higher value
for warrants. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Since under a warrant plan rate changes are
basically compensated by changes in warrant value, we think that
Congress should focus on efficiency when deciding on post-privatization
rates. However, the end users' gains will be also affected by
clarity of the rules. If those who would like to gain control
of the PMA's are risk averse, they will be willing to pay less
for the warrants if they are uncertain about the rates they will
be allowed to charge. Hence the rules under which rates will be
determined need to be made clear and should not be altered during
the course of privatization. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">What should the rules be like? First, there
is no economic reason why Congress should continue to give some
wholesalers preferential access to hydropower.  Second, instead
of trying to dictate specific rates, Congress should take into
account the fact that wholesale power markets have become sufficiently
competitive and little regulation is actually needed.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">From the &quot;level the playing field&quot;
point of view, the solution most readily available is to make
the post-privatized PMA's subject to the same FERC wholesale rate
regulations that apply to all IOU's. However, such a solution
has a shortcoming: It is very unclear what the rates would actually
be under such a proposal. FERC may be ordered to base them on
historical costs, but in that case, rates would probably only
cover actual costs if the strike price was set below book value
as the capital costs of PMA acquisition would reflect market,
not government-subsidized interest rates. Moreover, in this case
the FERC would be prolonging the PMA pricing problem. On the other
hand, reflecting the capital costs of acquisition in the rate
base creates a circularity problem, that is, the rates would be
higher the more the new owners paid for the PMA's. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">We think Congress should rely on markets rather
than regulators by letting the PMA's charge market rates. Markets
will set a limit on the rates that the privatized PMA's will be
able to charge, and in this case market prices will be more predictable
than regulators. Intervention might be needed when a PMA has significant
market power. This may be a problem in those areas where the PMA's
transmission lines are constrained and in this case FERC might
regulate rates using a benchmark approach. We think that requiring
PMA's to charge no more than market rate prevailing in a given
region in a given time is a sufficiently general solution to the
rate setting problem.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The position of existing contracts with preference
customers is problematic. The current contracts are written for
a very long period (many of them do not expire until well beyond
2000) and usually contain cost-based formula, disadvantages of
which were discussed above. We would suggest that the federal
government simply define market based rates as cost based rates
for the purpose of these contracts. As compensation for this action
the federal government should allow the preference customers to
back out of any of these contracts. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Finally it also should be noted that in order
to create a level playing field in the electricity markets, the
privatized PMA's should become subject to the same tax laws and
security laws as any other business, as well as to FERC's open
access transmission requirements.</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">The Importance of PUHCA Repeal </FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">It is worth stressing that any cost or restriction
on the prospective buyers of the PMA's and any restriction of
the rights of end users to freely sell their warrants will lead
to lower prices for warrants, lower gains to end users, and reduce
the political attractiveness of privatization.  For many investor-owned
utilities buying stock in a privatized PMA is complicated by the
Public Utility Holding Company Act of 1935 (PUHCA). Another New
Deal legacy, PUHCA will limit the number of buyers and complicate
efforts to gain control of the newly privatized PMA's. By restricting
the market for corporate control PUHCA lowers the potential price
of the PMA's.  This is just one of many reasons why PUHCA should
be repealed. However, it may happen that PUHCA as such is not
repealed at the time the PMA privatization legislation is pending
in Congress, and it would not be wise to either privatize the
PMA's without PUHCA repeal or postpone privatization until after
PUHCA is repealed. The remedy to this is to make acquisition of
PMA's exempt from all provision of PUHCA.</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Political Variables</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">There are a number of issues that Congress
will have to address if they are to implement a privatization
proposal similar to ours.  While these issues have limited efficiency
consequences, they could dramatically affect the distribution
of benefits from such a privatization </FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Warrant Eligibility</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Arial">.
First, it will be necessary to specify the formula for distributing
warrants among the end users. The basic choice is whether the
calculations should be based on physical units (power sales in
kWh) or monetary units (power sales in dollars). The distinction
would be irrelevant if all classes of customers faced the same
electricity rates. But rates differ significantly between the
various classes of users. Generally it is the residential customers
who pay the highest prices per kWh, while large industrial users
and public users pay the lowest unit prices. While we do not have
aggregate data on both physical sales and revenues from sales
by customer classes for PMA's, we do have such information for
all utilities, presented in Table 4.</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">TABLE 4:  SHARE OF POWER SALES
AND REVENUES AMONG ULTIMATE CUSTOMER CLASSES</FONT></CENTER>
<TABLE BORDERCOLOR=#808080 BORDER=1>
