</TABLE>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The percentages in the Table 4 indicate how
the warrants (and hence profits) would be distributed among different
customer classes, provided of course that the same sales distribution
ratios apply to PMA's as other utilities. The choice between basing
the distribution of warrants on physical sales or on revenues
from sales has significant implications for the gains from privatization
among residential and industrial consumers. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Our recommendation is to base the allocation
formula on monetary values and not physical units, as this will
make the gains more visible to the residential users without impairing
the visibility of gains to the industrial users. The gains to
industrial users are already visible due to the absolute magnitude
of electricity consumption while the perceived gains to residential
customers needs all the magnification possible. We base all of
our following estimates of end user stock ownership and gains
on revenues, not physical sales.</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Firm/Non-Firm Power<B>.  </B></FONT></B><FONT FACE="Arial">Another
aspect of PMA privatization that has similar distributional consequences
is whether to count only firm power sales or both firm and non-firm
power sales for warrant eligibility. Wholesale customers receive
firm and non-firm power from the PMA's in varying proportions.
For example, while non-firm WAPA sales in 1993 represented only
about 2 percent of power sold to municipal utilities, or 4 percent
in the case of cooperatives, they made up 45 percent of power
sold to investor-owned utilities. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Basing warrant eligibility only on firm power
sales would reduce by half the number of shares IOU customers
would receive, without increasing significantly the number of
shares available to other end users. Not only because of this,
but mostly because of the fact that customers are ultimately billed
for firm as well as non-firm power, we recommend to include both
firm and non-firm power into calculations of warrant eligibility.</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Reference Time Period.</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Arial">
A more subtle problem Congress will face is the choice of the
reference time period to be used for the calculation of warrant
eligibility. Because of annual fluctuations in electricity consumption,
basing warrant eligibility on consumption in the past several
years instead of only the most recent year spreads the gains more
equally among consumers. It also lowers the gains to those who
moved into PMA power areas only recently (and thus enjoyed the
subsidized power for a shorter time period), while enabling those
who already moved out of PMA power areas to capture some of the
gains - even though these people are not going to be affected
by any potential rate increase resulting from removing the subsidies.
In this case, there is a minor efficiency impact: Using several
years as a base requires more sales data and analysis and thus
is more costly to calculate. For economic as well as political
reasons we would suggest using only a single year (perhaps the
last calendar or fiscal year) as a reference year. </FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Strike Price.</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Arial">
A key issue in implementing our privatization plan is the strike
price. The revenue to the Treasury from PMA privatization is the
number of shares times the strike price. The higher the strike
price, the larger the contribution PMA privatization will make
to budget deficit reduction. On the other hand, since the gains
to the end users are equal to the difference between the expected
market value of the shares and the strike price, placing too much
emphasis on the budgetary impact of PMA privatization will dissipate
the gains of end users and reduce their interest in the process
- the interest of people who we plan to assign much of the privatization
gains and who we hope will be the principal source of support
for privatization. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Congress may pick virtually any value between
zero and the expected market value as the strike price, and there
really is no efficiency argument for one value over any other.
At one extreme, it may set the strike price at zero, by which
it would transfer the entire value of the PMA's to the end users
and investors, without any direct contribution to the budget.
(There will, of course, be an indirect contribution from federal
taxes paid by PMA's and their shareholders or bondholders in the
future.) At the other extreme, it may choose the future market
value, by which it would collect the same amount of money as in
the auction to the highest bidder, leaving the end users only
with possible rate increases but no offsetting gains.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">We suggest two basic approaches to follow when
setting the strike price, and choosing between them depends on
the primary objective of privatization. If the emphasis is on
making sure that privatization does not hurt consumers, then it
makes sense to set the strike price at such a level that the gains
the average end user makes by selling his warrants would just
equal the net present value of the average expected bill increase.
What is left after compensating consumers goes to the budget.
If the emphasis is that PMA privatization be (at least) budget-neutral,
then the strike price should just equal the net present value
of the future contributions of PMA's to the budget (or more),
giving to end users what is left after satisfying budgetary needs.
Fortunately, our estimates conclude that there is no direct conflict
between the two objectives.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Following are four specific strike prices based
on the approach just described:</FONT>
<P>
<U><FONT FACE="Arial">Budget Neutral (BN).</FONT></U><FONT FACE="Arial">
Probably the easiest way to set the strike price is to have it
equal to the present value of the revenue from PMA's foregone
by privatization. This makes the budget just break-even, assuming
there will be no income taxes in the future. According to our
estimates, the Budget Neutral strike price is $688 million for
SEPA, $389 million for SWPA and $2,309 million for WAPA - see
Table 5. The BN strike price discounts (SPD) are 0.636, 0.786
and 0.554,  respectively, which means that about 64 percent, 79
percent and 55 percent of the total value of SEPA, SWPA and WAPA
will end up in the hands of end users.</FONT>
<P>
<U><FONT FACE="Arial">Budget Neutral with Taxes (BNT).</FONT></U><FONT FACE="Arial">
The approach just described actually overpays the federal government.
As the government will also be receiving income taxes after the
PMA's are privatized, it can afford to lower the strike price
by the present value of future taxes without harming the budget.
Since it is lower, the BNT strike price also has the advantage
of making privatization more attractive to end users.</FONT>
<P>
<U><FONT FACE="Arial">Consumer Neutral (CN).</FONT></U><FONT FACE="Arial">
According to our calculations, the average residential customer
of a municipal or cooperative utility would suffer a 1.87 percent
(or $18.5 per year) increase in their bill in the case of SEPA,
4.07 percent (or $36.5) in the case of SWPA and 1.96 percent (or
$12.6) in the case of WAPA. The present value of these average
bill increases over 20 years is $172, $339 and $117, respectively.
In order to compensate consumers, the strike price discount must
be high enough to allow the value of warrants to be at least equal
to these values. To achieve this, following our estimates of the
gains available to end users from privatization (presented and
analyzed in a comprehensive manner in Part 3 and Appendix 3),
the Consumer Neutral (CN) strike price must be 70.1 percent below
market value for SEPA, 65.8 percent below market value for SWPA,
and 32.7 percent below market value for WAPA (see Table 5). Setting
the strike price at these (or any lower) values guarantees that
the end users of PMA power are no worse off (or even better off)
after privatization.</FONT>
<P>
<U><FONT FACE="Arial">Balanced Gains (BG).</FONT></U><FONT FACE="Arial">
As it is apparent from Table 5, the Consumer Neutral strike price
is higher than the Budget Neutral with Taxes strike price for
all three PMA's and is also higher than the Budget Neutral strike
price for SWPA and WAPA. This means that after perfectly compensating
the end users and the budget, there is still some value left.
Here the net privatization gains become apparent both to end users
and the budget makers. By setting the strike somewhere between
BNT and CN,<I> both</I> the end users and the Treasury actually
profit from privatization, and Congress has a &quot;bargaining
space&quot; within the BNT and CN belt for negotiation over who
should get bigger piece of the pie. The most natural suggestion
for us to recommend is to split this pie equally (hence Balanced
Gains). The end users of SEPA, SWPA and WAPA power will receive
about 73 percent, 78 percent and 50 percent of the total value
of these companies, while the Treasury will receive $3,523 million,
which is actually higher than the Budget Neutral (without taxes)
strike price, hence eliminating any uncertainty about future taxes.
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The Balanced Gains is the strike price on which
all our estimates of the value of warrants presented in this paper
are based. We think that due to its &quot;equal sharing&quot;
character it is also very likely to be politically attractive.
</FONT>
<P>
