<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Federal Warrants.  </FONT></B><FONT FACE="Arial">Finally,
it is important to recognize that a considerable part of PMA power
is consumed by public entities, including federal ones. For example,
as we can see in Table 3, federal agencies (mainly the Department
of Defense) purchase for their ultimate use almost 9 percent of
all the power distributed by WAPA. Other examples of direct public
users include many state universities and hospitals especially
in the Western states. In addition, thousands of public authorities
purchase PMA power indirectly for purposes like street lighting
through their municipal or cooperative electric utility. Treating
all end users equally implies the distribution of warrants to
the public users who would then decide whether they want to sell
their warrants or purchase shares of the privatized PMA. The latter,
at least as it applies to the federal government, would not facilitate
the federal government's retrenchment from the economy. Shifting
ownership of PMA's from the Department of Energy to the Department
of Defense is not privatization. Shifting some of the ownership
to state and local entities is also hardly privatization, but
in the spirit of federalism the decision of whether these entities
continue to hold shares of a PMA is best left at the state and
local level.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">We propose the following treatment of ownership
&quot;rights&quot; accruing to the federal government: Congress
can and should insist that all warrants assigned to the federal
agencies be pooled together for each PMA and sold in a direct
sale to the highest bidder. It is important that this auction
takes place before warrants are distributed to end users or at
least before they are redeemed for shares, so that the auction
provides clear information about the real value of PMA shares.
Such a sale of warrants would bring at least an additional $319
million to the Treasury, provided that strike price is set at
BG (this estimate includes direct federal purchases only). As
for non-federal warrant holders, we believe that they will find
it preferable to sell their warrants and not to become shareholders.
Their consumption of PMA power is too low to allow them to exercise
relevant control over the privatized PMA's, and selling warrants
does not require them to spend money from their budgets, while
buying shares does. However, as we note above, this is a local
issue and it is best solved at that level. After exchanging warrants
for shares, the federal government should also auction off the
shares that were not claimed by warrant holders.</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5 FACE="Arial">PART 3</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5 FACE="Arial">WHO GAINS AND HOW MUCH THEY
GAIN UNDER THE BLOCK-SHADEGG PRIVATIZATION PLAN?</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">When privatization legislation is enacted and
warrants distributed, all end users will focus on one question:
&quot;How much money can I get for my warrants?&quot; Here we
show that our plan will generate several billion dollars in gains
for households, businesses, and state and local governments. Depending
on the value of the strike price, all current PMA customers can
earn substantial amounts of money in gains as a direct result
of privatization. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">This section shows how much the average business,
household and public agency could make by selling their warrants,
assuming that the strike price is set at the BG. In reaching our
estimates, we followed our recommendations from the previous section
regarding warrant eligibility and non-firm power. Our estimates
are based on 1993 sales data, and are in 1995 dollars. The estimations
of the market value of the PMA's were taken from an EOP Group
Study, which presumes that the PMA's would raise prices to the
levels prevalent in their geographic areas. Since the time of
that study, wholesale electricity prices have generally been falling,
which would result in somewhat lower market value of the PMA's.
On the other hand, the study did not account for any efficiency
improvements, which have an offsetting effect on market value.
 Detailed information on potential gains, including the effect
of different strike prices, is given in Appendix 2.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Average consumer gains under the Block-Shadegg
plan are given in Table 6. The average gain for nearly all customer
types for each PMA is over $100. Only the average residential
consumer of WAPA power earns less than $100, and this is due to
a large number of IOU customers who receive PMA power. The average
residential customer of a co-op or muni that buys power from WAPA
could earn an amount comparable the residential customers in other
PMA areas. As Table 6 shows, the average commercial consumer of
PMA power could gain several hundred dollars by selling their
warrant, and the average industrial user over $10,000. It should
be remembered that warrant holders can obtain these gains either
by selling their warrant, or by exercising the warrant and selling
the stock. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">End users' gains vary significantly depending
on their local electricity supplier. Co-op and muni customers,
those who ostensibly would suffer most from &quot;rate shock&quot;,
stand to gain substantially more than customers of IOUs. The concentration
of relatively larger average shareholdings in the hands of the
consumers served by munies and co-ops (in WAPA area there are
nearly 12 million households served by IOU's compared to about
4 million served by munies and co-ops) should create an easily
distinguishable group with a strong political interest in privatization.
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Co-op and muni customers are worth focusing
on because in the past they have been most resistant to the sale
of the PMA's. Table 7 shows that the average customer of a muni
or co-op will earn at least $100 through the Block-Shadegg plan.
The largest winners, on average, are consumers of SWPA power.
The average household ultimately buying SWPA electricity through
its muni or co-op could gain $401 dollars, the average commercial
business above $1,200, and the average industrial user about $39,000.
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">As can be seen in Table 7, the size of the
gain among co-op and muni customers varies broadly. The average
gain to the top 10 percent of warrant holders is much larger,
at least several hundred percent, than the bottom 10 percent.
However, except in the case of WAPA's residential consumers, the
majority of warrant holders still gain several hundred dollars.
Moreover the aggregate numbers hide the fact that there are some
very large potential winners under the Block-Shadegg plan. SEPA
contains over two dozen munies whose residential customers gain
more than $400. There are over two dozen munies and co-ops each
in SWPA and WAPA whose household customers will obtain more than
$1000. The largest winners are the customers of the municipal
utility that serves Manitou, Oklahoma. The average household there
could gain $3,958. (In Appendix 3, we present a list of munies
and co-ops whose average households are estimated to  gain more
than $400.)</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The data we had available allowed us to estimate
only the gains to <I>average</I> residential, commercial, industrial
and public end user served by a particular muni or co-op. It did
not allow us to find out what the distribution of gains is <I>within
</I>customer classes served by a particular muni or co-op. Thus
all distribution information presented here is based on comparison
of average gains for each muni or co-op. This does not appear
to reduce the value of the information that we present, especially
in the case of residential customers. The differences in electricity
consumption between high and low income households are much smaller
than the differences in contribution of PMA power in munies' and
co-ops' power needs. Also the distribution pattern for residential
customers can be assumed similar for all munies and co-ops. Hence
the decisive factor for the size of gains is the share of PMA
power in preference customers' power supply. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">In case of commercial and industrial end users,
the differences in average gains between munies and co-ops are
apparently caused not only by different shares of PMA power but
also by much greater differences in electricity consumption by
these end users. There are several industrial customers who, having
a high electricity consumption and being supplied by a muni or
co-op with a large share of PMA power, have gains exceeding $1,000,000.
Also note that our estimates were based on sales to commercial
and industrial <I>meters;</I> many companies have several meters
in different locations so their gains are actually more concentrated
than our estimates. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Finally, it is worth mentioning the gains that
can be obtained by state and local agencies. Unfortunately our
data allow us to identify these customers only in the WAPA area
because only WAPA sells its power directly to some public agencies
(all three PMA's have a handful of ultimate public end users supplied
by munies and co-ops). Organizations like the University of California
at Davis, the University of Nebraska, the North Dakota Mill and
Elevator Association, and the Fergus Falls Hospital in Minnesota
have the potential to earn hundreds of thousands or even millions
of dollars under the Block-Shadegg plan. These agencies are highly
visible interest groups and will be certain to get the attention
of their representatives in Washington. They would add a weighty
impetus to privatization. </FONT>
