</TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">34</FONT></TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">0</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">638</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=197><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Consumption as % of Total</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">68.97%</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">25.71%</FONT></TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">5.33%</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">0.00%</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">100.00%</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=197><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Gains to a Customer Class ($)</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">379,647</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">141,504</FONT></TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">29,336</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">0</FONT></TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">550,488</FONT>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=197><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">AVG Gains ($)</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">660</FONT></TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">3,144</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">29,336</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">0</FONT></TD><TD WIDTH=85><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">882</FONT>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">In some special cases, other adjustments were
necessary.  Specifically:<BR>
</FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">In calculating the gains of TVA's end users
(TVA is one of SEPA's customers), only those end users who buy
power directly from TVA were counted as eligible for warrants.
Those who buy TVA (and consequently SEPA) power via their muni
or co-op were not included in our estimates. </FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Similarly, when calculating purchases of
PMA power by munies or co-ops (except those operating in TVA service
area), only direct purchases and purchases from wholesale public
or cooperative utilities were included. Thus, our calculation
does not include cases such as where a PMA sells to an IOU and
then the IOU sells to a muni that also buys directly from a PMA.
It is a policy question where to draw the bright line in calculating
warrant eligibility. We never go beyond one intermediate sale
in our calculations. </FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">For some co-ops, the only information available
to us was PMA power (measured in MWh) as a share of total power
needs.  To estimate how much power (measured in $) they actually
bought from the PMA's, we multiplied the physical share of PMA
power by their revenue from total sales to ultimate customers.
This would be an exact estimate if all munies and coops were buying
PMA power as well as other power for the same prices and if they
did not charge any markup on the purchase price. To adjust for
at least some of the inaccuracies of such an estimate, we multiplied
the estimated PMA power purchases of all co-ops for which we did
not have the exact data by a coefficient that transformed them
so that the sum of both directly available and estimated power
purchases was equal to total PMA sales. These numbers were then
used as an  input in the gains calculation. </FONT>
</UL>
<P>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Arial">APPENDIX 3<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
