<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>	What American Voters Called for Last November  
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> 
<blockquote><ul>
<a href="/pff/"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">For Immediate Release</FONT>
<Br>
<FONT FACE="Arial">        August 20, 1996</FONT>
<FONT FACE="Arial">    <BR>
</FONT>
<br>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Contact:  Rick O'Donnell</FONT>
<br>
<FONT FACE="Arial">202/289-8928<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><I><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Arial">N E W S    R E L E A S
E</FONT></B></I></CENTER>
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER><U><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Arial">Congressional  Staffers Hear
Critique of Schaefer Bill<BR>
</FONT></U></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Legislation currently being considered in the
House to deregulate America's electric energy industry would fail
to create a truly competitive electricity market, Michael Block,
Senior Fellow at The Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation, told the
WEST Associates Congressional Energy Forum yesterday.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">At the August 18-20 conference in Santa Fe,
Block outlined principles that should guide efforts to replace
America's regulated electric energy industry with a competitive
market system.   The principles Block outlined included:<p>
</FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Objective of reform should be a competitive
market in electric energy, not choice per se.</FONT>
</UL>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"></FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Market discipline should be the regulatory
mechanism of choice.</FONT>
</UL>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"></FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Natural monopoly arguments about any activity
should require proof &quot;beyond a reasonable doubt.&quot;</FONT>
</UL>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"></FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">States rights should stop at the Commerce
Clause.</FONT>
</UL>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"></FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Antitrust oversight and light-handed regulation
should be preferred to so called &quot;incentive regulation,&quot;
which itself should be preferred to cost-of-service regulation.</FONT>
</UL>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"></FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Transition costs should be allocated, to
the maximum extent possible, in a manner that provides appropriate
incentives.</FONT>
</UL>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"></FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">The Federal government should seize every
opportunity to foster competitive restructuring at the state level.</FONT>
</UL>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"></FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Private property rights should be respected
and restructuring efforts should emphasize voluntarism.</FONT>
</UL>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"></FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Environmental concerns should, to the maximum
extent possible, be addressed through market mechanisms.</FONT>
</UL>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"></FONT>
<P>
<br>
<FONT FACE="Arial">August 20, 1996</FONT>
<P>
<br>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">The nuclear power dilemma should be addressed
in any restructuring effort.</FONT>
</UL>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"></FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Abolish FERC as we know it.  Whatever regulation
remains necessary should be done at the state and local, not Federal,
level.</FONT>
</UL>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"></FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Federal ownership of power assets is the
least preferred alternative; private ownership is the most preferred
alternative.</FONT>
</UL>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"></FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Social and redistributive policy should
be accomplished using explicit subsidies and taxes.</FONT>
</UL>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"></FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Outmoded Federal regulations should be
repealed.</FONT>
</UL>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"></FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Reform at the Federal level should begin
immediately.</FONT>
</UL>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Block examined how legislation (H.R. 3790)
introduced by Representative Dan Schaefer (R-CO), chairman of
the House Commerce subcommittee on energy, measures up to the
principles, and concluded that the Schaefer legislation does not
go far enough in terms of deregulation, fails to take a skeptical
enough view of Federal regulation, and contains some anti-competitive
provisions such as those mandating costly renewable energy sources.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">In a recent study, Block, who heads the Foundation's
project on &quot;Creating Competitive Markets in Electric Power,&quot;
argued that a better approach to energy deregulation this year
would be to repeal the Public Utility Holding Company Act of 1935
because it is hindering state efforts to reform energy markets.
 The study, <I>The Competition Revolution and the Market for Energy</I>,
argues that PUHCA repeal would get deregulation off to an immediate
start.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation is a
private, non-profit, non-partisan idea center established in 1993
to create a positive vision of the future founded in the historic
principles of the American Idea.  It brings together a diverse
group of thinkers and policy experts and shares their work with
the American people through seminars, conferences, publications
and broadcasts.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT FACE="Arial"># # #<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></CENTER>
