</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>Analog to Digital--That Is the Issue, Not Telecommunications -- PFF</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<h1>Analog to Digital--That Is the Issue, Not Telecommunications</h1>
<p>
<b>By G. A. Keyworth, II, Chairman</b>
<i>Remarks at the National Policy Forum's Megaconference<br>
on Telecommunications Law Reform: Reinventing Competition<br>
March 8, 1995<br>
Washington, D.C.</i>
<p>
Since I'm privileged to speak early on the agenda, let me begin with some
general perspectives on the whole issue of telecommunications law reform.
First, there is something terribly wrong with the whole language of the
debate. Look at the confusion the term "superhighway" has caused. With this
analogy to centrally planned, limited-access arteries it's hardly a
surprise that the new bogeyman of anti-process is the information have-not.

<P>
There's new life given to the anachronism of "universal service," as if
there were no new technologies blurring the cost-gap between urban and
rural telephony or, alternatively, as if we were discussing subsidizing
television viewing. Even the meaning of the word "competition" is softened
in that debate, sort of like golf, with various handicaps passed out to
contenders--by bureaucrats. One would almost think that regional phone
companies and cable-TV companies were still "natural monopolies" or that
the widespread erosion of barriers to entry was merely a myth. (Just ask
<a href = http://www.ibm.com>IBM</a>!)
<P>
Interpreting a central theme of Nick Negroponte's excellent and insightful
new book Being Digital, these are analog solutions to problems that are
inherently digital. This interpretation is much more, I believe, than an
arcane technical distinction. Analog communications are fundamentally
different than digital communications. The means of analog communications
are specific to each application, like wires for voice, broadcast for
radio, or even bicycles for newspaper delivery. In short, analog
communications are a monopolist's and regulator's dream. Digital
communications, however, by their nature, merge applications, such as
voice, TV and data on a single fiber, or paging and voice on a single
cellular radio system. Digital communications are a monopolist's and
regulator's nightmare.
<P>
The analog world is one where economies of scale still prevail, where to
have an installed base and to be big is to be successful; conversely, the
digital world is composed of narrow, but tall, niche industries, ruled by
Darwinian competition for each new product generation, and where and
installed base is as often a disadvantage as an asset. In short, the
digital world looks like today's computer industry, and the more
far-sighted communications companies recognize it as a factor in their
future, too.
<P>
Yet the debate over telecommunications reform sounds suspiciously analog.
This fundamental distinctions between the nature of yesterday's highly
regulated analog telephone industry, and tomorrow's digital communications
is largely absent in that debate. In fact, I would characterize virtually
all of the government's efforts at reform to date as analog. Somehow, we
need to change the language of the debate, and we need to pursue reform
that is digital in nature, drawing from the one role model we have--the
computer industry.
<P>
The societal objectives we seek in this endeavor are, of course, enhancing
economic growth and empowering individuals. And, again, what better role
model do we have than the computing sector. The race for leadership in
computing, concern over which was largely responsible in the 1980s for
making the word competitiveness part of our daily lexicon, is, for the
moment, over. And we Americans won that race. No "Fifth Generation Computer
Project" in Japan nor "Eureka" program in Europe affected the outcome, at
least not as was intended. Although hotly contested, we won that race "fair
and square," simply by providing the value customers wanted, at an
affordable price. And not least, we won by being a nations of people quick
to adapt to a new technology. The reward was good jobs, and rejuvenation of
our wealth generating machine. But it also gave new meaning to that second
objective--the empowerment of individuals. It gave us the hacker, a computer
-empowered individual who is both productive, and very American. It gave
stimulus to self-employment, and enabled the decentralized organization.
<P>
The computer industry is the industrial personification of things
digital--as things are becoming but not as they were. Moreover, it has
shown us just how well equipped we are, as a society, to confront progress,
with optimism. But the communications industry remains, in the view of most
Americans, far more as things were, not as things are becoming. And I'm
afraid that too much of today's telecommunications policy debate adds fuel
to the flames of that perception.
<P>
As I delve into the rich media treatment of telecommunications policy and
the information superhighway, I am often left with the impression that
breaking the local access monopoly in voice telephony, and adding a few
hundred more cable channels, with a dash of interactivity, will somehow,
inexplicably, lead us to a better world. The problem is that the hardly
dynamic metaphor telecommunications fails to support the promises, and the
far more dynamic metaphor of computing, that could, is notably absent.
<P>
Let me try to describe two ways people view computing. One perspective has
computing, whether in the guise of PCs, High Definition or Direct Broadcast
TV, 32-bit games, or embedded in Automatic Teller Machines or assembly
lines, as the technology that is reshaping our time. While some older
people are still intimidated by the mere work "computer," young people take
them for granted. And everyone equates computing with today, not yesterday.
Another sees computing as the most dynamic part of our job- and
wealth-generation-- machines, an American success story that is giving new
vigor to manufacturing, distribution, as well as to our rapidly growing
service sector. Either way, people view computers, increasingly, as the
essential tools of our time. And it is not such a big step to show those
same people that connecting all those computers together into a digital
communications system is simply the next, logical step. To me, that's the
"beef" of the telecommunications debate, and the challenge in
telecommunications reform.
<P>
Let me use two examples to show how the content of the debate needs to
change if we are to make real progress toward "digital legislation." One
pertains to the apparent fascination with managing how regional telephone
companies, long distance operators, cellular operators, and cable-TV
companies will offer new services, and compete with each other. This
fascination seems to pervade the FCC and much of The Congress--and not only
among Democrats. The basis for that fascination stems from those analog
tenets--that big is strong, and that an installed base is an unfair
advantage. The counter-argument, from digital experience, is that digital
technologies are moving too fast to predict rejuvenating effects of new
technology. The digital fascination would fasten upon making entry to new
players easier. To me, this is far more worthy of creative solutions, and
more consistent with real-world digital experience, than searching for new
regulatory tools to manage competition among current players.
<P>
My second example is more general: It is the obsession with controlling
hardware as the means to ensure competition. And the focus on bandwidth is
one of its more disturbing manifestations. This, too, stems from analog
tenets--the belief that more information, rather than better information,
is the main benefit of a next-generation telecommunications system. Here
let me invoke what I call the "30-30 rule" --that we humans can take in
information at only about 30 megahertz through our eyes or, even slower, at
30 kilohertz through our ears. Bandwidth is important to machine-to-machine
communications, but it is the computer, in some form, whether PC, PDA,
digital-phone or digital-TV, that will continue to determine the "match"
between bandwidth and the inherent limitation of the 30-30 rule. As
bandwidth explodes, and as digital connections become pervasive, the demand
for computers to provide a better "match" will remain the driving force
shaping digital communications. WE pay for human features, such as
resolution, portability, and ease-of-use, but the demand for bandwidth is
more elusive.
<P>
Those twin societal goals of enhancing economic growth and empowering
individuals are best addressed by thinking about how to make available all
those new services that are enabled by digital communications--connecting
computers--not just by the proliferation of bandwidth. This aspect of
digital communications is not benign; It means that application software,
more than hardware or system software, will be the differentiating factor.
<P>
And, in a truly competitive environment, that means that that's where a
large measure of future communications' profits will come from. It makes
the case for opening the doors to new entrants even more pertinent.
<P>
In the recent issue of Reason magazine, Peter Huber has outlined, clearly
and succinctly, the major elements for a telecommunications reform debate
that could, for the first time, lead to "digital legislation." His basic
assumptions there is that "Monopoly is indeed a nasty thing. The biggest
monopoly in town is always government........To fix monopoly, you have to
go after and disable the worst monopolist, government itself." To his
article, I would just add this additional point: Opening the door to new
entrants, especially in the local loop, should be an overarching objective
of any digital legislation. Moreover, in debating how to best accomplish
that, we must examine closely the computer industry's experience.
<P>
I leave you with one thought. Setting aside Judge Sporkin's legitimate
concerns, do you think Microsoft or Intel would be American companies if
computing had been regulated as communications is toady, or even as current
legislation pending would have it? Or do you think America would today
dominate the computer industry if new entrants had been inhibited? I do
not.
<p>
<p>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
</HTML>
