<html>
<head>
<title>Washington Report</title>
</head>
<p><br><br>
<body>
<center>
<table border>
<tr>
<td><IMG ALT="WASHINGTON REPORT LOGO" SRC="wlogo.GIF"></td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>

<img src="red-line.gif">
<h3>August 1995</h3>
</center>
<p>
<h3><a name="quick">QuickLinks</a></h3>
<a href="#NAACP">NAACP plans 'voter empowerment campaign' to create black districts</a><br>
<a href="#Fletcher">Arthur Fletcher enters GOP presidential race</a><br>
<a href="#Think">New think tank opens: The Center for New Black Leadership</a><br>
<a href="#Bacon">Fight discrimination: Repeal the Davis-Bacon Act</a><p>

<hr>
<a name="NAACP"></a>
<a href="#quick">(Back to QuickLinks)</a><p>
Shaken by Supreme Court decisions they consider hostile,
civil rights activists spelled out a strategy June 30 for
fighting back.  A main goal: Energizing jaded masses of black
people to act in what civil rights leaders say is their own
interest.
<p>     
The NAACP is staging a "national voter empowerment campaign"
that seeks to mobilize black constituents in political districts
where they comprise at least 15 percent of eligible voters but
less than a majority.
<p>     
The effort, approved in advance, is the first grassroots
response to Thursday's Supreme Court decision that using race as
an overriding concern when drawing minority districts is
unconstitutional.
<p>     
"We have to turn this pain around," said NAACP lobbyist Ed
Hailes Jr.  "Our participation in democracy is being denied."  
<p>
     
The Supreme Court's ruling was the latest in a series by the
high court this year that black activists say have chipped away
at the hard-won gains of the 1960s civil rights movement.
<p>       
Earlier, the court also jeopardized many federal affirmative
action programs by saying Congress must abide by the same strict
anti-bias standards as state and local governments.  And the
justices made it easier for school systems to get out from under
federal supervision of school desegregation.
<p>     
"I can assure you, we won't go back," said Rep. Eddie
Bernice Johnson, a Democrat whose Texas district is under
challenge.  "We know how to vote.  And we will vote.  We do it
best when we have a reason to."
<p>     
As the redistricting decision came down, the National Urban
League canceled plans to hold its 1996 convention in Los Angeles. 
It is protesting California Gov. Pete Wilson's executive order
ending state affirmative action programs.
<p>     
The league, alarmed by the high court's affirmative action
decision, has made protecting such programs its rallying cry.  By
canceling the conference--and the revenue it would have generated
for the area--the league hopes to discourage other states from
following Wilson's lead, particularly in light of the court's
decision.
<p>     
"We're not going to just express our dismay.  We're going to
do something about it," said league president Hugh B. Price.
<p>     
The NAACP campaign, set to begin in mid-July, targets
congressional seats, mostly in Southern states where majority
black districts are in peril.  Black Democrats are being asked to
lobby their representatives and state legislators about
redistricting, Supreme Court appointments and endorsements in the
1996 presidential election.
<p>    
 According to the NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund,
12 million blacks live in 113 majority-white congressional
districts in 11 Southern states.  And they've pumped up their
rhetoric too. 
<p>     
"With that kind of concentration and ratio of voters, we can
have great influence," said Washington NAACP director Wade
Henderson, coordinator of the campaign.  "It's open season on
black Americans.  We've got to start rewarding our friends and
punishing our enemies."
<p>     
The program will act in concert with efforts by the
Congressional Black Caucus and civil rights groups to add up to 7
million blacks to voting rolls.  The caucus' campaign is an
"immediate response" to the Supreme Court's decision, said Rep.
Kweisi Mfume (D-Md.).
<p>     
The goal is to "register every unregistered person in this
country, state by state, district by district, neighborhood by
neighborhood," Mfume said.  "In no way should those persons on
the other side of this (Supreme Court) decision think they have a
safe haven."
<p>     
In addition to registering voters, the caucus is working
with Democratic Party officials to ensure that black Democratic
incumbents will have their party's backing.
<p>     
"We will fight so that justice will reign in this country in
spite of the Supreme Court," said Rep. Donald Payne, (D-N.J.),
chairman of the caucus.
<p>     
But blacks who share a more conservative view say they also
have something to prove.  If conservatives say blacks can get
elected without the benefit of specially-carved out seats, they
must demonstrate this can, in fact, become a reality by getting
more mainstream minority candidates elected in 1996.  Thus, the
crucial work to be to recruit attractive conservative candidates
to run between now and then, probably as Republicans, but not
necessarily exclusively.
<p>
<hr>
<a name="Fletcher"></a>
<a href="#quick">(Back to QuickLinks)</a><p>
Arthur Fletcher, a Republican member of the U.S. Civil Rights
Commission, joined the 1996 presidential race July 7 urging his
party not to abandon minorities and the working class.  He is the
second black candidate to enter the race for the GOP nomination.
<p>
Fletcher, a strong advocate of affirmative action, said, "My
party has designed a top-down strategy, which says the wealthy,
the rich, the affluent belong to this party.  Anybody that
doesn't earn $35,000 a year is out of the equation."
<p>     
"It's time to stop that and say there's room for anybody who
wants to participate in the Republican Party."
<p>     
He announced his candidacy at a news conference in the
economically depressed Anacostia area of Washington.
Fletcher, who is black, has been promoting affirmative action
programs since the Nixon administration when he was a Labor
Department official.  Since then, three Republican presidents--Ford, Reagan and Bush--have appointed him to the U.S. Commission
of Civil Rights, which he chaired from 1990 to 1993.  He is 70
years old.
<p>     
He opined that GOP presidential candidates already in the
race must pander to the right wing in ways that threaten gains
made in civil rights since the 1960s.
<p>     
"There's not a ghost of a chance of their being nominated. 
Unless they engage in the race-baiting, gender-bashing tactics of
the moment," Fletcher said.
<p>     
"My concern, more than anything else, is to see to it that
the party doesn't completely end up abandoning the middle, where
the majority of the voters live, in pursuit of the nomination,"
he added.
<p>     
Fletcher first entered Republican politics in Kansas and was
vice chairman of the state GOP from 1955-57.
<p>     
In 1969, while working in Nixon's Labor Department, he
helped implement the "revised Philadelphia plan" that set and
enforced equal opportunity employment standards for companies
with federal contracts.
<p>     
He said he would finance his campaign largely by appealing
to minorities and women to send $5 contributions to his
headquarters in Kansas City, KS.
<p>     
His slogan: "Send five and keep affirmative action alive." 
With that money, Fletcher said he intends to lease a bus to
recreate the "Freedom Rides" of the 1960s to get his message out.
<p>     
"I will not be a high-flying, expensive candidate.  I'm
going to make sure the small people know I am their candidate,"
Fletcher said. 
<p>     
The former commissioner will likely have a tough time
getting press coverage and support from his fellow Republicans. 
The constituency for Fletcher's pet issues is so small within the
GOP that his candidacy is merely symbolic, at best.
<p>
<hr>
<a name="Think"></a>
<a href="#quick">(Back to QuickLinks)</a><p>
A new think tank recently opened in the nation's capitol to
promote self-help initiatives among black Americans.  The Center
for New Black Leadership commenced operation in Washington, D.C.
on May 1, 1995.  The Center is a nonprofit, nonpartisan think
tank devoted to reviving and encouraging traditionally effective
solutions to social and economic problems confronting the black
community.  The Center will work to encourage the development of
sound ideas and institutions consistent with the black
community's long-held commitments to individual initiative and
personal responsibility.
<p>     
The leadership of the Center consists of Directors Peter
Bell of TCF Financial Corp. in Minneapolis; Glenn Loury of Boston
University; Roy Innis of the Congress for Racial Equality;
Phyllis Berry Myers of Black America's PAC; and Shelby Steele of
the Hoover Institution.  The President of the Center is Brian W.
Jones.
<p>     
Jones is hopeful that the Center's work will perform a
function complementary to the work of the many conservative
grassroots and political organizations laboring in the black
community.  "Our goal," says Jones, "is to provide an
intellectual framework for the work of these other organizations. 
By providing a thoughtful defense of conservative ideas in the
black community, we can ensure the long-term viability of the
essential grassroots efforts already under way."
<p>    
Inquiries about the Center for New Black Leadership should
be directed to Brian W. Jones at 733 15th Street, N.W., Suite
700, Washington, D.C. 20005.  The Center's telephone number is
(202) 638-0651.
<p>
<hr>
<a name="Bacon"></a>
<a href="#quick">(Back to QuickLinks)</a><p>
Congress can fight racial discrimination in the construction
industry and save billions of tax dollars by repealing the Davis-Bacon Act, according to a Heritage Foundation analyst.
<p>
"This Depression-era law protects racial discrimination in
the construction industry, needlessly costs taxpayers billions of
dollars each year, stifles productivity, and subsidizes special
interests," says Mark Wilson, Heritage's Rebecca Lukens fellow in
labor policy.
<p>     
The 1931 law requires contractors working on federally
funded construction projects to pay workers "prevailing wages"
that are defined by the U.S. Department of Labor.  Through Davis-Bacon, the Labor Department also imposes costly and inflexible
job classification and apprenticeship regulations on contractors
seeking federal construction projects.
<p>     
"Ever since its adoption, Davis-Bacon has led to
discrimination against minorities in the construction industry,"
Wilson says.  The law has thus protected unions against
competition from outside non-unionized contractors using lower-cost itinerant labor, typically black workers from the South and
immigrants," says the former Labor Department economist.
<p>     
The result: Despite three decades of federally required
reverse discrimination and minority set-asides, black workers
still make up only 6.4 percent of the workers in the construction
industry.  By comparison, blacks make up 10.4 percent of the
total workforce.
<p>     
Black-owned firms are also kept out of federal construction
projects by Davis-Bacon, Wilson says.  "Few minority-owned firms
win Davis-Bacon contracts, and many give up trying because they
are less able to pay Davis-Bacon prevailing wage rates," he says.
<p>
Citing Congressional Budget Office estimates, Wilson says
Davis-Bacon costs taxpayers as much as $5.3 billion annually by
inflating labor costs on federally financed building projects. 
In Oakland, Calif., for example, carpenters are paid $28 per hour
on federally funded projects, compared to $15 per hour in that
city's private sector, Wilson says.
<p>     
Davis-Bacon repeal would also "free up an estimated 5
million labor hours per year that contractors now must spend
completing weekly payroll requirements that Labor Department
bureaucrats admit they ignore," Wilson says.  The cost of this
needless federal paperwork is passed on to taxpayers by the
contractor, he says.
<p>     
The only groups supporting Davis-Bacon are "building and
construction trade unions and their allies in Congress and the
Clinton administration," Wilson says.  "But Congress should be
looking out for the interests of taxpayers and all workers, not
just those who gain from the restrictive law," he says.
<p>
<p>
[ <a href="home.html">Home</a> | <a href="i-wr.html">Washington Report</a> ]
</body>
</html>
