<html><head><title>VOTE AMERICA:  Conventions</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="tile.gif">
<blockquote>
<center>
<a href="http://www.virtent.com"><img src="votelogo.gif" border="0"></a>

<P>
<h2>The fall campaign</h2>
</center>
<P>
In the final months of the campaign, there are certain orienting
landmarks--the Labor Day kick-off, September debate negotiations,
the debates themselves, and the grueling last-ditch effort as
the candidates strive for those few additional votes.  While the
candidates seem to be ricocheting around the country in no particular
pattern, the distribution of campaign resources is determined
by <b>electoral math</b>.  
<P>
<center><a href="fall.jpg"><img src="fall.gif" alt="Timeline" border="0"></a></center>
<P>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As outlined in the Twelfth Amendment to the Constitution, the
president is chosen not by direct popular vote, but by electors
from each state.  A state has a number of electors equal to its
number of congressmen and senators.  (The District of Columbia
also has three electors, bringing the total to 538.)  In most
states, the popular vote winner takes all the electors.  For example,
even if a candidate wins California by a margin of less than 1
percent, he will gain all of the state's 54 electors.  Thus the
campaigns' strategies revolve around winning states that will
add up to a minimum of 270 electoral votes.  Some are seen as
pretty sure bets, some are tightly contested &quot;play-hard&quot;
states, some are possibles, and some are essentially unwinnable.
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The campaigns are not only targeting particular states, but they
are trying to reach particular people within those states.  A
general election campaign is a battle for the attention of a relatively
small audience.  The rule of thumb in presidential campaigns is
that about 40 percent of those who turn out will vote for the
Republican candidate no matter what and another 40 percent will
vote Democratic no matter what.  Major resources during the fall
campaign are devoted to reaching and swaying the remaining 20
percent of the electorate--persuadable swing voters.  
<P>
<ul>
<b>Group A  </b><br>      
<ul>Will vote for the candidate almost automatically.  </ul>  
<P>
<b>Group B</b><br>
<ul>Will not vote for the candidate no matter what.</ul>
<P>
<B>Group C</B>
<ul>Swing voters; can be persuaded.
</ul></ul><P>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Politicians think of the electorate in terms of three groups.
 The first group will vote for their candidate almost automatically.
 The second group will not vote for their candidate no matter
what.  The third group are swing voters.  This model can also
be applied to races with many candidates; for example Group A
could be Perot, Bush, or Clinton backers.
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To attract the persuadables, candidates generally move toward
the middle, toning down the more extreme elements of their messages
that they had used to appeal to party activists during the primaries.
 They may run television spots and concentrate media efforts in
media markets with large numbers of persuadable voters.  The ads
one sees in this time are designed primarily to influence people
who have not made up their minds.
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Extensive resources are devoted to persuadable voters, but the
candidate's base (Group A) must be mobilized as well.  Some supporters
may need a bit of a nudge to get them out to the polls.  By narrowcasting
specific parts of the candidate's message to constituency groups,
the campaign can energize these people.  Then, as Election Day
approaches, get-out-the-vote efforts gear up to produce a big
turnout.
<p>
In 1994 and 1995, there was much speculation that one or more
credible independent or third-party candidates might emerge to
challenge the Democratic and Republican nominees.  Among those
mentioned were Colin Powell, Bill Bradley, Jesse Jackson, Lowell
Weicker, and Ross Perot.  Libertarians were also optimistic that
the ongoing reexamination of government would give their candidate
a boost.  
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The presence of a credible alternative to the major party candidates
adds a degree of uncertainty to the race, causing people to reassess
their support and increasing the competition for swing voters.
 Regardless of the number of candidates, the goal of each campaign
remains the same: go after the undecideds and mobilize supporters.
<P>
<b>Map available only in CD-ROM version.</b>
<P>
