<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT19-B27-180</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA086-000616-B048-15</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.cpac.org:80/ads/ve/presidnt.html 204.71.237.74 19970122022347 text/html 8385
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Wednesday, 22-Jan-97 02:24:08 GMT
Last-modified: Monday, 29-Jan-96 22:17:16 GMT
Content-length: 8199
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Vitrual Entertainment's VOTE AMERICA</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="tile.gif">
<blockquote>
<center>
<a href="http://www.virtent.com"><img src="votelogo.gif" border="0"></a>
<P>
<h2>What makes a president</h2>
</center>
<P>
A presidential election is a defining moment for the nation. 
At the outset, a dozen or so hopefuls may offer themselves to
the voters as leadership material.  Only one will emerge as each
party's nominee.  A unique set of qualities and traits, in tandem
with a fortuitous unfolding of events, allows a successful candidate
to make the leap from the crowd.
<P>
<b>Leadership</b><br>
<ul>
Leadership entails not only setting a direction but possessing
the skills to see to it that one's ideas are implemented.  In
The Prince, Machiavelli wrote, &quot;There is nothing so perilous
in its outcome nor uncertain in its success as the introduction
of a new order of things.&quot;  
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Choosing a president is a personal decision.  In general, our
assessments of a candidate's character figure prominently.  Is
the candidate independent, arrogant, flaky, courageous?  Character
questions go to a deep level, beyond ideology or positions on
issues.  For this reason, campaigns often seek to raise doubts
about an opponent's character.  (&quot;Do I trust this guy?&quot;
 &quot;Is he stable?&quot;)
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Robert Deutsch, a public communication analyst in Northern Virginia,
states that a candidate must convey three attributes at the same
time.  Familiarity means we perceive the candidate is like us.
 Appeasement means we feel the candidate cares for us as individuals.
 Power means we see the candidate as being more than any one ordinary
person; he or she is somehow in control of events.  Applying these
simple criteria, one can get a good idea of how a candidate will
fare regardless of what the public opinion polls of the moment
are saying.
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Thinking back to 1992, for example, Bill Clinton probably fulfilled
the above criteria better than George Bush.  Bush was portrayed
as being somewhat out of touch with ordinary Americans; an example
was the widely reported incident of the supermarket scanner. 
As for appeasement, there are numerous stories of Clinton's ability
to listen to people and ask thoughtful questions.  In terms of
being more than an ordinary individual, during the course of his
bus tours Clinton met with thousands of people and gained a unique
understanding of the nation.
</ul>
<P>
<b>Ideology counts</b>
<P>
<ul>
An ideology provides a consistent framework for addressing the
broad spectrum of issues.  Some of the candidates have clearly
discernable ideologies or political philosophies, while others
rely more on polls and behave more as opportunists.  Ideology
may be more important during the primaries, when people are choosing
among a bevy of candidates, than in the general election when
leadership attributes are particularly important.
</ul><P>
<center><h3>Who wins?</h3></center>
<P>
There have been numerous instances of candidates who have been
built up prior to the campaign failing to do well (John Glenn
in 1984 or Gary Hart in 1988).  Other candidates are much admired
but fail to get through the primaries (Bruce Babbitt in 1988 or
Paul Tsongas in 1992).  Rather than referring to another mindless
poll, think about some of the factors at work:
<P>
<ul><li><b>Television</b> has elevated the importance of external appearances.
 Historically, a candidate's physical appearance may have made
some difference; for example it is recognized that taller candidates
may have an advantage.  In the television era, a candidate's <a href="images.html">ability
to perform well on the medium of television</a> is fundamental to
his or her political success.  The candidate must have no &quot;edges&quot;
that will jar viewers.  In 1992, for example, Bush often appeared
ill-at-ease, while Clinton moved around with the ease of a television
show host.
<P>
<li><a href="process.html"><b>The nominating process itself</b></a>, while designed to be neutral, does
favor certain types of candidates.  For example, some potentially
solid candidates are discouraged from running by fundraising demands.
 It is true that all the candidates must play by the same rules,
but one can see that different rules would produce different outcomes.
 A closely grouped succession of primaries requires that a candidate
run an expensive media campaign.  Caucuses, by contrast, tend
to favor candidates who can organize at the grassroots.  
<P>
<li><b>Incumbency</b> can be an advantage for the president both in terms
of symbolism and concrete actions.  An incumbent president has
an edge in conforming to one's internal image of a leader because
he is surrounded by the trappings of office.  He arrives on Air
Force I, he gets &quot;Hail to the Chief,&quot; and he speaks
from a lectern with the presidential seal on it.
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The incumbent can also take steps during the campaign to &quot;buy&quot;
support.  For example, in 1992, at the beginning of September,
President Bush announced an increase in subsidies for wheat exports
and the sale of 150 F-16 fighter planes to Taiwan.  These and
other actions caused Detroit News writer James Gannon to label
him &quot;a flying fountain of federal aid&quot; and the Washington
Post to compare him to &quot;a department store Santa Claus in
December.&quot;  Incumbency has a downside too.  After a party
has been in power for a number of years, it may grow complacent
or be afflicted by various scandals; people start thinking about
change.
<P>
<li><b><a href="context.html">The historical and economic context</b></a> in which an election campaign
is fought has an important effect on the outcome.  Had communism
in Eastern Europe and the Soviet Union not collapsed during the
Bush tenure, the dynamics of the 1992 campaign might have been
very different.  Coinciding with the end of the Soviet threat,
the Clinton-Gore ticket presented voters with the question of
whether they were ready for a younger generation of leadership.
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The state of the economy is particularly significant.  Ray Fair,
a professor at Yale University, has even developed an equation
that &quot;explains votes for president [in the general election]
on the basis of economic conditions at the time of the election.&quot;
 Fair writes, &quot;The two economic variables that seem most
important are the growth rate of real per capita GNP in the six-month
period prior to the election and the rate of inflation in the
two-year period prior to the election.&quot;  In the 1992 campaign,
lackluster economic performance in Bush's term clearly undercut
his re-election bid.
<P>
<li>With the historical and economic context and the candidates set,
<b><a href="genl.html">a well-run campaign</a></b> can also make some difference in the outcome
of an election.  A good campaign organization sets the agenda
and the terms of debate.  The 1992 contest was not about foreign
policy--Bush's terrain--but revolved around the domestic economy,
as in, &quot;It's the economy, stupid.&quot;  Exactly how much
of an effect a campaign can have is a much-debated point, but
most observers agree that Bush's campaign was poorly managed,
while Clinton's team avoided the mistakes of past Democratic efforts.
<P>
<li>Finally, there is always the <b>element of chance</b>.  The best-laid
plans, the most careful positioning, and the soundest campaign
organization can all be knocked awry by an unexpected event.
</ul>
<P>
<center>
<small><a href="contents.html">Table of Contents</a> | <a href="process.html">Next Section</a> | <a href="welcome.html">Vote America Home</a> | <a href="order.html.cgi">Order</a> | <a href="/townhall">Town Hall</a>
<P>
&copy; 1996 <a href="http://www.virtent.com">Virtual Entertainment</a></small>
</center>
</BODY>

