<DOCHDR>
http://www.cpac.org:80/ads/ve/process.html 204.71.237.74 19970121224934 text/html 9411
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Tuesday, 21-Jan-97 22:49:55 GMT
Last-modified: Monday, 29-Jan-96 23:18:05 GMT
Content-length: 9227
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>VOTE AMERICA:  The Process</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="tile.gif">
<blockquote>
<center>
<a href="http://www.virtent.com"><img src="votelogo.gif" border="0"></a>
<P>
<h2>The Process</h2>
</center>
<P>
<b>Candidates</b>  
<ul>More than 150 candidates have registered with the
Federal Election Commission to run for president.  The pack of
presidential hopefuls presents a wide range of experience and
motivations.  Some have served in politics for more than thirty
years; others have never run for public office.  Some have a well-defined
political philosophy, others are more pragmatic, and still others
may be running to draw attention to a single issue.  Some are
able to raise tens of millions of dollars and build elaborate
campaign organizations, while others have put up a few thousand
dollars to run a campaign out of their own homes.
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To actually appear on a ballot in a particular state, however,
a candidate must meet that state's criteria.  Ballot access rules
vary from state to state.  New York's rules were among the most
restrictive.  To fully compete in the New York Republican presidential
primary, a candidate had to obtain 1,250 signatures from each
of the state's 31 congressional districts (a few districts needed
less than 1,250).  In itself the task of getting 30,000 signatures
would be a straightforward proposition, but the party had arcane
rules that allowed petitions to be disqualified for the most minor
infractions.  By contrast, New Hampshire requires candidates to
file a declaration of candidacy &quot;not more than 74 nor less
than 60 days before the presidential primary&quot; and to pay
a fee of $1,000.  Candidates also need to provide information
on their delegates and alternates.  
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some individuals, whom the media have identified as &quot;presidential
material,&quot; survey the political landscape and decide not
to run, whether for family reasons, because they feel they do
not have the &quot;fire in the belly,&quot; or because they do
not feel they can meet fundraising demands.  These figures of
speculation often attract as much attention as declared candidates.
 Those who do decide to run announce their bids and set about
raising money and positioning themselves for the intense primary
period.</ul>
<P>
 
<P>
<b><a href="iowanh.html">Primaries and Caucuses.</a></b>  
<ul>While there are a range of political
parties to choose from, the two-party system is a solid feature
of American politics.  The Republican and Democratic parties,
by virtue of tradition and their vast resources, dominate the
presidential selection process.  From February to June, state
Republican and Democratic parties conduct primaries or caucuses
to select delegates to the national nominating conventions. 
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The series of presidential preference primaries and caucuses has
an almost circus-like air as the candidates race from state to
state trying to gain the attention of the media, pick up momentum
and win delegates.  Caucuses are a multi-step process for choosing
delegates that starts with meetings at the precinct level and
leads up to a state convention.  The caucus system is mostly confined
to smaller states and places a premium on grassroots organizing.
 In primaries, by contrast, the campaign has a media-intensive
orientation and delegates are distributed according to popular
vote.  
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Caucuses formerly were the dominant method of selecting delegates,
but the primary has come into increasing favor over the past two-and-a-half
decades as the parties have sought to open up the process.  Turnout
in primaries tends to well below 50 percent of eligible voters.
Caucuses, because they are more time-consuming, attract only the
most active party members.  
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In order to vote in a party's preference primary or participate
in a caucus one must be a registered voter.  Frequently one must
also be registered as member of the party.  Registering to vote
is a simple procedure, although each state's rules vary somewhat.
 In general a person must fill out a form stating that he or she
is a United States citizen, is 18 years or older and has a permanent
home in the locality in which he or she wishes to vote.  Some
states require that a person choose a party; others do not.  
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The chaotic primary system is uniquely American; in most other
countries the parties choose their leaders in a closed process.
 As Republicans and Democrats grab the media spotlight, smaller,
third parties are also choosing their nominees.  Finally, a candidate
can run as an independent, bypassing the party route altogether
and qualifying for the November ballot by petitioning to get on
the ballot.  While Ross Perot did this in 1992, tremendous resources
were needed to make it happen in all fifty states. 
</ul><P>
 
<P>
<b><a href="conv.html">Conventions</a></b>  
<ul>During two separate weeks in August, delegates gather
at the Republican and Democratic national conventions to choose
the parties' nominees.  Conventions formerly served as decision-making
bodies, but in recent decades the outcomes have been a foregone
conclusion.  The convention allows the party to present its ticket
to the national television audience and is in a sense a giant
ad for the party.  The convention also approves the party platform.
</ul><P>
<b><a href="elect.html">Election Day</a></b>
<ul>Fresh from the conventions, the Democratic and
Republican nominees enter the second phase of the election--the
fall campaign.  They are joined by third party and independent
candidates who, despite their best efforts, are generally marginalized.
 Meanwhile, the Democratic and Republican candidates crisscross
the country focusing their resources on winnable states that will
enable them to reach the required 270 electoral votes.  The campaigns
each spend tens of millions of dollars on advertising campaigns.
 A series of high-stakes presidential and vice-presidential debates
and efforts to mobilize supporters (Get Out The Vote) lead up
to Election Day.  As provided for by Article II of the Constitution,
Congress has set Election Day as the first Tuesday following the
first Monday of November.
</ul><P>
<b>The Electoral College</b>  
<ul>One of the most misunderstood features
of American presidential elections is the Electoral College. 
The President is not selected by direct popular vote.  On Election
Day, when a voter chooses a particular candidate, he or she is
actually voting for that candidate's electors.  The Electoral
College system, although decried by many as an anachronism, is
prescribed by the Constitution.  Each state has a number of electors
equal to its number of Senators and Representatives and the District
of Columbia has three for a total of 538.  The electors meet about
a month after the election in the 50 state capitols.  In most
states they are bound to vote in a bloc for the popular vote winner.
 Only when the results of Electoral College voting are transmitted
to the President of the Senate and one of the candidates has achieved
a majority (270), does the outcome of the election become official.

<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A comparable situation would be if, in the election of a student
body president, each class had a number of representatives based
on its size--say one for every seven people.  The class would
vote, and the results would be tallied.  If Joe Smith won, all
of the class representatives or electors would be committed to
Smith.  They would meet a month later at the teacher's desk and
vote for Smith.  The results from each class would be then transmitted
to the Vice Principal's office and counted to determine the new
president.
</ul><P>
 
<P>
<b><a href="trans.html">Seal</a></b>  
<ul>Despite the Electoral College procedure, it is almost always
clear from the popular vote count who has won the election.  In
the transition period, the winning candidate, now the President-elect,
shifts from campaign mode to shaping the new administration. 
Elaborate festivities build up to Inauguration Day, which is set
by the Twentieth Amendment to the Constitution on the 20th day
of January.  The swearing-in ceremony completes the transfer of
power and the new (or second-term) administration is underway.
 The election process is complete--except for the analyses which
will go on for several years more.  Those who are thinking about
running in the year 2000 start to engage in a few preliminary
musings!
</ul><P>

<center>
<small><a href="contents.html">Table of Contents</a> | <a href="context.html">Next Section</a> | <a href="welcome.html">Vote America Home</a> | <a href="order.html.cgi">Order</a> | <a href="/townhall">Town Hall</a>
<P>
&copy; 1996 <a href="http://www.virtent.com">Virtual Entertainment</a></small>
</center>
 
</BODY>

</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT19-B27-182</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA086-000617-B041-426</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.cpac.org:80/ads/ve/context.html 204.71.237.74 19970122011658 text/html 4951
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Wednesday, 22-Jan-97 01:17:19 GMT
Last-modified: Monday, 29-Jan-96 22:16:17 GMT
Content-length: 4765
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>VOTE AMERICA:  Context</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="tile.gif">
<blockquote>
<center>
<a href="http://www.virtent.com"><img src="votelogo.gif" border="0"></a>

<P>
<h2>Context</h2>
</center>
<P>
The historical context in which an election occurs is as important
as the qualities of the candidates and the rules of the nominating
process in determining its outcome.  In 1992 for example, the
end of the Cold War tilted the playing field away from George
Bush, the candidate with recognized foreign policy experience.

<P>
A number of factors will set the context for the 1996 campaign.
<ul>
<li>The <b>state of the economy</b> is always at the forefront in presidential
elections.  People vote their pocketbooks, and if the economy
is strong a plurality may well opt to re-elect President Clinton
regardless of any qualms they may have about his character.  
<P><li>The year-long debate over the Clinton health care plan and the
subsequent Republican surge in the 1994 midterm elections have
led to a thorough re-examination of <b>the proper role of the federal
government</b>, what some are terming &quot;the second American revolution.&quot;
 If not a revolution, the conservative advances certainly suggest
a major realignment.  The welfare state and programs instituted
by Franklin Roosevelt in the 1930s are undergoing thorough scrutiny.
<br>
<P><li><b>The 1994 elections</b> gave Republicans control of both the House
and Senate for the first time in 40 years.  After November 1994,
Republicans held thirty governorships, including eight of the
nine biggest states (only Florida withstood the tide) and the
key Mideastern states of Michigan, Pennsylvania, and Ohio.  From
a narrow political point of view, the Republican wins have expanded
the friendly territory available to the Republican presidential
nominee during the fall campaign.  
<br>
<P><li>The <b>discontent</b> that first emerged in the electorate during the
1990 elections does not appear to be dissipating as a result of
the activities of the Republican Congress.  Inaction on matters
such as term limits and campaign finance reform and underlying
uncertainties about economic security may remain.  Voter frustration
could turn against the Republican Congress, be channeled into
a third party or independent presidential candidacy, spark renewed
local activism, or manifest itself in ways as yet unseen.
<P><li>Surface political currents should not obscure some of the <b>deeper
issues</b> facing society.  Widely differing perceptions of the O.
J. Simpson trial and the October 1995 Million Man March on Washington
showed that substantial work remains to be done to improve race
relations in this country.  Others have expressed more general
concerns about community.  In a much-discussed article &quot;Bowling
Alone,&quot; Robert Putnam drew attention to decreasing levels
of individual participation and involvement. 

<P><li>Half a dozen years into the post-Cold War era, <b>foreign
policy and national security issues</b> appear to have lessened in
importance.  Unrest in Bosnia, China, and some of the states of
the former Soviet Union could again move these concerns to the
fore.  And, in an increasingly interconnected world, less conventional
threats including terrorism, man-made mishaps, and global environmental
problems cannot be ignored.
<P><li>America finds itself in the midst of the <b>Information Revolution</b>.
 E-mail allows us to stay in touch with family and friends and
the World Wide Web provides instant access to material on everything
from phylogenetics to political candidates.  Yet while we are
connected to all this information, there is at times a sense of
disconnection.  More than fifty years after the end of World War
II, heading into a new millennium, many voters believe it's time
to overhaul some of the institutions and ways of doing things
that have evolved in these past decades.  In this context, then,
the candidates will offer their prescriptions and the 1996 campaign
will unfold.
</ul><P>
Additional Resources.
<ul>Robert D. Putnam.  &quot;Bowling Alone: America's Declining Social
Capital.&quot;  <I>Journal of Democracy</I>, January 1995, v6n1,
p. 65-78.
<P>
Francis Fukuyama.  1995.  <I>Trust: Social Virtues and the Creation
of Prosperity</I>.  New York: The Free Press.</ul>
<P>
<center>
