</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>VOTE AMERICA:  Pre-Primary Period</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="tile.gif">
<blockquote>
<center>
<a href="http://www.virtent.com"><img src="votelogo.gif" border="0"></a>

<P>
<h2>Pre-primary period</h2>
</center>

<P>
In a sense, following developments in the pre-primary period is
like watching athletes do their warm-up exercises before a race.
 There is a lot of speculation, and one can make some useful observations,
but there is no telling what will happen when the candidates face
real voters.
<P>
The 1992 campaign did not get fully underway until September 1991
because President Bush's popularity after the Gulf War deterred
most Democrats from making a move.  For 1996 the situation is
quite different.  President Clinton's perceived weakness and the
frontloading of the primary schedule prompted many Republican
candidates to start their activities within a few months of the
1994 mid-term elections.  Republican challengers will have had
about half a year longer to build their organizations, raise money,
and hone their messages than did their Democratic counterparts
in 1992.  
<P>
<center><a href="preprim1.jpg"><img src="preprim1.gif" border="0" alt="Timeline"></a></center>
<P>
The first step in launching a presidential bid is &quot;testing
the waters.&quot;  The potential candidate talks with friends
and colleagues, seeks advice from a number of sources, makes some
thoughtful speeches in Iowa and New Hampshire, and gauges the
reaction.  He or she weighs current responsibilities and the prospects
of success (winning the nomination or shaping the debate) against
the toll a campaign will take on his or her personal life.  At
this point some decide to bow out.  
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For those who decide to proceed and want to start <a href="financ.html">raising and
spending money</a>, the next step is to establish an exploratory committee
or file a statement of candidacy.  During this time, the candidate
will have a detailed plan drawn up that outlines his or her strengths,
weaknesses, and strategy.
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The announcement speech or announcement tour is one of the most
symbolic events of the campaign.  In a carefully selected location
before a carefully prepared backdrop, helped along by crowds of
cheering supporters, the candidate launches his or her quest.
 Announcement speeches are typically replete with references to
family, God, and country.  The candidate presents his or her vision
of the country's problems and its future.  Oftentimes footage
shot at the announcement speech will appear in campaign videos
or ads.
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For the next six months to a year, the candidates are out making
the rounds at various party gatherings, seeking support from activists,
holding fundraising events, and working to generate favorable
media coverage.  Aside from activists and political reporters,
however, most people are paying scant attention. 
<P>
<center><a href="preprim2.jpg"><img src="preprim2.gif" border="0" alt="Timeline"></a></center>
<P>
The major challenge candidates face in the pre-primary period
is to establish <B>credibility</B>.  The three main ingredients
to credibility are stature, money, and campaign organization.
<P>
<blockquote>
<b>Stature</b>
<ul>Candidates without previous service in high elective
office have generally not been selected as nominees by the major
parties.  For the most part, successful Democratic and Republican
presidential candidates have come out of governors' offices or
the U.S. Senate or House of Representatives.  Candidates from
outside the political domain are rare; Eisenhower was a notable
exception. Lack of political experience often counts as an automatic
first strike against a candidate.  In fact, however, it is not
so much experience, but stature that counts.  A candidate who
repeatedly delivers substantial, well-received speeches will garner
favorable reviews and gain the support of party activists looking
to find someone who is &quot;presidential material.&quot; 
</ul>
  
<P>
<a href="financ.html"><b>Money</b></a>
<ul>Fundraising is sometimes referred to as the first
primary.  Money will be particularly important in the 1996 campaign
because of the compressed primary schedule.  Early on, Senator
Phil Gramm set the stakes by spreading the word that he would
raise $20 to $30 million before the first contest, the Iowa caucuses.
 Bob Dole and Lamar Alexander vowed to match Gramm.  Raising more
than $70,000 a day requires a lot of $1,000-a-plate dinners. 
Contributors are essentially investing in what is an untested
commodity, for there is no telling how well the candidates will
do when they face the voters.  Fundraising demands have discouraged
a number of well-qualified presidential prospects from running.
</ul>
<P>
<b>Campaign organization</b>
<ul>The battle for talent, in which
candidates seek to attract big-name media consultants, fundraisers
and pollsters to their campaigns, starts even before the announcement
speeches.  After building the core, candidates work to line up
endorsements from elected officials and party activists in key
primary states.  Meanwhile, their organizations generate shows
of support at myriad party gatherings and straw polls.  (Straw
polls are votes put on by state party organizations that have
no effect on the selection of delegates and are basically exercises
in hype.)  While the candidates circulate at the &quot;cattle
shows,&quot; their campaign organizations play up positive news
stories and attempt to douse negative ones. 
</ul>
</blockquote>
<P>
In its early stages, a candidacy can be compared to the tender
shoot of a sprouting seed; a spate of negative publicity can cripple
it and small problems may be indicative of difficulties to come.
 The successful candidate must demonstrate stature, fundraising
strength and organizational ability in the pre-primary period.
 Based on these three factors, the media determine that some candidates
are &quot;credible&quot; or &quot;serious&quot; and have a chance
winning the nomination.  The rest are classified as second or
third tier candidates, although not a single vote has been cast.
<P>
<B>Additional Resources:</B>
<P>
<ul>
<B><a href="http://www.cityvote.org">CityVote</a></B>.  The nonprofit CityVote organized a &quot;national
urban presidential primary,&quot; held on November 7, 1995 in
about 20 cities across the country in conjunction with local elections.
 CityVote sought to focus attention on the problems of America's
cities.  Its &quot;primary&quot; was not part of the nominating
process and had no impact on the selection of delegates.  Nonetheless
as a national event, occurring three months before the Iowa and
New Hampshire contests, it did draw some attention.  CityVote
had also planned four nationally televised candidate debates for
October and early November, but the &quot;major&quot; candidates
declined to participate.   
<P>
<ul>
<b>CityVote</b>
<br>14978 Sand Canyon Avenue, Suite A
<br>Irvine, CA  92718
<br>phone: (714) 552-9596   
<br>fax: (714) 552-9599
<br>e-mail: cityvote@cityvote.org
<br>web site: <a href="http://www.cityvote.org">http://www.cityvote.org/cityvote/home.htm</a>
</ul></ul><P>
