<html><head><title>VOTE AMERICA:  Iowa and New Hampshire Primaries</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="tile.gif">
<blockquote>
<center>
<a href="http://www.virtent.com"><img src="votelogo.gif" border="0"></a>


<P>
<h2>Iowa and New Hampshire</h2>
</center>
<P>
The Iowa caucuses and the New Hampshire primary offer presidential
candidates an opportunity to engage in retail politics and to
refine their messages before moving to a more media intensive
mode later in the campaign.  
<p>

<center><a href="iowanh.jpg"><img src="iowanh.gif" border="0" alt="Timeline"></a></center>
<P>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Iowa and New Hampshire zealously guard their first-in-the nation
status.  Indeed, Iowa law requires that the Iowa caucuses be held
eight days before any other state's delegate selection process.
 When Delaware Republicans sought to move their 1996 primary to
within four days of the New Hampshire primary, New Hampshirites
took severe umbrage.
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Iowa and New Hampshire are not typical states.  Iowa has about
1.7 million registered voters, but only a few hundred thousand
turn out at the Republican and Democratic precinct caucuses. New
Hampshire, with a population of just 1.1 million, is one of the
most Republican, whitest and wealthiest states in the nation.
 Iowa's and New Hampshire's importance in 1996 will be greater
than ever because of the compressed primary schedule.  Carl Cameron,
WMUR-TV's (Manchester, NH) political reporter, says that his state
will act as &quot;a sprinter's starting block.&quot;
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What the candidates seek from Iowa and New Hampshire is momentum.
 In 1976, Iowa gave Jimmy Carter a boost.  As for New Hampshire,
since 1952 no man--except Bill Clinton--has won the presidency
without first winning the state's primary.  In 1992 Clinton came
in second to Paul Tsongas with 25 percent of the vote, but was
able to claim a measure of victory as &quot;the comeback kid.&quot;
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One cannot discuss the New Hampshire primary without mention of
the state's two biggest media outlets.  <a href="http://www.wmur.com">WMUR-TV Channel 9</a>, an
ABC affiliate, and the Union Leader and New Hampshire Sunday News
wield tremendous influence.  WMUR-TV's weekday newscasts reach
over 290,000 adults each weekday.  The candidates go to great
lengths to get coverage from the station which has a national
reputation for its coverage of politics.  The Union Leader, with
a daily circulation of 70,013 and a daily adult readership of
189,000, has broken many candidates over the years and for utra-conservatives
the paper's endorsement is a crown jewel. 
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As the first contests, Iowa and New Hampshire receive a disproportionate
amount of news coverage from the national and international media.
 William C. Adams, a professor at George Washington University,
put together a map for the 1984 campaign showing the sizes of
the states in proportion to the amount of campaign coverage they
received.  New Hampshire, with a 1984 voting age population of
just 722,000, was as big as the 19 westernmost states including
California and Texas, states with a voting-age population in the
tens of millions.  1996 should follow the 1984 pattern.

<P>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Iowa and New Hampshire first-in-the-nation tradition is now
well established, but it does raise questions of fairness.  These
two states with such small populations have a huge influence in
the nominating process, while millions of voters in later contests
sometimes find that the nominees have essentially been selected.
<P>
   
<P>
<b>Map available in CD-ROM version only.</b>  
<P>

 
<P>
<b>Additional Resources:</b>
<ul>
Gary R. Orren and Nelson W. Polsby.  1987.  Media and Momentum:
The New Hampshire Primary and Nomination Politics.  Chatham, NJ:
Chatham House Publishers.
<P>
Dayton Duncan.  1991.  Grass Roots: One Year in the Life of the
New Hampshire Presidential Primary.  New York: Penguin Books.
</ul><P>
<b>On-line information:</b>
<ul>
<a href="http://www.profiles.iastate.edu/iacaucus/">The Iowa Caucus Project</a> is a joint project of the Iowa Association
of Business and Industry and the Iowa Department of Economic Development
in cooperation with 11 partner communities.  Its mission is &quot;to
serve...as a clearinghouse of information for the news media and
general public for Iowa's 1996 First in the Nation caucuses.&quot;

<P>
<a href="http://www.drake.edu/public/caucus.html">CyberCaucus: Iowa's First-in-the Nation Caucus</a> is part of a research
project supported by Drake University in Des Moines, Iowa.  The
project's adviser is Robert D. Woodward, a professor of journalism
and mass communication.  Woodward and two students, Laura Patterson
and Vicki Cassatt, developed CyberCaucus in Spring 1995.  The
site appeared in May 1995, hibernated during the summer, and resumed
activity in the fall:
<P>
In early 1995, Mark Kuhn and Jim Farrell, professors in the Department
of Communication at the University of New Hampshire, Durham started
<a href="http://unhinfo.unh.edu/unh/acad/libarts/comm/nhprimary/nhprim.html">NH-Primary</a>, an electronic discussion list and clearinghouse devoted
solely to the New Hampshire primary.  In addition to &quot;study
and civil debate about the 1996 New Hampshire presidential primary
campaign,&quot; the service provided information on candidate
appearances and campaign events, speeches and issues statements,
summaries of local news coverage and polling data from the University
of New Hampshire Survey Center.  The material was archived and
made available through a Web site that opened on May 9, 1995.
 To sign up for the list, send a subscribe message to NH-Primary@unh.edu
<P>
Foster's Daily Democrat (Dover, NH) and The Citizen (Laconia,
NH) have put together a well-organized site, <a href="http://www.fosters.com">Primary Destination:
New Hampshire</a>, which is strengthened with editorial contributions
from the Associated Press, The Christian Science Monitor, and
The New York Times Syndicate.  PD:NH is freely available, and
does not require paid subscriptions.
<P>
<a href="http://www.wmur.com">WMUR-TV News Nine</a> (Manchester, NH). 
<P>
The Concord Monitor and The Telegraph, with cooperation from The
Keene Sentinel, the Valley News, and the Associated Press are
offering <a href="http://www.cmonitor.com">Primary Monitor</a>.  However users need a <b>paid subscription</b>
to access much of the information.
</ul></blockquote><P>

<P>
