<html><head><title>VOTE AMERICA:  Election Day</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="tile.gif">
<blockquote>
<center>
<a href="http://www.virtent.com"><img src="votelogo.gif" border="0"></a>

<P>
<h2>Election Day</h2>
</center>
<P>
On November 5, 1996, an election campaign that has been underway
for almost two years draws to a close.  The candidates, exhausted
by last-ditch efforts to rally up votes, are among the approximately
100 million citizens turning out at polling places across the
country.  
<P>
Also on the ground are thousands of interviewers surveying a sample
of the voters who have just cast their ballots.  Exit poll results
are a major feature of election night coverage.  They provide
a window on the concerns of voters as well as useful information
on gender, race, age, and other variations in voting behavior.
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Controversy has arisen over the networks' use of exit polls to
project winners before the polls close.  Critics argue that early
projections of winners discourage voters from turning out.  In
1985 the networks pledged to Congress that they would refrain
from declaring winners in a state until the polls in that state
closed.  As a result, a less-than-adequate situation exists where
reporters have information but are bound not to relate it.  By
midafternoon on November 3, 1992, exit poll data showed that Clinton
had won big in the Electoral College.  NBC President Michael Gartner
observed in a post-election <I>Wall Street Journal</I> article that,
&quot;Everybody knew who the winner was but the people.&quot;
 
<P>
Election night is a major production for the networks' news divisions.
 Often they will construct a special set dominated by a big electoral
map and filled with lots of monitors.  The anchor and his in-studio
team analyze and relate the results, while other correspondents
report from the candidates' headquarters and from tightly contested
races around the country.  The evening draws to a close with concession
and victory speeches.
<P>
<br><center><small><a href="contents.html">Table of Contents</a> | <a href="trans.html">Next Section</a> | <a href="welcome.html">Vote America Home</a> | <a href="order.html.cgi">Order</a> | <a href="/townhall">Town Hall</a>
<P>
&copy; 1996 <a href="http://www.virtent.com">Virtual Entertainment</a></small>
</center>
</BODY>

</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT19-B27-188</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA086-000617-B041-379</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.cpac.org:80/ads/ve/trans.html 204.71.237.74 19970122011628 text/html 5567
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
