<html><head><title>VOTE AMERICA:  Language</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="tile.gif">
<blockquote>
<center>
<a href="http://www.virtent.com"><img src="votelogo.gif" border="0"></a>
<P>
<h2>Language</h2>
</center>
<P>
A campaign generates a plentitude of words.  While there is a
fair degree of overblown rhetoric, obfuscation, and partisan sniping,
occasionally one of the candidates delivers a finely crafted speech
with a beginning, middle, and end.  In his recent book The Inarticulate
Society, Tom Shachtman argues that there is a &quot;crisis in
eloquence.&quot;  Politicians' concern with getting their soundbites
in the news may be one of the factors contributing to this decline.
<P>
The use of language in labeling merits some attention.  Labeling
people and subjects helps us to get a fix on them.  While some
labels such as &quot;former governor&quot; are harmless, others
such as &quot;pro-life&quot;/&quot;anti-choice&quot; and &quot;pro-choice&quot;/&quot;pro-abortion&quot;
are ideologically charged.  
<P>
In a press release, bombast can sometimes be amusing.  For example,
one of the National Rainbow Coalition's JaxFaxes refers to Senator
Dole as &quot;Consummate Washington insider, deal-maker, cynic,
affirmative action race-baiter and leading Republican presidential
candidate Sen. Robert Dole (R-KS).&quot;  A weekly sheet put out
by the Dole campaign describes Lamar Alexander thusly: &quot;Lamar
Alexander, a former Southern Governor like Bill Clinton&quot;
<P>
Reporters, seeking to be objective and fair, must be careful not
to pick up this kind of charged language.  Sometimes the biases
carried by different words can be more subtle.  For example, Jesse
Jackson argues that when speaking of affirmative action debate,
&quot;quotas&quot; and &quot;preferences&quot; are incorrect;
affirmative action is, he says, about &quot;goals, targets, and
timetables.&quot; 
<P>
<b>Additional Resources:</b>
<P><ul>
Tom Shachtman.  1995.  <I>The Inarticulate Society: Eloquence and
Culture in America</I>.  New York: Free Press.
<P>
Stephen A. Smith, ed.  1994.  <I>Bill Clinton on Stump, State and
Stage: The Rhetorical Road to the White House</I>.  Fayetteville:
University of Arkansas Press.
<P>
Kathleen Hall Jamieson.  1988.  <I>Eloquence in an Electronic Age:
The Transformation of Political Speechmaking</I>.  New York: Oxford
University Press.
<P>
William Safire.  1993.  <I>Safire's New Political Dictionary</I>.  New
York: Random House.
<P>
Nicholas Comfort.  1993.  <I>Brewer's Politics: A Phrase and Fable
Dictionary</I>.  London: Cassell Publishers Limited.  
<ul>
Although published in the U.K., this book has a solid dose of
American political lingo.
</ul></ul><P>
<center><small><a href="welcome.html">Vote America Home</a> | <a href="order.html.cgi">Order</a> | <a href="/townhall/">Town Hall</a><p>&copy; 1996 <a href="http://www.virtent.com">Virtual Entertainment</a></small></center>
 
</BODY>

</HTML>
