<html><head><title>VOTE AMERICA: Cutting Through the Blizzard of Messages</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="tile.gif">
<blockquote>
<center>
<a href="http://www.virtent.com"><img src="votelogo.gif" border="0"></a>
<P>
<h2>Cutting Through the Blizzard of Messages</h2>
</center>
<P>
This is a checklist of questions to ask yourself to better get to the root of the numerous statements you will hear during the upcoming elections.
<ul>
<h3>What is the ultimate source of the information?</h3>  
<ul>
A candidate.
<br>Someone in or affiliated with one of the campaigns.
<br> An expert, a think tank, or government statistics.
<br> An interest group.
<br> An ordinary citizen or voter expressing an opinion.
<P></ul>
<h3>Is the source credible and the information believable and
complete?</h3>
<ul> Clearly, when considering information from a partisan source,
one must be  careful.<br>
 The facts cited may be true, but present only part of the picture.
</ul><P>
<h3>Is this information relevant?</h3>
<ul>
 A lot of charges fly hither and yon during a political campaign.
 One needs  to ask not only if a specific charge is true, but
also whether it affects a  candidate's capacity to set a direction,
implement policies, respond to  difficult situations, and be an
effective leader.
</ul><P>
<h3>What are other, opposing sources saying about the subject?</h3>
<ul>
 Seeking out three or four different points of view is a good
way to clarify  one's own thinking on an issue.
</ul>
<h3>Is there some aspect of the debate that is not being represented?</h3>
<ul>
 The campaigns may not be addressing some of the more difficult
issues, and  the media do occasionally suffer from blind spots.
</ul>
<h3>What do I think?</h3>
<ul>
 Difficult problems usually do not lend themselves to quick solutions.
 Each  of the approaches put forth may have some merit.  Which
do you think is  best, and why? 
</ul></ul>
<P>
<center><small><a href="welcome.html">Vote America Home</a> | <a href="order.html.cgi">Order</a> | <a href="/townhall/">Town Hall</a><p>&copy; 1996 <a href="http://www.virtent.com">Virtual Entertainment</a></small></center>
</BODY>

</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT19-B27-193</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA086-000617-B001-21</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.cpac.org:80/ads/ve/advert.html 204.71.237.74 19970122022702 text/html 4388
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Wednesday, 22-Jan-97 02:27:18 GMT
Last-modified: Monday, 29-Jan-96 23:16:09 GMT
Content-length: 4202
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>VOTE AMERICA:  Watching Campaign Ads</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="tile.gif">
<blockquote>
<center>
<a href="http://www.virtent.com"><img src="votelogo.gif" border="0"></a>
<P>
<h2>Watching Campaign Ads</h2>
</center>
<P>
The campaigns spend vast sums to develop, produce, and air television
spots.  In the 1992 general election, about two-thirds of the
Bush and Clinton campaigns' funds went into advertising.  All
told, the Bush, Clinton, and Perot campaigns spent a total of
$133 million on television advertising in the fall.  Television
ads offer very highly refined versions of a campaign's messages--in
a sense they are &quot;pure&quot; message--and as such they merit
close attention. 
<P>
For television ads to be effective they must <B>fit within a broad
communication strategy</B> so that the same message is being presented
by the different parts of the campaign.  In an era of rampant
channel surfing, good political ads <B>stand out from the clutter
of commercial advertising and programming</B>.  Their <B>technical
quality</B> must be such that viewers are not paying attention
to poor lighting or sound, but to the message.  They must be <B>believable</B>.
 Devices used to achieve credibility include news clips, documented
statistics, endorsements, testimonials by ordinary citizens, and
the use of formal office settings.  And, very importantly, a good
ad <B>strikes &quot;a responsive chord;&quot;</B> it causes the
viewer to smile or tap his foot.
<P>
Consultants can make use of many different types of images in
putting together a campaign ad.  If the candidate performs well
on camera, he or she may be prominently featured.  Other ads use
stock footage and still photos of children in classrooms, people
at work, and so forth.  Clips of the candidate's opponent are
central to many attack ads.  Viewers draw meaning from the surroundings
the candidate is in, the people he or she is interacting with,
and the types of clothes he or she is wearing.  However, pictures
alone do not make a good ad.  Producers of political ads are skilled
at using all of the <B>aesthetic fields</B>--light and color,
space, time and motion, and sound to create and enhance moods.
   
<P>
It is easy to denounce 30-second spots as &quot;soap bubbles&quot;
or &quot;dirt&quot; that reduce the level of debate and manipulate
viewers' emotions.  It can also be argued that they distract us
from the real issues.  The principal problem with advertising
is not the blatantly wrong or false ad, but the many ads that
shade the truth.  Advertisements often attack a candidate on one
or two specific points, devaluing the sum of his or her record.
 While consultants argue that negative ads &quot;make democracy
work&quot; by educating people about the candidates, attacks may
also contribute to a cynical electorate.  Finally, complex problems
simply cannot be discussed in 30 seconds.
<P>
<ul>
<li>When you see or hear an ad consider what sort of appeal
it is making (logical, emotional, ethical, fear), what its purpose
is (bio, define the opponent, respond to an attack and launch
a counterattack), and whether it is fair.   
<P>
<li>If you come across an ad that is not fair or bends the truth,
respond.  Let the campaign and the station that airs it know exactly
what the fault is.
<P>
<li>Look in newspapers and news programming for ad watches,
in which reporters present and analyze the campaigns' ads. 
<P>
<li>Play theater critic.  Has the consultant made good use of
the aesthetic fields--light and color, space, time and motion,
and sound?  Is the ad effective?  Why or why not?
<P>
<li>Think about what program the ad is airing on and what audience
the campaign is trying to reach. 
<P>
<li>Keep track of the spots the candidate has been running in
the course of the campaign and try to discern major themes. 
</ul>
<P>
<br>
<center><small><a href="welcome.html">Vote America Home</a> | <a href="order.html.cgi">Order</a> | <a href="/townhall/">Town Hall</a><p>&copy; 1996 <a href="http://www.virtent.com">Virtual Entertainment</a></small></center>
</BODY>

