<html><head><title>Vitrual Entertainment's VOTE AMERICA</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="tile.gif">
<blockquote>
<center>
<a href="http://www.virtent.com"><img src="votelogo.gif" border="0"></a>
<P>
<h2>Be a better news consumer</h2>
</center>
<P>
Careful regard to one's news and information sources is more important
than the actual quantity of news one takes in.  Catching the 6:00
news or reading the newspaper doesn't always result in a complete
understanding of the issues. 
<P>
Even if you do not read the newspaper daily, there are steps you
can take to better assess the information that is out there.
<P>
<ul>
<li>Look beyond familiar news sources and consider how other
news organizations are covering the campaign.
<P>
<li>Think about whether your newspaper or news sources devote
well-defined and organized space/time to the campaign or whether
their focus could be improved.
<P>
<li>Pay attention to the sources used in news stories: is the
information coming from someone affiliated with one of the campaigns,
an interest group, an expert, a voter?
<P>
<li>The media provide versions of the truth.  There may be aspects
of an event or situation that are not being reported on at all,
or that are not being covered sufficiently.
<P>
<li>If you think your preferred media outlets can do better,
contact them and let them know specific ways in which you think
their coverage can be improved. (Is their coverage disorganized?
 Are they running to many horse race polls?)  In general, news
organizations are happy to find out that people are paying attention,
provided the input is well thought out.
</ul><P>
<center><small><a href="welcome.html">Vote America Home</a> | <a href="order.html.cgi">Order</a> | <a href="/townhall/">Town Hall</a><p>&copy; 1996 <a href="http://www.virtent.com">Virtual Entertainment</a></small></center>
