</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Vitrual Entertainment's VOTE AMERICA</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="tile.gif">
<blockquote>
<center>
<a href="http://www.virtent.com"><img src="votelogo.gif" border="0"></a>
<P>
<h2>Follow the Money</h2>
</center>
<P>
In April 1995, the New York Times Magazine ran a cover story on
Republican presidential hopeful Lamar Alexander with the headline
&quot;To Run for President, He Needs to Raise $77,000 a Day.&quot;
 Sen. Phil Gramm, another leading Republican candidate, says he
has the &quot;the most reliable friend that you can have in American
politics, and that's ready money.&quot;
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Given all the attention to fundraising in the lead-up to the primaries,
one might get the impression that money, rather than sound ideas,
is what makes a credible candidate.  The role of money in politics
has long been problematic, not just here in the United States,
but in democracies around the world.
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The system of presidential campaign finance in effect in the U.S.,
while not without its imperfections, is relatively simple in its
broad outlines.  During the primaries, partial public financing
provides qualifying candidates with matching funds from the U.S.
Treasury.  In the general election, candidates who agree to forgo
private money are fully funded.  The parties are also granted
money to put on their national conventions.  The money for these
payments comes from the Presidential Election Campaign Fund, which
is filled by the $3 check-off on individuals' federal income tax
forms and administered by the Federal Election Commission (FEC)
and the U.S. Treasury Department. 
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In 1974, in the aftermath of Watergate, Congress created the FEC
and established the current system of financing presidential elections,
including contribution limits, spending limits, disclosure requirements,
and public financing.  Public financing was introduced to address
several concerns:
<P><ul>
<li>The disproportionate influence (or the appearance of influence)
of wealthy contributors;
<P>
<li>The demands of fundraising that prevented some candidates
from adequately presenting their views to the public; and
<P>
<li>The increasing cost of presidential campaigns that effectively
disqualified candidates who did not have access to large sums
of money.
<br>
<small>Source: FEC.  <I>Report of the Presidential Public Funding Program</I>
(April 1993).</small>
</ul>
<P>
Public financing has recently come under increasing attack.  Participation
in the check-off has steadily declined.  In 1993, because of a
projected shortfall in the fund, Congress increased the check-off
to $3, up from the previous $1 level.  For 1993 returns, participation
in the tax form check-off was only 14.5 percent, despite a public
education campaign.  Given the fact that much of the money distributed
from the Fund goes to buy 30-second television spots, one can
understand why some people hesitate to take part.  In a June 1995
column, George Will described the program as &quot;an entitlement
for politicians, funded in a mendacious manner.&quot;  Sen. Mitch
McConnell (R-KY) has also been a harsh critic of public financing.
 
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Federal campaign finance laws have not been significantly changed
since 1979, and other shortcomings have become apparent.  For
example, the $1,000 contribution limit has never been adjusted;
by 1992, accounting for inflation, $1,000 was worth only $350.
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some would raise or do away with contribution limits altogether
(when you think about it, the idea that you as an individual can
only contribute $1,000 to a campaign is a pretty strong restriction,
but it was upheld by the Supreme Court in the famous 1976 Buckley
vs. Valeo decision).  At the opposite extreme, one has the example
of Jerry Brown.  In his 1992 Democratic primary campaign, Brown
issued a sweeping indictment of the role of money in politics,
limited himself to $100 contributions and ran a guerilla-style,
grassroots campaign.  On the downside, one can see that operating
under such conditions, politicians might actually have to spend
more time raising money than they do now.
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Another obvious problem with the current system is soft money.
 Corporations, unions, and wealthy individuals can contribute
unlimited amounts to the parties, provided the money is used for
state and local &quot;party-building&quot; activities.  Broad
interpretations of what exactly constitutes &quot;party building&quot;
have opened the soft money loophole.  Fred Wertheimer, former
head of Common Cause, has written that soft money &quot;threatens
to render meaningless all federal limits on campaign contributions
and to destroy the integrity of the presidential campaign finance
system.&quot;
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Enforcement is another weakness.  Former Democratic national chairman
Robert Strauss observed in a 1992 &quot;Frontline&quot; program
on PBS that, &quot;People are not really worried much about violating
the FEC rules.  They figure, 'What the heck, the election will
be over six months before it [a complaint] ever comes up' &quot;

<P>
<B>Primaries</B>
<ul><P>
<I>Eligibility</I>. To qualify for matching funds, a candidate must raise
$5,000 in each of 20 states, consisting of contributions of $250
or less from individuals.  This $100,000 threshold is intended
to distinguish candidates with broad national support.  Candidates
must also agree to abide by spending limits, keep acceptable records,
and undergo a detailed audit.
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;After eligibility is established, contributions of $250 or less
are matched dollar for dollar with money from the Treasury.
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For the 1992 prenomination period, the U.S. Treasury dispensed
$43.4 million to 12 candidates.  The maximum amount any candidate
could receive was $13,810,000.
<P>
<I>Spending limits</I>. The Federal Election Campaign Act established
limits on how much a campaign may spend prior to the convention.
 In 1992, the national spending limit was $27.62 million (this
is the original 1974 level of $10 million adjusted for inflation).
 </ul>
<P>
<B>Conventions</B>
<ul><P>
Each major party receives money from the U.S. Treasury to put
on its convention.  In 1992, the figure was $11.048 million.
</ul><P>
 <B>General Election</B>
<ul><P>
If a presidential candidate pledges not to accept private contributions,
he or she receives public financing in the general election. 
In 1992, the Bush and Clinton general election campaign committees
each received $55.24 million ($20 million adjusted for inflation)
from the U.S. Treasury.  Perot did not ask for public funds. 
He contributed more than $60 million to his campaign.  
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Supplementing the federal grants to the campaigns are several
other sources of money, including &quot;coordinated expenditures&quot;
made by the political parties to support their nominees and soft
money which often goes to voter registration and get-out-the-vote
efforts.
</ul><br><br><P>
<B>Additional Resources:</B>
<ul><P>
Federal Election Commission.  The FEC is responsible for interpreting
and enforcing campaign finance laws passed by Congress.  Federal
campaigns are required to file regular financial reports with
the FEC.  These can be viewed in the FEC's Public Records Office,
which is one of the most user-friendly offices in Washington,
D.C.  Rather than waiting in line at the Hard Rock Cafe next door,
stop in and learn about campaign finance!
<ul>
Federal Election Commission<br>
999 E Street, N.W.  <br>
Washington, DC  20463  <br>
Phone: (800) 424-9530
</ul><P>
Center for Responsive Politics.  The Center, a nonprofit, nonpartisan
research group founded in 1983, has become a reliable source of
information on the influence of money in American elections.
<ul>
Center for Responsive Politics
<br>1320 Nineteenth Street, N.W.  
<br>Washington, DC  20036<br>
Phone: (202) 857-0044  |  Fax: (202) 857-7809
<br>e-mail:  crp@igc.apc.org
internet:  gopher://gopher.crp.org:5050
</ul>
<P>
Common Cause.  A nonpartisan, nonprofit citizens' lobby campaigning
for honest and accountable government, Common Cause was founded
in 1970 by former HEW Secretary John Gardner.  Campaign finance
is one of the issues it has tackled.    
<ul>
Common Cause<br>
2030 M Street, N.W.  <br>
Washington, DC  20036<br>
Phone: (202) 833-1200  |  Fax: (202) 659-3716
</ul><P>
Herbert E. Alexander and Anthony Corrado.  1995.  <I>Financing the
1992 Election</I>.  Armonk, NY: M.E. Sharpe.
<P>
Anthony Corrado.  1993.  <I>Paying for Presidents: Public Financing
in National Elections</I>.  New York: The Twentieth Century Fund Press.
<P>
 Frank J. Sorauf.  1992.  <I>Inside Campaign Finance: Myths and Realities</I>.
 New Haven: Yale University Press.
<P>
<P>
<center><small><a href="welcome.html">Vote America Home</a> | <a href="order.html.cgi">Order</a> | <a href="/townhall/">Town Hall</a><p>&copy; 1996 <a href="http://www.virtent.com">Virtual Entertainment</a></small></center>
</BODY>

