<HTML>

<HEAD>
<title>Washington Report:  March 1996</title>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<center><table border>
<tr>
<img alt="Washington Report Logo" src="wlogo.gif"> </td>
</tr></table>
<p><h3>April 1996</h3><p>
<img src= "red-line.gif">
</center><p>




WASHINGTON REPORT

<ul><li>GOP presidential contender Alan Keyes finally got the national television exposure he has been working for throughout his campaign, although not exactly the kind he might have hoped for.  After twice trying to force his entry into the studios of WSB in Atlanta to crash the candidates' Mar. 3 debate, Keyes appeared on several national talk shows the following morning, including ABC's "Good Morning America," and said, "This is a disgrace to American democracy, but it's also a threat to the freedom of this country.  Party bosses or media bosses should not be allowed to select candidates in America."<p>
     Keyes added:  "This was an effort to manipulate the outcome and force the people. . .to vote for certain candidates by refusing to allow them to vote for others."<p>
     Keyes, who, along with other Republican candidates including Senator Richard Lugar, was not invited by the television station to debate, was taken into custody by police when he attempted to enter the studio a half-hour before the debate was set to begin.  Throughout the day, the former United Nations ambassador and a group of supporters had staged an extended fast in five pup tents set up on the studio's front lawn.
     <p>As Keyes was taken away by police, his supporters shouted, "Let him speak.  Let him speak."  Keyes was not arrested; rather, he was driven a short distance and released, whereupon Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell picked him up in his Lincoln Town Car.
    <p> Bill Nigut, WSB-TV political reporter and debate panelist, noted that other GOP candidates also weren't invited.  He said the station had no intention of reconsidering its decision not to invite Keyes.  In a written statement issued later, WSB-TV said inviting the top four vote getters offered Georgia voters "the most substantive debate."
    <p> However, in the future, the station and other organizations sponsoring debates would do well to establish the criteria before hand--and make the specifications public.
    <p> Despite single-digit support in nearly every state and an accumula-tion of less than 10 delegates, Keyes has vowed to stay in the race until the San Diego convention in August.  "Our commitment is to get out our message and spread our moral agenda," he said.
<p>
  <li>Elijah Cummings, the candidate with the most political experience, television ads and money, easily beat 26 other Democrats in the primary race to succeed Kweisi Mfume.  Republicans selected Kenneth Kondner, a dental technician.
   <p>  Cummings, a lawyer who has spent the past 13 years in the state House of Delegates, becomes a virtual shoo-in for election in Maryland's 7th District, where 83 percent of voters are registered Democrats.
   <p>  Though some had thought the Democratic race was up for grabs because of the crowded field, just two candidates split more than 60 percent of the vote in the Mar. 5 election.
   <p>  Cummings got 37 percent while the Rev. Frank Reid III, stepbrother of Mayor Kurt Schmoke, was second with 24 percent.  State Sen. Delores Kelley was next with 10 percent.
    <p> Knodner, 57, who ran unsuccessfully against Mfume three times, won the Republican nomination with 45 percent.
    <p> The voting, held in conjunction with the state's presidential primary, was the first congressional primary of the 1996 season.
    <p> Cummings, 44, raised more than $220,000--twice that of Reid--and spent it on a last-minute TV advertising blitz.  He promised to make crime fighting his top priority if he wins the general election.  Actually, the 7th District nominees will run in two elections--April 16 to serve the remainder of Mfume's term, and one Nov. 5 for the regular two-year term.
     <p>"We have a situation where people are afraid to come out of their houses," Cummings said.  "Eighty-five percent of all our crime problems stem from drugs."
     <p>In Maryland's seven other congressional districts, incumbents breezed to renomination.
     <p>Mfume, former head of the Congressional Black Caucus, was in the middle of his fifth term when he announced in December that he was taking over the presidency of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, based in Baltimore.
    <p> Mfume is one of 43 House members--27 of them Democrats--who are not seeking reelection this year.  Democrats would need to take 23 seats away from the GOP to regain control of the House.
Benjamin Chavis, national director of the Million Man March and ousted executive director of the NAACP, is asking local organizers of the march to raise an additional $150,000 to cover unpaid bills incurred by the march's national office.
     <p>According to a report in the Chicago Tribune, the appeal was included in a Feb. 2 letter from Chavis to local march organizers in some 350 cities inviting them to a meeting in Chicago.  It asked each city's local organizing committee to "make a minimum contribution of $1,000" by Feb. 24 "National Meeting of LOCs," or to bring the money with them.
     <p>The request came as a shock to many who helped raise money before the Oct. 16 event and then contributed what some thought to be millions more at the march.
     <p>Some local leaders were especially surprised that Chavis would expect them to donate more money or solicit contributions when national organizers have yet to produce a promised audit on march expenses.  "Until we get an accounting, we can't talk about any money--period," said Earl Hollis, a member of Chicago's local organizing committee.
     <p>Chavis said march organizers have paid $1.4 million in expenses for the march, though he would not specify what they were.  He said that the $150,000 debt comes from bills that didn't arrive until after the first of the year.
     <p>"The letter was an upbeat letter because we're pleased that we were able to meet 95 percent of the bills from money raised at the march and prior to the march and since the march," Chavis said in a Tribune interview.
     pHe said the audit has been delayed partly because of the late-coming bills.
     <p>Rev. James Demus, a co-chairman of Chicago's organizing committee, said he is prepared to launch a local fundraising campaign that may include letters to the 50,000 or more men who attended the march from the Chicago area.
    <p> But there clearly is resistance on the part of some march participants to bail out the national office.
    <p> Much of it is because the small-scale local efforts across the country that have carried out the work inspired by the march have virtually no ties to the national office and do not feel beholden to it.
    <p> "If they don't have enough money, let them worry about the money," said Bob Wilburn, president of Million Man Ministries, a group that has started at the Chicago-area Park Manor Christian Church.  "We've gotten together now a group of men that are doing something."
    <p> That attitude violates the spirit of the march, said Earl King, the Midwest Director of Chavis' National African-American Leadership Summit. "This is the first time ever a march has been paid for (solely) by African-American people," King said.  "This is about self-respect.  We have to be together in unity."
     <p>Despite the financial controversy surrounding the march, Nation of Islam Minister Louis Farrakhan continues to receive credit for his role in spearheading the march.  Farrakhan was in Washington, D.C. Mar. 14 to receive the 1995 Newsmaker of the Year Award from the National Newspaper Publishers Association at the National Press Club.  The association, representing about 200 black-owned newspapers, said Farrakhan was selected primarily for the vision he showed in putting together his Million Man March on the Washington Mall last year.
     <p>But Farrakhan received a letter recently from the U.S. government, which did not include good news.  The Treasury Department's Foreign Assets Control Office sent a letter in February advising the Nation of Islam minister that presidential orders under the International Emergency Economic Powers Act prohibit U.S. citizens from spending U.S. currency in several countries, including Libya and Iran among those visited by Farrakhan.
<p>
   <li>The forgotten patriots of the Revolutionary War, black men both free and slave who fought for liberty, may finally be remembered in a memorial on the National Mall--unless time runs out.
    <p> The nonprofit group raising funds for the memorial trumpeted its largest contribution ever on Feb. 29, a $1.5 million corporate commitment, and promised to get the rest, reported the Associated Press.
    <p> The decade-old project still needs $5 million more by October, or it risks losing congressional approval and its coveted site on the Mall, between the monuments to Washington and Lincoln.
     <p>In past years, the effort has been plagued by missteps and internal dissension.  Architect Marshall E. Purnell, who has been working on the plans from the beginning, said several times he feared the project would collapse.
     <p>"I've thought that on and off a lot," Purnell said, "but I refused to accept it.  It's too important an idea."
     <p>Approved by Congress in 1986, the monument would honor more than 5,000 black soldiers and sailors who fought in the Revolutionary War, as well as black men, women and children who helped build the colonies.
    <p> An escaped slave, Crispus Attucks, was the first American to die in the Revolution.  But organizers say many Americans have no idea that black soldiers fought alongside whites for independence.
    <p> A combination of two curved walls and sculpted figures by artist Ed Dwight, it would be the nation's second-largest bronze artwork, after the Statue of Liberty.
     <p>General Motors Corp., an early supporter of the project, donated $400,000 on Feb. 29 and pledged to raise $1.5 million more.
    <p> To meet its Oct. 27 deadline, the foundation must raise all the needed money and obtain final design approval, an expensive and time-consuming process.  The foundation missed two earlier deadlines and was granted extensions by Congress.  There is no guarantee of yet another extension.
     <p>Donations are accepted by telephone at 1-800-888-9811, or can be mailed to the Black Patriots Foundation, 1612 K St., N.W., Suite 1104, Washington, DC 20006.

<P><P>
