<HEAD>

<TITLE>Creating Competitive Markets in Electric Energy -- PFF</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Authorized Gateway Customer">
<META NAME="OPERATOR" CONTENT="Microsoft Corporation">
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<br>
<h2>Creating Competitive Markets in Electric Energy</h2>
<P>
<br>
<a href="#intro">Introduction</a><br>
<a href="#activities">The Project and Its Activities</a><br>
<a href="#structure">Program Structure</a><br>
<a href="#schedule">Project Schedule</a><P>
<br>
<a name="intro"></a>
&quot;Power-Hungry companies will be able to wheel for deals in
the future.&quot;  This is a headline not from <i>Financial Times</i>
or the <i><a href="http://www.wsj.com">Wall Street Journal</a></i> but rather from the <i>Charleston
Gazette</i> and it's about Appalachian Power Company and Monongahela
Power Company. On the same day the <i>Providence Journal-Bulletin</i>
carried a story about <i>Narragansett Electric's</i> proposals
to &quot;introduce competition in the sale of electricity in Rhode
Island.&quot;
<P>
Talk of competition in the electric utility industry is breaking
out all over the country.  This is no longer simply an idea discussed
in the ivory towers of academia or by &quot;policy wonks&quot;
in Washington or even Brussels.  This is what regulatory commissions,
utilities and big power users are talking about across America.
 Those whose business it is to know about electricity are all
talking about competition.   According to the cognoscente the
question is no longer if competition is coming to electric markets
but rather when it will come and how it will come.
<P>
Electric energy is a big industry in the U.S.  We are home to
nearly one-third of all the installed electric generating capacity
in the world.  Our investor-owned utilities have assets in excess
of $500 billion and total sales of electric energy are nearly
$200 billion a year.  Which is all in the way of saying we ought
to be very deliberate in the way we think about change in this
industry.  Change is coming, and while it is unproductive to resist
these market forces, managing the change, and developing transition-easing
strategies can pay large dividends.
<P>
The crucial public policy issue at this point, especially at the
federal level, is how we should restructure the rules of the game
so as to make the most of the current opportunity.  What would
be unfortunate would be a regulatory reform process that the major
players, i.e., the utilities and the regulators, resisted.  While
no regulatory change of this magnitude can preserve the status
quo for all participants, it can be a process in which all participants
 have an opportunity to take advantage of the change.  Reform
can be structured more like a market driven process where participants
can adjust and move, and less like a traditional bureaucratic
change that resembles a bolt of lightening both in its speed and
limited scope for mitigation.
<P>
Market discipline is far superior to bureaucratic regulation and
the federal government should be in the position of doing all
it can do to foster the substitution of market regulation for
bureaucratic regulation. FERC, PUHCA, PURPA and in the 1992 Energy
Policy Act were developed in the context of bureaucratically regulated
electric power industry;  all need major revision and, in some
cases, outright repeal.  The structure of the electric power market
is going to change and the federal government should be out ahead
laying tracks rather than simply being a passenger or, worse,
an obstacle to a more competitive market in electricity.
<P>
<a name="activities"></a>
<h3>The Project and Its Activities</h3>
<P>
The Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation is in the business of creating
replacement models to current federal regulatory bureaucracies.
 Examples of current projects include; an FCC replacement project
and a medical innovations project designed to replace the FDA.
 (See enclosed newspaper clips relating to these projects.)
<P>
What the Foundation is proposing to undertake with this project
is the design of an operational model which would provide the
legal structure necessary to create a vastly more competitive
electricity market.
<P>
<B>Creating a Competitive Marketplace:  </B>Our first task will
be to develop a policy agenda for the federal government aimed
at eliminating artificial constraints on the structure, scope
and activities of electric power producers.  For all its market-style
trappings, the bureaucratic regulation of electric power in the
United States is a close cousin of socialist central planning.
 The Soviet planners structured their industries to make them
easier to plan for; they vertically integrated at every opportunity,
they limited product availability; and they opted for large single
enterprise industries whenever possible.  Regulators and their
supporters in the U.S. behaved quite similarly, i.e., they attempted
to control industrial structure in ways that facilitated regulation.
 The Public Utility Holding Act (PUHCA) may have made some sense
as a structural limitation on utilities in 1935.  It makes little
sense in the current regulatory environment and will be even more
damaging in a competitive environment.  PUHCA is not an isolated
example.  PURPA, for all the positive, if unintended, effects
it has had on opening up the wholesale electric market, is also
a relic from the era of bureaucratic regulation.  We intend to
analyze all of the major structural and behavioral restrictions
placed on electric power producers by the federal government and
develop a feasible plan for the elimination of redundant and dysfunctional
restrictions.
<P>
<B>Leveling the Playing Field:</B>   Both for reasons of equity
and efficiency, we intend also to turn our attention  to the issue
of public ownership of electric utilities, especially federal
ownership of generating capacity.  The participants in the process
are unlikely to take seriously the federal government's claim
that it is out to reform the electric power industry unless it
is willing to address the issue of public power.  Right now, more
than seventeen percent of all electric energy generated in the
U.S. is produced by the federal government or the electric cooperatives.
Subsidized power, whether through a marketing authority or through
a governmental corporation like TVA, poses a problem in a competitive
environment.  Private producers who have to cover all of their
costs and cannot borrow at subsidized rates will be at a competitive
disadvantage with respect to these governmental entities.  Moreover,
it is the taxpayer who is financing a playing field tilted against
private enterprise.  The taxpayer is burdened either with outright
subsidies to these government enterprises, or more indirectly,
by providing subsidized capital to the customers of these government
utilities.
<P>
The Clinton Administration has recognized at least the fiscal
aspects of the problem. In their FY' 96 budget, they propose to
privatize four power marketing administrations (Alaska, Southeastern,
Southwestern, and Western) while they will net almost $4 billion
next year.  Moreover, the Administration suggests converting the
Bonneville Power Administration into a government corporation.
The fate of the Administration's proposal is very uncertain; historically,
proposals to privatize the federal government's power activities
have not fared well.
<P>
Our contribution here will be to develop a privatization plan
that recognizes the interest group nature of this political process
and  is designed to be accommodating enough to have a serious
chance of making it through the Congress.  Subsidized power has
a powerful constituency and only by recognizing this and crafting
a plan that attempts to deal with the subsidy issue can any privatization
proposal make it through the legislative process.  There has been
a substantial amount of privatization in the rest of the world
during the past decade, and we will draw on that experience to
help design an action plan for privatizing federal power production
and transmission.
<P>
<B>Nuclear Power:  </B>Although not ordinarily associated with
the issue of competitive electric supply, the nuclear regulatory
efforts of the federal government have a profound  effect on the
electric power market and will effect the course of any deregulation
effort.  Utilities with large nuclear capacity and those that
might benefit from such capacity may face special difficulties
as the market for energy becomes more competitive.  Existing regulatory
policy has all but eliminated the promise of nuclear power in
the future.  In the context of a thorough transformation of economic
regulation of power production and distribution, it is time to
revisit the nuclear regulatory issue.  
<P>
<B>Building a Competitive Market:  </B>Finally, we will assess
the central operational issues that arise in the development of
a &quot;state of the art&quot; competitive market in electric
energy.  Specifically, we will consider what the federal government's
role should be in developing:  (1) open entry to buy, sell and
transmit power; (2) a computerized regional dispatch of electric
energy that is based on property rights -- rights to inject or
withdraw power, rights of transmission access, rights to invest
and claim the benefits (or incur the losses) that accrue to such
investment; (3) a spot market for electric energy with both demand
side and supply side bidding; (4) contractual instruments that
allow market participants to transfer risk but not power; and
(5) a system of &quot;model&quot; or distance pricing.
<P>
The practical problems of moving from the current bureaucratically
regulated industry and balkanized transmission grid to a market-disciplined
system with a transmission grid that is essentially a competitively-ruled
joint venture are immense.  The so called &quot;stranded investment&quot;
problem and the related &quot;stranded contract&quot; problem
have to be resolved.  Mechanisms must be designed to ease the
transition to competition by firms that have operated and invested
in a sheltered regulatory environment.
<P>
<B>Remaining Issues:  </B>Much of the talk now is how the utilities
will need to &quot;protect&quot; the residential rate payer in
the era of competition.  The assumption seems to be that only
the large users of electricity will be able to play the competition
game.  Some of this talk may simply be subterfuge aimed at enlisting
homeowners in an effort to protect utilities; but most is likely
to reflect conventional wisdom.  There really does not appear
to be any reason why the benefits of competition must be restricted
to large users.  As part of this project, we will investigate
what the federal government might to do encourage the development
of competitive supply for households.  What we have in mind here
are not subsidy programs, but rather creating a market structure
where the government helps create the property right system and
rules of the game that encourage the development of competitive
provision of electric power to the small user.
<P>
We will also considered the federal government's purchases of
electric  power and the ways theses purchases can stimulate the
development of competition.  For example, the government may be
able to create model demonstrations to competitive electric markets
from which regulators and law makers can learn.
<P>
<a name="structure"></a>
<h3>Program Structure</h3>
<P>
 
<P>
 The Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation will provide overall direction
for the project and will have ultimate responsibility for the
final product.
<P>
<B>Project Team:</B>  The team working on this project will include
economists and lawyers with expertise in regulated network industries,
privatization, institutional design, restructuring, and experimental
economics.  Included on the team will be:  Dr. Michael K. Block,
Professor of Law and Economics, University of Arizona (Project
Director); Dr. Thomas Lenard, Senior Fellow and Director of Regulatory
Studies, The Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation; Dr. Vernon Smith,
Regents Professor of Economics, University of Arizona; Dr. Steve
Rassenti, Research Director, Economic Science Laboratory, University
of Arizona; and Dr. Richard Geddes, Associate Professor of Economics,
Fordham University.
<P>
<B>Advisory Committee:</B>  The project will be assisted by an
advisory committee of experts from academia, the utility industry,
and the public policy community.  These experts will provide continuous
input and guidance as the project progresses.
<P>
<a name="schedule"></a>
<h3>Project Schedule</h3>
<P>
<B>I. Project Design:</B>  This project will be conducted in three
phases: The first phase of the project will involve background
research and outreach within the electric power community, selection
of members for the Advisory Committee as  well as research on
reform proposal on PUCHA and related issues.  The second phase
of the project will involve research for the preparation of a
reform proposals on public power and on nuclear energy regulation.
 The third and final phase of the project will involve research
for preparation of a reform proposal on facilitating a competitive
market in electricity.
<P>
<B>II. Timing:  </B>The project team will work with the Advisory
Committee to produce a Draft Proposal on reforming electric industry
regulation (PUCHA etc.) to be circulated during the fall of 1995.
 This term will also prepare Draft Proposals in reforming public
power and nuclear regulation for circulation during the spring
of 1996 and a Draft Proposal on establishing a competitive market
in electric power to be circulated during the fall of 1996.
<P>
The PFF proposals will be the subject of a number of conferences
during the project period including a major conference on the
competitive electric power market proposal will be held during
the winter of 1996.
<P>
<B>III. Public Education:</B>  The project will involve a substantial
effort to educate civic leaders, public interest groups, academic
and intellectual leaders, the electric energy community and the
public at large about the need for reform.  Through press briefings,
op-eds, appearances on television programs, participation in conferences,
testimony before Congressional committees and similar activities,
PFF will seek maximum exposure for the proposal and its underlying
rationale.
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="footer.map"><img src="footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center>
