<head>
<title>A New Approach For Bringing Medical Products to Market -- PFF</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<h2>The Future of Medical Innovation: A New Approach For Bringing Medical Products to Market</h2>

<b>By Thomas M. Lenard, Ralph A. Epstein, Robert D. Tollison, W. Kip Viscusi
and William M. Wardell</b>
</center>
<p>
<h3>Introduction and Summary</h3>

The United States is the world's leader in biomedical research:  in public sector
spending through the National Institutes of Health and other government agencies;
in private sector research and development; in the dramatic scientific
discoveries that all this research has produced; and, in manufacturing the drugs,
diagnostics and medical devices that apply these breakthroughs to improving human
health.  It has, however, become increasingly difficult to bring these beneficial
new medical products to the market.<p>

<a href="#references">Numerous studies</a> provide convincing
evidence of the discouraging effect our current regulatory structure has on the
development of new products. Americans obtain access to fewer new drugs and
devices and receive them later than they should.  America's procedures for
bringing new products to patients are among the slowest and most expensive in the
developed world, and it is now routine for new drugs and devices to be available
in other countries before they become available here.<p>

Sick patients need safer and more effective medical products--drugs, diagnostics
and devices.  However, these products are not being brought to the market in a
timely manner because the development process for new medical products in the
United States has become increasingly lengthy, expensive and complex.  In the
case of drug development, for example, the number of new chemical entities
entering clinical research and those ultimately approved for marketing has not
increased over the past 30 years, despite a ten-fold real increase in the
industry's research expenditures and stunning scientific advances, such as the
emergence of the whole new field of biotechnology.1  Although there are many
reasons for this stagnation, U.S. regulatory demands and delays are very
significant factors.<p>

There is a general consensus among the American public, as well as the regulated
pharmaceutical and medical device industries, that the fundamental premises
underlying the current drug and device approval processes are sound--that medical
products should meet appropriate safety standards, defined in terms of the
relationship between benefits and risks; that they should produce the therapeutic
effect and perform as claimed; and, that they should be evaluated by qualified
experts on the basis of adequate data.  There is also, however, widespread
concern among both industry and patient representatives about the
innovation-inhibiting effects of the way these standards have been implemented. 
This concern began soon after enactment of the Federal Food, Drug, and Cosmetic
Act of 1938, and increased greatly after passage of the 1962 Amendments to the
Act.<p>

The fact that most of the significant reforms still have not been adopted,
despite a drumbeat of almost identical recommendations over more than three
decades, suggests that this system will not be able to reform itself.
The essential criticism of the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) is that the
procedures it has established to implement its statutory mandate are too costly,
complex, time-consuming and unpredictable.  The result is that safe and effective
products are delayed in reaching consumers.  Numerous blue ribbon panels have
examined these issues, most recently the Commission on the Federal Drug Approval
Process (MacMahon Committee, 1982); the National Committee to Review Current
Procedures for Approval of New Drugs for Cancer and AIDs (Lasagna Committee,
1990); and, the Department of Health and Human Services Advisory Committee on the
Food and Drug Administration (Edwards Committee, 1991).  Each of these panels
recognized the need for a faster and less costly drug development process.  In
1991, the Vice President's Council on Competitiveness distilled the best of the
panels' recommendations and made them the basis of a Bush Administration
initiative.  The fact that most of the significant reforms still have not been
adopted, despite a drumbeat of almost identical recommendations over more than
three decades, suggests that this system will not be able to reform itself.<p>

Safety is a twofold concern.  Keeping dangerous medical products off the market
promotes safety, but keeping beneficial products off the market has the opposite
effect.  Depriving patients of beneficial products imposes significant costs on
them in the form of morbidity, reduced quality of life, lost wages, longer
hospital stays and, even, loss of life.  In this regulatory context, more
stringent regulations are not necessarily safer.  Indeed, every FDA Commissioner
in the last 30 years has publicly acknowledged that the failure to approve
important new products can be detrimental to the public health.2<p>

Under America's current system, the only route to market for a new drug or device
is through the FDA.  Standard economic theory predicts that a certification
monopoly, such as the FDA, will raise the cost for approvals, while limiting
their quantity.  The FDA's status as a government entity creates an additional
imbalance in the incentives faced by the agency.  Manufacturers, not the FDA,
receive any gains realized from the earlier approval of medical products.  Yet if
problems arise from earlier approval, the FDA bears immediate costs in the form
of a public outcry, sensational media coverage and being grilled by Congressional
overseers.  Thus, one expects to see what we in fact observe--a very strong
incentive to keep unsafe products off the market at the expense of also blocking
beneficial new products.<p>

The system as now configured deprives patients of life-saving and life-enhancing
products that never come to market because the overall costs of innovation have
been driven too high.<p>

What are the effects on the drug and device industries of delegating the approval
process to a risk-averse agency operating in a political environment?  Here
again, the expectation is exactly what the empirical record reveals.  The return
to research has fallen and become more uncertain, resulting in less domestic
product development.  We also observe "approval arbitrage,"  whereby companies
concentrate their R&D efforts overseas where the regulatory burden is less
onerous.  The high regulatory costs and increased uncertainty also deter new
entrants into the drug and device industries, reducing the pool of capital
available for funding new research.  Ultimately, the system as now configured
deprives patients of life-saving and life-enhancing products that never come to
market because the overall costs of innovation have been driven too high.<p>

The slowness of the FDA process for approving products already on the market for
new uses deprives patients and their doctors of critically important information
for long periods of time--long after the scientific evidence is available that a
treatment may be beneficial for a particular condition.  The biomedical research
industry is an information industry, and the FDA's principal functions should in
one way or another be related to getting more information to doctors and the
public.  Yet manufacturers are prohibited by the FDA from disseminating much
valuable information about their products.  Roughly half of all drugs, including
many of those for children, are prescribed for unapproved "off-label" uses,
because doctors believe the evidence shows they are effective in such conditions.
 
The FDA prohibits manufacturers from marketing drugs for these uses until full
evidence is available, presented and reviewed (just as for a new drug).  But such
"supplemental" New Drug Approvals have a low priority for review at the FDA, and
sometimes take longer than for a new drug.3  Thus, for example, manufacturers
cannot circulate to physicians the results of National Institutes of Health
studies of off-label cancer treatments.  At the same time, however, a
pediatrician who withheld a drug from a sick child simply because it was not
labeled for that indication could be subject to a charge of malpractice.4<p>

Yet manufacturers are prohibited by the FDA from disseminating much valuable
information about their products.<p>

The regulation of drugs and medical devices can only be justified to the extent
that there is a net benefit to patients.  With this in mind, the authors of this
report propose a new institutional arrangement to ensure the safety and
effectiveness of new drugs and medical devices.  Our proposed system would
separate oversight of the drug and device development process from the
government's role in maintaining and enforcing legally mandated safety and
effectiveness standards.  The latter functions would be retained in the
government.  Oversight of a product's movement through the various stages of the
development process and review of the scientific studies obtained would be moved
to the private sector, performed by experts at centers of medical excellence and
other private entities licensed by the FDA to ensure they meet necessary
standards and qualifications.  Manufacturers of drugs and devices would have a
choice of organizations to oversee their product's development in light of the
applicable standards.  Competition among these organizations would produce a
lower-cost, faster and higher-quality drug and device development and review
process.  The competitive oversight process would be performed under the same
framework of safety and effectiveness standards as currently exist (in the case
of drugs), or a revised, more rational set of standards (for devices).  This
proposal would expedite the development and approval process for health-enhancing
new products while not compromising safety or government monitoring of the
required safety standards.<p>

<h2>The Revolution in Medical Knowledge and Technology 5</h2>

Rapid advances in information technology are transforming many industries, and
nowhere is that more evident than in medicine.  The combination of computers,
sensors, and imaging systems--CAT and PET scans and MRI--are replacing invasive
procedures and "exploratory" surgery.  Microscopic cameras and microscopic tools
are making Fantastic Voyage seem not so far fetched.  Already, physicians have
tested a "virtual colonoscopy" that couples a virtual-reality imaging system with
a CAT scan.  Without inserting an instrument, the physician can "fly" through the
patient's colon on screen, searching for signs of disease.  In addition to
creating such medical devices, data processing capabilities promise to allow far
more efficient tracking of treatments and outcomes for large numbers of patients,
allowing successful medical strategies to be identified.<p>

This rapid pace of progress in information technology is more than matched by the
explosion of knowledge about the genetic and molecular foundation of life--a
result of the application of the new biotechnology.  This new knowledge provides
us with a far better understanding of the causes of diseases, and a far better
ability to design treatments or prophylaxis.  We can identify a "typo" in an
individual gene and are learning how to correct it.  We are beginning to
understand the complex mechanisms by which genes are turned on and off, and how
cancer, autoimmune and other diseases result when these mechanisms go awry.<p>

This proposal would expedite the development and approval process for
health-enhancing new products while not compromising safety or government
monitoring of the required safety standards.<p>

Modern medical technology enables us to know far more than was previously
possible about the causes and likely remedies for a wide range of illnesses. 
Identification of genetic defects has expanded exponentially; already, two
children with Severe Combined Immune Deficiency6 have been treated with
corrective genes.  The recent identification of the cystic fibrosis (CF) gene may
make possible a similar gene therapy approach.  Gene therapy is also being
attempted for cancer, a disease with genetic components.  For more than a decade,
patients have been treated with the protein products of human genes--such as
human growth hormone and human insulin--which are manufactured by genetically
modified organisms that produce the human protein.  There are several advantages
to using microorganisms to manufacture human proteins.  One major advantage of
many of these genetically engineered biologicals is that they can be made to
match perfectly the human version (so that diabetics can use human, rather than
pig, insulin).  In addition, there is no chance of contamination with
adventitious agents, such as viruses (as can be the case when the same product is
obtained from animal or human donors).  Even when the source of the drug is
cultured mammalian cells, sensitive techniques derived from the new biotechnology
permit the detection of even small amounts of contaminants.<p>

When human donors must be used--as is still the case with blood and other organ
transplants--biotechnology supplies sensitive diagnostic tests to identify known
dangerous contamination or tissue mismatch.  New biotechnology-based tests for
exposure to HIV-1 and the hepatitis viruses are essential to assuring the safety
of the U.S. blood supply.<p>

Despite skyrocketing research and development budgets, there has been no
corresponding increase in the flow of new drugs and devices to the market.
Genetic engineering brings special advantages to the production of vaccines.  In
the past, a pathogen most often was either killed or genetically weakened before
being administered.  On occasion, such as the first vaccine for Hepatitis B, the
vaccine was purified from an undesirable source--the pooled plasma of patients
with chronic active Hepatitis.  These preparations required careful quality
control to ensure that each individual batch was both active (as an immunogen)
but contained no adventitious agents.  The new biotechnology allows us to
construct vaccines that do not depend on whole microbes.  Instead, key
components, such as the surface antigen of the Hepatitis B virus, can be
manufactured synthetically through biotechnology.  The new biotechnology thus
offers several alternatives that make vaccines safer and more effective.  For
example, the first genetically engineered Hepatitis vaccine consisted of a single
protein highly purified from baker's yeast, which had been genetically
programmed.<p>

In addition, improved understanding of the genetic and molecular basis of the
immune function has made possible therapies for various auto-immune diseases, as
well as offering the possibility of enhancing the immune response to infectious
agents.<p>

Human gene therapy--the substitution or modulation of genes in a patient's
tissues--offers the possibility of correcting genetic defects, as well as new
kinds of therapies for malignancies, blood dyscrasias, infectious diseases, and
heart disease.<p>

Biotechnology also provides tools for identifying and studying the pathogens that
cause infectious diseases.  While satisfactory progress against AIDS has been
frustratingly difficult to achieve, scientists are vastly more knowledgeable than
they would be without the tools of the new biotechnology.  Other biotechnology
applications in medicine include diagnostic applications based on monoclonal
antibodies and DNA probes, biopolymers or synthetic tissues used for implants,
prosthetics and other clinical uses.<p>

<h2>From Laboratory to Patient--Research and Development in Medical Innovation</h2><p>

Despite skyrocketing research and development budgets--with industry spending $14
billion and NIH spending $11 billion annually--there has been no corresponding
increase in the flow of new drugs and devices to the market.7  The industry's
research spending, after adjusting for inflation, is ten times the level it was
in the early 1960s.  In contrast, the output of approved new molecular entities
has not increased since the Kefauver-Harris Amendments of 1962, and remains far
below the pre-1962 level.  In the medical device field, the number of premarket
approval applications decreased from 78 in 1990 to 40 in 1993, while the time for
approval increased from 609 to 823 days.8  These are sobering facts, in the face
of the large increases in research budgets and the availability of totally new
sciences, such as biotechnology and powerful computing, since the early 1960s.<p>

To the extent that we reduce regulatory costs, we increase the flow of capital to
this market and hence the flow of beneficial new products to physicians and
patients.<p>

The discovery and development of pharmaceuticals and medical devices is a
time-consuming, uncertain process that requires years of expensive laboratory
work, pre-clinical and, ultimately, clinical testing.  It now takes approximately
15 years to bring a drug to the market, at an average cost that has been
estimated at close to $400 million.9  Only a small fraction of laboratory
investigations yield a compound suitable for animal studies, and only a small
fraction of those are in turn promising enough to warrant clinical testing in
humans.  Many years of costs are incurred before there is even a slight chance of
patients receiving new medicines and of companies earning returns on their
investment.  This is of special significance for start-up companies, such as the
many small biotechnology and device firms, which have no products bringing in
revenue while they invest heavily in researching new products.<p>

The enormous uncertainties associated with the R&D process are dominant factors,
not only for biotechnology firms, but for the medical technology sector
generally.  At the most basic level is the scientific risk associated with the
research.  Researchers cannot predict in advance what is going to work, how well
or when.  If the science does work out in some form, and a product can be brought
to market, what will the conditions of the market be?  How much competition will
there be, here and abroad?  Will other scientific developments quickly make this
new product obsolete, perhaps even before it is ready?  Investing in intellectual
property carries its own particular risks, since investors cannot be sure that,
years later, they will still own that for which they paid.  Talented individuals
represent significant assets and cannot be indentured.  Only patentable
inventions have secure value, and the patent process has its own risks and
limitations<p>

Additional uncertainty can be created by government or private health-care
financing rules.  Patients may not have coverage for new treatments (regardless
of whether they are approved by the FDA).  Or the price paid by health care
programs may be too low to fully recover research and development costs.<p>

On top of these significant scientific and market risks, the FDA approval process
creates its own major uncertainties, with respect both to ultimate approval and
the time and expense required to get there.  FDA negativity at any stage of the
process can reduce the value of a firm and raise its effective cost of capital
overnight, especially for small companies without diversified (or even marketed)
product lines.  These regulatory uncertainties reduce the returns from research
and development in the pharmaceutical and device sectors and, therefore, the
number of new therapeutic products that can be developed by individual companies
and, through the investment climate that results, the industry as a whole.<p>

Many costs and risks are intrinsic to the product development process itself. 
regulatory costs are the only component of development costs over which society
exercises control, and some of these costs are clearly avoidable.  To the extent
that we reduce regulatory costs--and the drag they exert on innovation--we
increase the flow of capital to this market and hence the flow of beneficial new
products to physicians and patients.<p>

<h2>From Helping to Hindering the Market--A Brief Historical Review of Drug and Device Approval</h2><p>

Pharmaceuticals regulation always has been appropriately concerned with
information.  Sellers of medical products frequently know more about their
products than buyers, and this can be harmful to the proper functioning of the
market.  But over the years the focus of drug regulation has shifted, from trying
to correct this information asymmetry to the regulator becoming a central
participant in the basic processes of generating and disseminating information
throughout the major phases of a product's development and marketing.10<p>

Attention must therefore be focused on the FDA's approval and oversight criteria
for the NDA and IND processes, respectively, rather than simply focusing on the
final review period.<p>

The purpose of the Pure Food and Drug Act of 1906, the first major piece of drug
legislation, was to provide consumers with accurate information about the quality
of products they were purchasing.  False and misleading claims about drugs and
their contents were prohibited, and manufacturers were made liable for
adulterated or misbranded drugs.<p>

The Federal Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act of 1938 established the requirement for
the government to be notified before a drug could be marketed.  Manufacturers
were required to test for safety in animals and humans and submit those test
results to the FDA for review.  If the FDA did not disapprove within 60 days, the
drug was cleared for marketing.  The process was far shorter and the FDA's role
more limited than now.<p>

The Drug Amendments of 1962 ushered in the current regulatory regime for drugs. 
First, they required that manufacturers provide premarket evidence of
effectiveness as well as safety.  Second, and most importantly, they changed the
drug approval process from premarket notification to premarket approval.  The FDA
is required to explicitly approve a New Drug Application (NDA) rather than simply
let it become effective through inaction.  Although not required by the
legislation, at this time the FDA decided to exercise control over the clinical
testing phase by issuing new regulations requiring that sponsors submit to FDA a
notice of claimed exemption for an investigational new drug (IND) before entering
into clinical testing.<p>

Thus, the 1962 Amendments marked a major change in the FDA's role in
pharmaceutical regulation--from essentially being a reviewer and evaluator of
information to playing a central role in the conduct of clinical research,
through specifying in great detail the goals of clinical research and the manner
in which it is practiced.  FDA now judges in detail the protocols for the
clinical trials undertaken prior to the NDA, evaluates the data and may require
additional testing.  After approval, the FDA regulates what manufacturers can say
about their products, by ensuring that statements do not venture outside the
approved "label."<p>

There are two kinds of mistakes government reviewers can make:  (1) approving a
product that turns out to be dangerous; and, (2) blocking or delaying a product
that would have been beneficial.<p>

For almost 40 years after the passage of the Federal Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act
of 1938, there was little governmental regulation of medical devices, because of
the general view that drugs and devices are fundamentally different.  Drugs
generally are responsible for specific clinical effects.  Devices more often are
part of a system and usually have no specific clinical effect by themselves. 
Thus, the purpose of an antibiotic drug is to cure an infectious disease and
proof of its effectiveness requires the completion of well-controlled clinical
studies.  The pump that delivers the antibiotic has no specific therapeutic
properties, and cannot be evaluated primarily by clinical experiments.  Rather,
there needs to be assurance that the device will perform as claimed by the
manufacturer.  Devices are thus generally judged by how well they conform to the
manufacturer's description and to established standards.<p>

The process of innovation in devices is also quite different from that of drugs. 
Each drug is a unique compound.  Except for dosage form, drugs are not modified
after they are synthesized or discovered.  Any modification in the structure of a
therapeutic compound produces a brand new entity which needs to be tested anew. <p>

Innovation in devices, on the other hand, is generally incremental.  Experience
in use often suggests very small changes which cumulatively allow for significant
improvements.  A successful drug will remain on the market for many years, while
a successful device may undergo improvements almost continuously.  The rapidity
of device changes has increased as more and more functions are controlled by
software, which is relatively easy to modify.  <p>

For these and other reasons, device regulation throughout the developed world has
differed qualitatively from drug regulation.  The 1976 amendments to the Federal
Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act marked the beginning of systematic federal
regulation of medical devices.  The law divided devices into three classes. 
Class I devices, which the authors of the law thought would apply to most
devices, were required to have accurate labeling and an orderly manufacturing
process.  No governmental permission was required before marketing.  Most other
devices were placed in Class II.  Such devices also had to conform to
governmentally approved performance standards.  The manufacturer was required to
notify the government before marketing but advanced permission was not required. 
Finally, a small number of devices for which conformance with performance
standards was not sufficient, were required to have prior governmental permission
to allow marketing.<p>

The institutional pressures faced by FDA do not recognize that equal weight
should be given to the costs to patients when beneficial products are kept off
the market.
Most devices have gone through a process that applies to devices that can be
shown to be "substantially equivalent" to products already on the market--the
"section 510(k)" process.  Such devices are put in the same class as the older
predicate device and allowed to come to market.  While the 1976 law merely
required that the manufacturer notify the FDA of this "substantial equivalence"
90 days prior to marketing the device, the FDA has used its power to gradually
convert this "notification" process to an "approval" process and more and more to
extend the 90-day period.  Truly new devices have been placed in Class III and
required to undergo a premarket approval (PMA) process which, with the passage of
time, has become more and more like a drug approval process.  The 1990 amendments
codified what had become FDA practice, making explicit that the FDA had to
approve all devices prior to marketing.<p>

Recognizing the inverse relationship between the length of the approval process
and the effective remaining patent life, and in response to evidence that the
average effective patent life for products subject to the FDA review and approval
process was declining as the development process lengthened, Congress passed
legislation in 1984 increasing patent life for pharmaceuticals and medical
devices for up to five years.  At the same time, Congress gave FDA the authority
to approve abbreviated NDAs for generic drugs, after the period of market
exclusivity expired.  The result was a substantial easing of the requirements for
the approval of generic drugs.<p>

An important corollary of the current drug approval process is that manufacturers
are precluded from disseminating any information on the effectiveness or safety
of their products, unless such data have been included in an approved NDA. 
Similar restrictions apply to manufacturers of medical devices.  Adding new
information to a drug "label" normally requires submitting a supplemental NDA. 
These usually are low priority items at the FDA, since the product is already on
the market, and may take longer than NDAs for new products.<p>

Physicians, however, are free to prescribe approved products for applications
other than those in the NDA, and it is estimated that roughly half of all drugs
are prescribed for "off-label" uses.11  Nonetheless, manufacturers are not
allowed to refer to any published studies, including refereed journal articles or
textbooks, in their promotional materials or to sponsor educational symposia
about new uses.  They cannot, therefore, tell you or your doctor about research
results on such subjects as the effects of aspirin on heart attacks or of
estrogen on cancer.12  Device manufacturers face comparable restrictions in the
kinds of hands-on demonstrations they can offer physicians.  These restrictions
deprive doctors and their patients of valuable information.<p>

<h2>The Development Process for Drugs</h2>

The development of new drugs is undertaken by a sponsor, which typically is a
drug firm, but also can be a federal agency, hospital, clinic or research
institution.  After the synthesis or discovery phase, development generally
begins with the screening of a great many chemical compounds in laboratory
animals to determine possible therapeutic activity and toxicology information.<p>

The percentage of drugs that are first available in the United States is low.
When laboratory and animal studies suggest that a compound may be therapeutically
promising, the sponsor submits an IND to the FDA in order to begin clinical
testing, which introduces the drug into humans for the first time.  The primary
criterion for permitting clinical research to start is whether the overall
risk/benefit considerations warrant research on human subjects.  Currently, the
IND "approval" process occurs in two stages--a review by the FDA and an approval
by an institutional review board (IRB).  All institutions at which clinical
research is performed have IRBs responsible for reviewing whether it is safe for
patients to participate in the clinical study, whether any risks are justified by
the potential benefits, and whether the rights of the patients as experimental
subjects are protected.<p>

At this stage, the FDA also assesses the safety of the proposed research,
performing a comprehensive review of the sponsor's physico-chemical studies of
the product's identity and purity, the animal safety data and the details of the
proposed clinical trial, particularly the dosage proposed.  During the remainder
of the clinical research phase, the FDA continues to review proposals and data in
these three critical areas--physico-chemical, animal and clinical--and, if asked
by the sponsor, advises on an IND program that may result in a successful NDA
submission.<p>

The clinical trial process for drugs consists of three phases.  Phase I trials,
which involve a small number of healthy adults, are designed to elicit
information about "the metabolism and pharmacologic actions of the drugs in
humans, [and] the side effects associated with increasing doses."13  These tests
are largely intended to provide information pertaining to the product's safety.<p>

If the phase I trials are successful, the sponsor proceeds to phase II trials,
which involve testing the drug on individuals who suffer from the disease or
condition targeted by the drug.  The phase II trials are "conducted to evaluate
the effectiveness of the drug for a particular indication or indications in
patients with the disease or condition under study."14  In addition, these trials
are intended to assess whether there are unacceptable adverse side effects
associated with the drug.<p>

If the phase II trials show some evidence of therapeutic effect, the sponsor
proceeds to phase III clinical trials involving a larger number of patients who
also have the specific condition or disease addressed by the drug.15  At the
conclusion of this phase, the sponsor submits the NDA, which is a compendium of
all the available data regarding the performance of the drug relating to its
safety and effectiveness.  The NDA must also include information pertaining to
the proposed labeling for the new drug.16<p>

He indicated that American patients are sometimes receiving therapies that are
two-to-three generations behind those available in Europe, Canada and Japan.
The studies performed during the development of a compound are submitted to the
FDA in three sections:  chemistry, manufacturing and controls; pre-clinical; and
clinical.  The clinical section, containing the human safety and effectiveness
data, is clearly the most important.<p>

In evaluating the NDA, the FDA must ensure that the product complies with the
Federal Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act requirements pertaining to safety, and that
"substantial evidence" of effectiveness be demonstrated.  This stage of the drug
approval process is often quite lengthy.  In many cases, delay arises because the
FDA requests new information from the sponsor.<p>

A large part of the NDA review is devoted to ensuring that the data are valid,
representative, correctly analyzed and reported; and to making the final
risk-benefit judgment.  This critical decision determines whether safety and
effectiveness have been demonstrated in the overall treatment group or in any
appropriately identified subset, and what therapeutic claims, directions, dosages
and warnings are to be included in the labeling.  While the evaluation process is
in principle straightforward, it may be complicated by a number of factors,
including the volume of data submitted, the variety of expertise needed to assess
the data properly and the subtleties involved in the balancing of risks and
benefits.<p>

In the long run, most NDA submissions (over 80 percent) are eventually approved
by the FDA, although final approval frequently comes after considerable time,
negotiation and the submission of additional data.17  Reduction in this time,
while desirable, will not greatly affect the overall time required for drug
development, review and approval.  Attention must therefore be focused on the
FDA's approval and oversight criteria for the NDA and IND processes,
respectively, rather than simply focusing on the final review period.<p>

<h2>Adverse Effects of Regulatory Oversight, Control, and Review</h2>

These effects cannot be remedied by tinkering with the current system, because
they reflect a systemic problem.  The skewed institutional incentives faced by
FDA will always cause the agency to err on the side of keeping products off the
market.
The goal of regulatory review of new medical products is to block ineffective or
dangerous products while permitting beneficial ones to go forward.  There are two
kinds of mistakes government reviewers can make:  (1) approving a product that
turns out to be dangerous; and, (2) blocking or delaying a product that would
have been beneficial.  While both types of mistakes impose serious consequences
on patients, they are not viewed as equally serious by regulators.  Victims of
the first type of mistake, approving a product that turns out to be dangerous,
often are very visible, provoking Congressional hearings, public outcry,
sensational media coverage and perhaps damage to the careers of FDA reviewers. 
This "Congressional-fishbowl syndrome" provides a strong disincentive to approve
something that has even a remote potential of having unexpected negative effects.
 Mistakes of the second type, however, often go unseen.  Victims of a delay in or
disapproval of a beneficial product are not readily observed.18  The costs in
terms of morbidity or mortality of the second type of mistake, therefore, are not
readily apparent and are difficult to quantify.  These factors conspire to create
strong incentives for reviewers to err on the side of conservatism and caution,
and to require an overabundance of proof before approving new products.<p>

A regulator can always ask for additional information and increase statistical
precision by requiring additional testing.  And this may improve the chances of
detecting problems in a new drug or medical device, although the returns from
additional data gathering diminish sharply at some point.  The institutional
pressures faced by FDA do not recognize that equal weight should be given to the
costs to patients when beneficial products are kept off the market.<p>

There is a substantial consensus by students of the regulatory process that the
1962 Amendments have slowed the rate of pharmaceutical innovation.  A series of
studies by prominent researchers found that the 1962 Amendments and ensuing
regulations had a significant adverse effect on the introduction of new chemical
entities, after controlling for the influence of other factors.19  Recent data
indicate no diminution in the burdens imposed on the development of new products:<p>

The time required to bring a new drug to market, including pre-clinical testing,
clinical development and regulatory review increased from a low of 6.3 years in
1963-1965 to a high of 16.1 years in 1988-90--an increase of 156 percent.20  The
average time, from synthesis to marketing, for a U.S.-approved new chemical
entity had risen to 15 years by the early 1990s.21<p>

There is evidence of similar burdens from the review process for medical
devices:22<p>

The number of PMA medical device approvals declined steeply in the late 1980s and
early 1990s, falling from 46 in 1988 to a low of 12 in 1992, before rising to 26
in 1994.  At the same time, the average approval time increased from 337 days in
1988 to 823 days in 1994.
During the same period, average review times for premarket notifications
[510(k)s] increased from 78 days in 1988 to 216 days in 1994.<p>

International comparisons provide additional evidence:23<p>

The percentage of drugs that are first available in the United States is low. 
Only 27 percent of drugs approved during 1987-92 were first introduced here; 54
percent were available in a foreign market one or more years before becoming
available here, and 12 percent were available more than 10 years before U.S.
approval.24<p>

While 58 percent of biopharmaceutical products approved in the United States,
Europe or Japan through the middle of 1992 originated in the United States, and
47 percent were first subjected to clinical testing here, only 18 percent were
first marketed here.25<p>

Average development times for pharmaceuticals, including clinical testing and
review times, are 77 percent higher in the United States than in other countries
(9.2 vs. 5.2 years).26<p>

In 1992, the average PMA approval time of 663 working days was more than twice
the time needed in Europe and Japan.27<p>

Medical device manufacturers are increasingly locating research and manufacturing
facilities offshore.  For example, the CEO of a major medical device
manufacturer--responsible for developing pacemaker technology--recently reported
that virtually all of his firm's major products are now being developed, tested
and produced overseas, and, most importantly, are available to patients elsewhere
much earlier than here.28  He indicated that American patients are sometimes
receiving therapies that are two-to-three generations behind those available in
Europe, Canada and Japan.<p>

"[T]he regulation of new drugs by the FDA...has undoubtedly been the most
thoroughly investigated and studied program of government regulation in history."
The largest corporations can, to some extent, absorb and adapt to excessive
regulatory requirements.  But such requirements are most harmful to the hundreds
of small, entrepreneurial companies that make up America's early-stage
biopharmaceutical and medical device industries.  The discovery process in drugs
and devices has flourished most in small, entrepreneurial firms.  Biotechnology
and certain types of medical devices are all particularly suited to the discovery
genius of gifted individuals, and the venture capital community has been quick to
identify such talented idea people and get their companies started.  In the field
of biotechnology alone, more than 1,300 small U.S. companies have been founded to
create products.  Likewise, in the medical device industry, 88 percent of
companies have fewer than 100 employees, while the average expenditure on
research and development as a percent of sales is more than twice that of the
average of all manufacturing companies.29<p>

These companies must cope with a product development process and extremely
detailed set of requirements that have evolved over 33 years of interaction
between the FDA and the large drug companies.  Small companies cannot survive in
an environment where the clinical research and regulatory affairs departments of
large pharmaceutical companies may each have more people than the average biotech
or device company.  The costs and regulatory barriers to entry that are
manageable to a large drug company are untenable to a small one.<p>

These effects cannot be remedied by tinkering with the current system, because
they reflect a systemic problem.  The skewed institutional incentives faced by
FDA will always cause the agency to err on the side of keeping products off the
market.<p>

<h2>A Review of Reform Proposals</h2>

The existing regulatory structure, given the institutional pressures and
constraints under which it operates, cannot be relied on to reform itself.
There have been literally scores of studies into the process by which new medical
products are brought to market, leading one prominent student of the FDA to
observe that  "[t]he regulation of new drugs by the FDA...has undoubtedly been
the most thoroughly investigated and studied program of government regulation in
history."30 <p>

Of the numerous inquiries over the past half century, the more recent ones--the
1982 MacMahon Report (of the Scheuer-Gore Commission on the Drug Approval
Process), and the reports of the Lasagna Committee (1990), the Edwards Committee
(1991) and the Council on Competitiveness (1991)--stand out because of the
qualifications of their panel members, and the depth in which they studied the
problems in the system.  The themes that run through these reports include the
following:<p>

There should be a devolution of the FDA's monopoly over drug and device
evaluation and testing to private sector entities.  This should include
deregulation of early clinical research and an expanded role for IRBs and other
independent oversight bodies of the IND process; expanded use of advisory
committees and other outside experts in the NDA oversight and evaluation process;
and, external review and evaluation of the data in NDAs.<p>

The FDA should be limited by the statutory definition of "substantial evidence,"
and not go beyond it.  The agency should expand approval of drugs on the basis of
"surrogate" endpoints.  There should in general be a more flexible, clinically
relevant interpretation of the approval standard, including expedited approval
for important new drugs, in some cases combined with increased post-marking
surveillance oversight and review process.<p>

The FDA should institute process and management reforms that improve its handling
of the oversight.<p>

The uniformity of the main reform themes sounded by outside review bodies
indicates a widespread consensus on the part of industry, patient groups and
other students of the FDA that substantial problems exist in current system.  The
FDA has substantial flexibility within its current statute to develop and adopt
major reforms.  The fact that this has not occurred--even when the agency itself
has proposed reforms (as in the case of the 1991 Council on Competitiveness
proposals)--suggests that it is not possible for the current system to reform
itself.  Indeed, as discussed elsewhere in this report, the tendency has been for
the efficiency of the FDA's review functions to deteriorate, rather than to
improve.<p>

This paper's recommendations are aimed at the core set of problems that the
distinguished panels have identified, and thus are in the mainstream of
regulatory reform proposals of the last quarter century.  We differ, however, in
recognizing what experience has shown to be the case--that the existing
regulatory structure, given the institutional pressures and constraints under
which it operates, cannot be relied on to reform itself.  True reform requires a
new institutional arrangement for bringing medical products to market.<p>

<h2>A New Approach for Bringing Drugs and Medical Devices to Market</h2>

Any proposal for change should recognize that patients have come to rely on the
third-party stamp of approval that the FDA now confers, signifying that benefits
and risks have been appropriately evaluated and balanced.  Patients will demand
to be equally comfortable with any alternative arrangements.
Any proposal for change should recognize that patients have come to rely on the
third-party stamp of approval that the FDA now confers, signifying that benefits
and risks have been appropriately evaluated and balanced.<p>

Because of the important differences between the pharmaceutical and the device
industries and the ways they have been affected by government regulation and
failures in government systems, we are proposing for them somewhat different
approaches to reform.  The functioning of the pharmaceutical industry has been
impaired by the way the FDA has interpreted and enforced the legal standards,
rather than the standards themselves.  This has resulted in needless
expenditures, delays and roadblocks in the availability of new therapeutic agents
in this country.<p>

The situation with respect to medical devices is somewhat different, as the
standards themselves are flawed.  The 1976 statute (and its later amendments) did
not create a set of logical, consistent requirements.  For example, the 1976 law
created a class of devices (Class II), whose regulation was predicated on
performance standards which did not exist and have never been developed.  Despite
these problems, the system worked well initially, providing relatively smooth
access to the market for low- and medium-risk devices, and only subjecting a
small portion of devices to a premarket approval process.  In recent years,
however, the FDA has created additional requirements for devices, without
providing adequate objective guidelines.  The result often has been regulatory
gridlock and an unpredictability that greatly discourages capital investment and
product innovation.<p>

The proposals we outline below reflect the differences between drugs and devices.
 For drugs, we propose retaining the existing standards, but adopting a new
system for their implementation.  The device approval system needs both a new set
of standards as well as a new method of implementation.  During the last several
years, the European Union has developed a rational regulatory framework.  We
propose that we adopt the best features of this system.<p>

A new framework for bringing new drugs and medical devices to market should
achieve several objectives.  It should:<p>

maintain or improve existing safety and efficacy standards, and thereby maintain
the present level of public trust in the products on the market;
continue to provide for independent review of new products, indicating that the
necessary data have been gathered and evaluated, and that benefits and risks have
been appropriately balanced;
retain the FDA stamp of approval, providing a check that proper procedures have
been followed and standards met;
facilitate the application of cutting-edge scientific knowledge and talent to the
review process; and,
foster competition and management efficiency in the research, development and
oversight process for reform to be meaningful and lasting.<p>

The result should be a far more efficient system that encourages innovation while
maintaining the public's trust.<p>

We believe our proposals achieve these objectives.  Our proposals use the
expertise available in the nation's centers of medical excellence in the
development and approval process by authorizing qualified bodies to perform the
oversight and review functions currently performed by the FDA.  These qualified
bodies would be subject to government standards and oversight, but would compete
to satisfy the mandatory requirements more efficiently and at lower cost.  The
result should be a far more efficient system that encourages innovation while
maintaining the public's trust.<p>

Under our proposal, the FDA would license private entities called Drug (or
Device) Certifying Bodies (DCBs) to assure that these institutions possess access
to the necessary technical expertise (in-house or otherwise), have the necessary
management systems and are not subject to conflicts of interest.31  Sponsors of
products would retain DCBs instead of the FDA to oversee their product's
development according to the applicable statutory standards.  DCBs could draw on
the expertise of, or even be located in, existing centers of medical excellence. 
In the case of cancer therapy, for example, nationally recognized centers, such
as Memorial Sloan Kettering, M.D. Anderson, Roswell Park and Fred Hutchison,
would be prime candidates to participate in the process.<p>

In this way, the drug development process can be opened to a wide range of
skilled individuals and institutions that can perform oversight and review
functions, consistent with maintaining rigorous statutory standards.
National recognition as a medical center would, however, be neither necessary nor
sufficient to qualify as a DCB.  Drug Certifying Bodies would need to supplement
clinical expertise with the services of key experts qualified in the drug
development sciences--including chemistry, biopharmaceutics, biometrics, and
pharmacoepidemiology.  Nor would a DCB need to be in an existing medical
institution.  For example, a company like the Mitre Corporation, which already
has performed the NDA review function (see discussion below) would be a prime
candidate to be a DCB.  The key requirements would be that it meets the licensing
criteria of skills, management and freedom from conflict of interest.  In this
way, the drug development process can be opened to a wide range of skilled
individuals and institutions that can perform oversight and review functions,
consistent with maintaining rigorous statutory standards.<p>

For devices, which must conform to a very large set of design and production
standards, DCBs would more likely be found among recognized testing bodies rather
than among academic medical centers.  Such bodies are currently used for
specialized testing (e.g., electromagnetic radiation), conformance with quality
assurance standards (e.g., ISO 9000) and for qualification for European Union
marketing.<p>

In the case of pharmaceutical development, private entities already have
performed (and perform today) all functions involved in this process, except the
final approval step.  This includes clinical development programs, NDA
preparation and, in the case of seven supplemental "effectiveness" NDAs delegated
for review in 1992 as a pilot project to the Mitre Corporation, the penultimate
review step.  Any of the institutions that currently offers clinical research
services can obtain access to the management and scientific skills necessary to
monitor and review INDs and NDAs.  These institutions include academic health
centers, other hospitals, some managed care organizations and contract research
organizations (CROs).<p>

The development of the CRO industry in recent years illustrates the ability of
the market to fill rapidly this type of need when necessary.  CROs perform a
variety of services for sponsors, including taking charge of the entire drug
development process--from laboratory to NDA submission--either by themselves or
by subcontracting out parts (such as toxicology) that they do not normally
perform in house.  In addition, there is a range of small specialized CROs.  All
these firms follow applicable FDA and other regulations.  There are even
contractors whose sole business is to audit studies and programs, usually for
sponsors, but sometimes for the FDA.<p>

Clearly, an individual CRO could not both develop products and be a DCB, because
of conflict of interest problems.  The same sets of skills are applicable,
however, and the development of CROs illustrates that this expertise is available
in the private sector, along with the key management abilities required for the
performance of these complex tasks.  Arguably, the design, execution and written
presentation of a good IND/NDA program is a much more difficult effort than the
review of it.<p>

Competition between firms would inevitably produce a lower-cost, faster and
higher-quality development and approval process.
An important element of the system we propose is the separation of the
government's current dual roles of review/approval role and enforcement. 
Enforcement, a function more appropriate to a public sector agency, would be
retained in the government.  Reviewing the scientific studies associated with a
new medical product would be moved to the private sector, which, as discussed
above, can assemble the expertise necessary for the task.  The process would,
thereby, be opened to competition.  This framework would encourage the
application of subject-specific, cutting-edge scientific expertise tailored to
individual drug approval projects.<p>

The proposed system would retain government standards and oversight.  Drug
Certifying Bodies would be guided by the same general safety and efficacy
standards for new products as currently exist, and Device Certifying Bodies would
be guided by a new set of rigorous standards (explained in more detail below). 
The DCBs would, however, have flexibility in attaining those standards, and
competition between firms would inevitably produce a lower-cost, faster and
higher-quality development and approval process.  Manufacturers would be required
to hire a licensed certification firm to bring a new product to market.  A final
government review and approval step would also be retained.  There would,
however, be a strong presumption that private certification decisions would not
be overturned without substantial cause, because the private certifiers have been
licensed and operate under government oversight.<p>

Note that this mechanism differs significantly from a system in which the FDA
maintains its current role, but tries to inject competition by contracting out
more of its review functions.  Relative to the current system of in-house
reviews, competitive bidding for FDA review contracts might yield some
efficiencies.  But the FDA's certification monopoly would remain essentially
unchanged.  The FDA would still have the incentive to add costs and time to the
review process, either through requirements imposed on its contractors or through
the procedures followed after receiving the contractors' reports.<p>

<h2>How the Process Would Work For Drugs</h2>

As discussed above, the FDA regulates new drugs at two key points in the
development process, which provide the agency with substantial influence
throughout the process.  First, sponsors are required to obtain approval to begin
clinical trials by submitting an IND application to the FDA, and the agency then
continues to oversee the sponsor's clinical program through regular reports and
other mechanisms.  After the clinical studies are completed, sponsors submit a
NDA to the FDA for its approval.<p>

Under our proposal, sponsors of individual drugs would hire and deal with a DCB,
not the FDA, throughout the development process.  The DCB would have full
responsibility for overseeing and advising on all aspects of the development and
review of individual drugs--from the pre-IND stage through NDA approval.  The
process is outlined and compared to the current process in Figure 1.<p>

A government agency should not simultaneously have regulatory authority over, and
be in competition with, private entities.<p>

The DCBs would apply existing regulatory standards.  The current standards for
clinical research, protecting human subjects and data integrity, and safety and
effectiveness of new drugs are set out in the IND and NDA regulations.  These
documents are clear and can be applied by appropriately constituted outside
review groups.  DCBs could adopt many of the reform recommendations that the FDA
has failed to implement, without changing its existing standards.  Barriers to
early clinical research could be lowered; NDAs could more often be approved on
the basis of reasonable surrogate endpoints; and, post-approval studies could
more often substitute for or supplement pre-approval studies.  All of these are
consistent with the major recommendations made by the distinguished review panels
over the years, and none require any dilution of the existing safety and
effectiveness standards.<p>

When a drug receives preliminary approval by a DCB, the DCB would document the
basis for the approval in a "summary basis of approval" report, which would be
submitted to the Commissioner of the FDA.  This report would document the basis
for the DCB's conclusion that the NDA meets the statutory standards for approval.<p>

Because the DCBs would be licensed by the FDA and subject to its oversight, there
would be a strong presumption that their approval would not be overturned.  The
proposed procedures allow for an FDA veto, however, if the FDA finds the new drug
unsafe or ineffective.  The FDA would review the DCB's own analysis of the data,
and would not be authorized to request new data or testing.32  The FDA would have
to exercise its veto within a fixed time period (e.g., 90 days) after which the
drug would automatically receive FDA approval.<p>

In the event of a FDA veto of a DCB's approval, the sponsor would have the right
to appeal to a specially constituted board of experts operating under government
auspices.  The proceedings of this appeal would be public.<p>

Note that, once this regime is fully established, the FDA could not itself
perform the functions of a DCB.  This is because the FDA would perform licensing
and oversight functions for DCBs, and because the FDA would retain a final
sign-off role in the approval process.  A government agency should not
simultaneously have regulatory authority over, and be in competition with,
private entities.<p>

During the transition, however, the FDA could continue to review products, and it
is important that the transition be structured so as not disrupt the process for
products already in the FDA pipeline.  After a date certain, the FDA's review
function would be expected to cease.<p>

Both the FDA and the DCBs would have a role in postmarket surveillance.  Both
would receive adverse incident reports and both would have authority to recommend
that a product be removed from the market.<p>

<h2>How the Process Would Work For Devices</h2>

The current U.S. system of device regulation is not based on a consistent set of
standards.  Rather, almost all devices go through the 510(k) process, under which
a device can be marketed if it can be shown to be substantially equivalent to a
predicate device already on the market.  The criteria for establishing
substantial equivalence are not, however, well defined by statute.  Moreover,
clear criteria never have been developed for assigning devices to the various
classes, or for the standards that should be applied to each class. <p>

The proposed procedures allow for an FDA veto, however, if the FDA finds the new
drug unsafe or ineffective.
The European system of device regulation, based on the European Council Directive
93/42/EEC of June 14, 1993 addresses these problems.  The Directive contains a
set of general principles to which manufacturers must adhere, including a set of
essential requirements for all devices.  The need for additional requirements
depends on the class the device is in.  Classes are numbered I (least control),
IIa, IIb and III (greatest control).33  In general, low-risk, non-invasive
devices are in Class I, high-risk implanted devices in contact with the central
circulatory or nervous systems are in Class III, with intermediate devices in
Classes IIa and IIb.  In all cases, manufacturers may choose from alternative
methods to demonstrate compliance with the standards.  In general, recognizing
the diversity of medical devices and device companies, the Directive allows the
choice of conforming to various combinations of design examination, production
testing and design and production quality assurance standards, as are appropriate
to assure the safety of the type of device in question.  The emphasis is on
assuring that the device performs in accord with its design requirements.  For
Class I devices, the manufacturer may simply self-declare compliance with the
essential requirements.  For all other devices, the manufacturer must retain an
independent government-certified notified body to certify compliance.  Actual
premarket approval of the specific design of the product (with original or
referenced clinical data) is required only for Class III products.
The substantial tort liability exposure of the pharmaceutical industry is
particularly striking because it is coupled with very strict regulation of the
products themselves for safety and effectiveness.<p>

We propose adopting the best of this system.  Device Certification Bodies (DCBs)
would be licensed by the FDA.  Manufacturers of Class I devices would be able to
self-certify that they have complied with a rigorous set of basic internationally
accepted procedures and objective standards.  Manufacturers of Class IIa, IIb,
and III devices would require a licensed DCB to certify their compliance with a
progressively more stringent set of standards and procedures.  For Class III
devices this would include a mandatory detailed assessment of the product design
itself.  The FDA would review the DCB's design certifications to ensure that
appropriate standards were referenced.  The process is outlined and compared with
the current procedures in Figures 2 and 3.  For all cases there would be a
FDA-administered postmarketing surveillance program to guard against unforeseen
product failures.   <p>

<h2>Product Liability Issues</h2>

Lawsuits against the pharmaceutical industry have long been among the most
prominent liability cases.34  This is not a reflection of corporate
irresponsibility, but rather of the fact that pharmaceutical products are
intrinsically involved in individual health and in the treatment of patients,
many of whom will experience adverse outcomes and even death during the natural
course of their treatment.  The product's use, coupled with the stringent nature
of liability standards, has led to a substantial liability burden that is
unproductive.  For example, the National Academy of Sciences concluded that high
product liability costs were largely responsible for shutting down American
research on oral or parenteral (non-barrier) contraceptives.35<p>

The substantial tort liability exposure of the pharmaceutical industry is
particularly striking because it is coupled with very strict regulation of the
products themselves for safety and effectiveness.  The premarket approval process
for pharmaceuticals is much more extensive than regulation of other consumer
products, such as automobiles, that also generate considerable risks.<p>


By imposing costs on the tortfeasor, the liability system generates incentives
for efficient risk avoidance as well as compensation for accident victims.  There
is a general consensus, however, that the tort system is an inefficient way of
providing compensation.  Litigation costs for both plaintiffs and defendants are
often quite substantial--far higher than usual insurance administrative costs. 
In addition, tort liability forces consumers to, in effect, purchase insurance
through higher prices for coverage that they would not purchase voluntarily. 
Pain and suffering damages and punitive damages are chief among the items for
which individuals would not voluntarily purchase insurance.
Tort liability costs have led manufacturers of certain products simply to
terminate production and leave the marketplace, even where the product occupies
an important niche.<p>

Tort liability can, however, be an efficient way of inducing firms to produce
safe products, but its role in that regard should depend on the other societal
institutions in place.  If the risk level and adequacy of warnings are addressed
through a regulatory structure that ensures that the level of precautions is
efficient, there is no deterrence rationale for having tort liability.  To the
extent that the FDA regulations achieve the social objective of efficient control
of risk, it is duplicative to also perform this function through additional tort
liability.  An obvious exception is when critical information is withheld from
the regulatory agency so that the regulation cannot be set in an ideal manner.<p>

Government regulations can of course be set either too leniently or too
stringently.  The fact that a regulatory program exists does not necessarily
imply that there is no role for any supplementary social institution, such as
tort liability.  In the case of the FDA, however, the general consensus in the
literature on this issue is that the regulations are at least adequate and, to
the extent that there is any divergence from optimality, perhaps excessively
stringent with respect to the promotion of product safety.  Because of this, one
would not want to further deter companies from introducing beneficial new
products through additional tort liability sanctions.<p>

The effects on pharmaceuticals of not having a regulatory compliance defense have
been quite striking.  Tort liability costs have led manufacturers of certain
products simply to terminate production and leave the marketplace, even where the
product occupies an important niche.  An example is the product Bendectin, an
anti-nausea drug for pregnant women.  After dozens of successful defenses against
claims of drug-induced birth defects, the manufacturer simply ceased production. 
Similarly, vaccine manufacturers have exited the market, increasing concentration
in that market, and raising prices well in excess of the inflation rate.  Since
1968, the number of vaccine manufacturers in the United States has dropped by
over 50 percent.36  The U.S. markets for vaccines for polio, rubella, measles,
mumps and rabies are each now controlled by a single producer.  Similar
monopolies exist for many pediatric vaccines as well.37<p>

In contrast to the treatment of pharmaceuticals, the Medical Devices Amendments
of 1976 preempt claims against medical devices.  Indeed, in the recent 1995 case
of Michael v. Shiley, Inc., the court ruled that the 1976 amendments preempt
actions involving negligence, strict liability and breach of implied warranty for
medical devices.38  What is striking about this legal shield, in contrast with
the treatment of pharmaceuticals, is that only a small fraction of devices (i.e.,
those in Class III) are subject to formal premarket approval.<p>

Deterring innovation and promoting market exit is not desirable if these actions
are the result of sanctions that are not linked to a provision of an efficient
degree of safety but in fact are imposed on the firm even if appropriate safety
standards have been met.<p>

One possible counter argument to the regulatory compliance defense is that after
a drug is approved, it may turn out to have adverse effects that were not
anticipated.  However, the task regarding the review of the product for safety
and effectiveness is to make the best judgment possible at the time the product
is marketed.  If new information becomes available to indicate that the product
presents risks greater than initially believed, then the company should be held
responsible for acting upon this new information in a responsible manner.<p>

This way of dealing with new information is the approach taken in Europe with
respect to medical devices in which companies have a "development-risk" defense. 
A company is free of liability in the tort liability regime in all European Union
countries other than Luxembourg if it can show that the "state of scientific and
technical knowledge at the time when [it] put the product into circulation was
not such as to enable the existence of the defect to be discovered."  This state
of information defense, coupled with a requirement that companies meet the
applicable regulatory standards, ensures that an efficient degree of product
safety be provided both at the time of the product's introduction as well as
throughout the product's life.  Once this has been assured, there is no
additional rationale for augmenting these safety incentives, at least from the
standpoint of risk prevention.<p>

Although regulatory compliance should be a defense against all tort liability,
there is an even stronger argument that punitive damages (above and beyond
compensatory damages) are not warranted if a firm has fulfilled all its
regulatory obligations and has not withheld information from the regulatory
agency.  Once the efficient level of safety has been provided, punitive damages
are not innocuous.  Imposing punitive damages will deter companies from
developing products that are especially vulnerable to large punitive damage
awards, such as oral or parenteral contraceptives, or products intended for
pregnant women.  Similarly, companies will have an incentive to exit the market
altogether in an effort to avoid punitive damages, as has been the case with
vaccines and Bendectin.  Deterring innovation and promoting market exit is not
desirable if these actions are the result of sanctions that are not linked to a
provision of an efficient degree of safety but in fact are imposed on the firm
even if appropriate safety standards have been met.<p>

The framework we propose would make the "off-label" issue much less of an issue,
because it would strengthen the incentives for manufacturers to submit their
products for supplementary approvals.<p>

Except for medical devices, there is currently only minimal recognition of a
regulatory compliance defense.39  With respect to pharmaceuticals, there are only
five states thus 
far--Arizona, New Jersey, Ohio, Oregon, and Utah--that have provided for a FDA
regulatory compliance defense against punitive damages.  There has been no
federal punitive damage defense, although provision for one is frequently
included in draft bills.<p>

There is no rationale for continuing the distinction between pharmaceutical
products and medical devices in this area.  We propose going beyond the
regulatory compliance defense with respect to punitive damages for FDA-approved
products.  As long as current regulatory standards are maintained, there also
should be a regulatory compliance defense with respect to liability more
generally.  This would make the regulatory compliance defense the same for
pharmaceuticals as it is for medical devices.  The premarket approval system is
much more stringent for pharmaceutical products--and will remain much more
stringent--than for most medical devices.  The criteria involved ensure the
safety and effectiveness of the product based on the best available state of the
information at the time.<p>

The principal requirements for advocating a regulatory compliance defense for any
revised FDA drug or medical device approval process are that the new process
maintain the current safety standards and continue to establish a uniform
warnings vocabulary.  Provided that these two conditions are met, this policy
should be applicable to different institutional structures.<p>

Within the context of this proposal, the DCBs could potentially be exposed to
liability.  If this liability were considerable, it would discourage entry into
the market by responsible entities who were reluctant to assume a large liability
burden or expose their existing assets to such lawsuits.  Although such companies
could have a government contractor defense, this defense in all likelihood would
be limited.  We propose the establishment of a shield against strict liability
lawsuits for DCBs, but that they be liable to lawsuits for negligence.<p>

<h2>The Off-Label Issue 40</h2>

Restrictions on the dissemination of information on off-label uses currently
affect not only the direct distribution of promotional materials, but also drug-
and device-company sponsorship of educational conferences for physicians and
patient groups, to whom it has become a very serious concern.<p>

There are three principal ways to address this issue:  (1) retain the current
restrictions; (2) relax the current restrictions, but establish new rules to
decide what manufacturers can say about their products; and, (3) eliminate all
restrictions.  The first alternative seems clearly unsatisfactory, because it
both repudiates the peer-reviewed medical literature as a means of disseminating
information to the medical community and deprives physicians and their patients
of valuable information.  The second alternative would require the establishment
of new rules to determine which studies and which journals have sufficient
scientific merit to allow information from them to be disseminated.  These rules
would be difficult to develop.<p>

The framework we propose would make the "off-label" issue much less of an issue,
because it would strengthen the incentives for manufacturers to submit their
products for supplementary approvals.  Under the current regulatory system, the
effective cost of submitting products for supplementary approvals is relatively
high.  The FDA has little incentive to give a high priority to supplemental NDAs,
and sponsors have a limited incentive to submit them.  Under the proposed system,
we expect that the costs of submitting products for supplementary approvals would
be significantly lower.  DCBs would have the incentive and the resources to
process supplementals efficiently and in a timely manner.  Some DCBs might even
specialize in supplementary approvals.<p>

Because only products used in approved uses would be eligible for the regulatory
compliance tort liability defense, sponsors would have a strong incentive to
submit products for supplemental approvals.  They would not have a regulatory
compliance defense shield for off-label uses.<p>

<h2>Reaping the Benefits of Biomedical Knowledge</h2>

As a nation, we spend tens of billions of dollars on medical research each year,
the major share of it conducted in the private sector.  The body of knowledge
relevant for medical innovation is increasing at a rapid rate, providing growing
opportunities for therapeutic advances.  In particular, the
"informational-cybernetic paradigm" of modern molecular biology offers the
promise of greater medical gains aimed at the causes of many diseases, not just
their symptoms.41<p>

Our citizens must be confident that they are reaping the benefits of the vast
research establishment our nation has erected--a flow of medical products that
are safe and the best available.  They and their doctors must also be sure they
can obtain the information necessary to make choices about their medical care.<p>

Designing a new system to bring pharmaceuticals and medical devices to the
patient more efficiently is a complex problem, involving interrelated scientific,
economic, institutional and legal issues.  The sectors that create new medical
knowledge are diverse, as are the products they create.  We believe the model
suggested has the flexibility to accommodate this diversity and nourish the
creative process, so that patients will have the innovative new medical products
they need.<p>


