<li>The off-label product usage issue is quite complex.  Physicians are not
required to disclose to patients that drug therapies are off-label.  The usage of
drugs for off-label purposes has been the subject of litigation with respect to
insurance reimbursement.  The courts have ruled, for example, that Medicaid
coverage could not exclude AZT therapy for certain classes of AIDS patients even
though such therapy was an off-label usage.  Similarly, high dose
chemotherapy-autologous bone marrow transplants are off-label usages, but
nevertheless some courts have ruled that Blue Cross-Blue Shield must reimburse
such therapies.  Indeed, the New York law expressly forbids insurers from
excluding off-label uses of cancer drugs under certain conditions.  For
discussion of these issues, see Christopher (1993), and Walsh and Pyrich (1994).
Federal Medicaid legislation goes further.  See Raiford et.al. (1994).
