<html><head><title>  Experimental Economics in Electric Power Deregulation -- PFF</title></head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>


<h2>A Progress Report on
The Future of Energy Transmission</h2>
<i>October 17, 1995</i>
<P>

<h3>Experimental Economics in Electric Power Deregulation</h3> 
</center><P>


In an effort to understand how to create competitive markets in electric energy, The Progress & Freedom Foundation recently arranged for a workshop in computerized economic experiments at the Economic Science Laboratory (ESL) at the University of Arizona.
<P>
Participants, seated at their own computers, were given self-paced instructions for a simple double auction experiment. They were divided into two groups, buyers and sellers, who could trade a fictitious commodity. The sellers were given information about their costs of production and buyers were given information about  their opportunity for reselling the fictitious commodity. Each individual had an opportunity to make a profit by receiving revenue greater than his/her costs (or purchase price) or incur losses by receiving revenue less than his/her costs (or purchase price). Each participant was free to trade several units each period and the experiment lasted ten (10) trading periods. Buyers sent their bids and sellers sent their offers via a computer network, and any participant could accept outstanding bids or offers.
<P>
After this experiment, the workshop director, professor Vernon Smith, explained the principles of experimental economics and the use of experimental methods as an analytical tool for assessing the success of various price mechanisms and institutions in achieving economic efficiency.
<P>
Following the discussion of the double auction experiment, the participants returned to the laboratory where they were involved in a second, more sophisticated experiment (this time with actual monetary payoffs) that simulated real-time trading in an electric power network. 
<P>
The participants in this experiment were divided into two groups.  One group was involved in an experiment with inactive or passive transmission ownership. The second group was involved in an experiment with active transmission owners. In the first group, the participants were divided into those who generated power and those who consumed power. The participants who generated power each were given information about their costs and transmission losses. Those who consumed power were given information about their resale possibilities. Participants were paid their profits, i.e. difference between their costs and revenues. In the second group, there were generators, consumers and some participants who actually owned transmission assets. 
<P>
Through twenty trading periods, buyers and sellers submitted both quantities of power they wanted to buy/sell and the prices they were willing to pay/accept for it. In the second group transmission owners also submitted offers. The computer algorithm or central dispatch calculated the optimal (i.e., value maximizing) prices and allocations and communicated them back to the subjects who could continuously make adjustments in their bids and offers.
<P>
What participants learned from the experiments both present and past, as well as from the discussion that followed, was the impact different market structures and institutions (i.e., the presence of power marketers, transmission line constraints, possibility of demand side bidding) have on both market efficiency and on the distribution of profits among groups of agents.
<P>
There was a discussion on the long-term versus spot markets for power and the difference between financial and physical contracts for power delivery. ESL is developing a market model where all physical flows are organized around the spot market. This is a concept based on property rights (i.e., rights to inject, transmit and withdraw power within the transmission network).
<P>
Another property rights question addressed was the difference between trading power through the pool or via bilateral contracts among generators, transmitters and consumers. The topic centered on the enforcement of property rights in a proposed pool mechanism.
<P>
Next came a discussion of the so-called "stranded investment" problem. Vernon Smith presented his proposal on this issue: A fixed (but declining) annual fee charged during a transition period to all utility customers. The fee would be calculated each year so as to reflect the utility's current depreciated value of "stranded" assets. This solution might resolve the utilities' stranded investment problem without distorting price signals and without creating any barriers to customers wishing to switch to more efficient producers.
<P>
There was nearly unanimous agreement among the participants that additional experimental work on a number of policy issues including pool versus bilateral trades and active versus passive transmission pricing would provide useful input into the public debate over electric energy policy.
<P>
The ESL experiments were the kick-off event for PFF's project on "Creating Competitive Markets in Electric Energy."  They were part of a two-day technical workshop held September 19 and 20, 1995, in Tucson. The participant group consisted of industry representatives and PFF staff. The objectives of the seminar were: 
<ol>
<LI>to introduce the industry representatives to the power of experimental economics, and in particular the ESL variant of this technique, to inform the debate concerning deregulation of electric power.
<LI>to provide industry representatives with PFF's overall conception of regulatory reform and of the transition to a more competitive electric industry; and,
<LI>to provide a forum in which industry representatives and the PFF study team (including Vernon Smith and his group) could discuss technical details concerning the institutional framework necessary to create competitive electric energy markets and the policy issues surrounding them.
</ol><P>
In addition to the ESL experiment, the workshop heard from Charles Bayless, CEO of Tucson Electric Power Co. and Lewis Harris from Edison Electric Institute. Bayless talked about a fast track to a competitive industry and Harris discussed the recent Notice of Proposed Rulemaking issued by FERC concerning transmission pricing and stranded costs and proposals on recovery of stranded investment. 
<P>
<i>This progress report was prepared by The Progress & Freedom's "Creating Competitive Markets in Electric Energy" project, led by senior fellows Michael Block and Thomas Lenard.<P>
 This is a progress report on The Future of Energy Transmission Project, which is designing a replacement for the current Federal regulatory regime that places artificial constraints on the structure, scope and activities of electric power producers.  Introducing true competition to the electric energy industry in the United States will greatly enhance American productivity and competitiveness by lowering the costs of a vital resource for America's business and families.  Richard F. O'Donnell-- Editor</I>


</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY></html>
