<DOCHDR>
http://www.cpac.org:80/pff/se-more.html 204.71.237.74 19970121224258 text/html 6377
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Tuesday, 21-Jan-97 22:43:20 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 11-Jul-96 19:36:54 GMT
Content-length: 6191
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Spaceship Earth: More Information -- PFF</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000">
<blockquote>
<a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<br>
<h2>Spaceship Earth</h2>
<b>More Information</b><p>

Since its birth on Earth Day, 1970, the modern environmental movement can
claim many successes:  Air and water are cleaner; automobiles operate more
efficiently and pollute less; "smokestack" industries are more
environment-friendly than ever before.  

<P>
Perhaps more impressive than these tangible achievements is the impact the
environmental movement has had on American culture.  The vast majority of
Americans now think of themselves as "environmentalists," and most people
engage on a regular basis in some activity (e.g. recycling newspapers) that
allows them to act personally on their environmental beliefs.  The
environmental movement fundamentally changed American values on a scale
comparable to such great historical movements as Methodism and the American
suffrage movement.


<P>
<a name="enter"></a>
The original environmentalists turned to government, especially the national
government, to achieve their objectives.  The government, in turn, applied
its bureaucratic regulatory model to environmental challenges.  To protect
and enhance the environment, government issued thousands of pages of
regulations; dedicated billions of tax dollars; and required others, state
and local government as well as private citizens, to redirect billions of
dollars more to environmental protection.

<P>
While this bureaucratic, regulatory model of government coincided with many
environmental successes, it has also failed (sometimes spectacularly) to
achieve its goals (e.g. Superfund).  Even in the areas where real progress
has been made, it has often been purchased only at the price of imposing
unnecessary burdens on economic growth.  

<P>

Perhaps most damaging, the regulatory approach has hampered technological
innovation, slowing the development and introduction of new approaches that
are essential to the next generation of environmental progress.  The
regulatory approach has "frozen" the environmental agenda in the increasingly
obsolete technologies of the 1970s.  Today, the environmental movement is
mired in a static model which is fundamentally flawed for practical,
scientific and cultural reasons.  

<P>
In practical terms, the static model, imposed through innovation-hostile
regulatory bureaucracies, has dramatically slowed the introduction of
environmentally-friendly technologies that are essential to the next
generation of environmental progress.  

<P>
In scientific terms, the model is flawed because it assumes that "spaceship
earth" is a static system -- that the environment is or ought to be
unchanging -- when it is in fact highly dynamic.  The earth has changed and
evolved dramatically, even during the relatively short course of human
history.  Oceans rise and fall, species come and go, temperatures fluctuate.
El Nino -- the massive air disturbance that has fundamentally changed the
global climate during this century -- is a dramatic current example of
environmental dynamism on spaceship earth.

<P>
In cultural terms, the static model is flawed because the idea of progress --
the belief that mankind has improved in the past, is improving today, and
will continue to improve into the foreseeable future -- is inextricably woven
into the American idea itself.  For Americans, it has never been enough to
"maintain" or "sustain;" our goal has always been to improve and make better.
A culturally sustainable environmentalism is therefore not one that equates
"stewardship" with "stasis."  Instead, it must recognize the dynamic nature
of the global environment, and it must seek to channel that dynamism in a
positive direction.  American environmentalism, in short, must be about
progress.

<P>
The static approach to environmentalism is, of course, not simply a result of
a regulatory approach.  The idea of "stasis" is deeply embedded in the
political philosophy of the environmental movement.  The idea is to "protect
and preserve," to prevent "significant deterioration," to advance
"sustainable" approaches to development.

<P>
It is not enough to "protect the environment from further damage."  Within
the framework of continuous environmental change, we must seek to enhance our
air, water and other natural resources.

<P>
Having recognized environmental dynamism, we cannot help but also recognize
that the regulatory approach adopted more than a generation ago must be
replaced by an approach that releases the dynamic energies of personal and
economic freedom.  Unlike the current approach, new environmental policies
must enhance market mechanisms, property rights, local initiative and,
perhaps most important, the development and use of environmentally friendly
technologies.  Not least among these is the advancement of  progress toward
an information-age economy, which is, by its nature, dramatically less
environmentally damaging than the "smokestack" economy of the industrial age.

<P>
It is time to develop the next generation of environmental thought and
policy.   What is needed is not so much a better way of regulation but a
better way of cleaning up toxic waste dumps.  It is not enough in the eyes of
the public to abolish the old system without offering a replacement vision.

<P>
Replacing more than 20 years of environmental doctrine, dogma, ideology,
politics and policy is, of course, a massive undertaking -- and may well be
expected to take a decade or more to complete.  But the work must begin
somewhere, and while completion is many years away, we must develop a new
framework that recognizes the scientific fact of environmental dynamism,
encourages the practical dynamism of environmentally friendly technological
innovation and embraces the cultural principle of positive environmental
dynamism  -- i.e. of environmental progress.<p>

<br>
<br>
<center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center><br>
</blockquote>
</BODY>
