</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>Washington Report</title>
</head>
<p><br><br>

<center>
<table border>
<tr>
<td><IMG ALT="WASHINGTON REPORT LOGO" SRC="wlogo.GIF"></td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>

<img src="red-line.gif">
<h3>July 1995</h3>
</center>
<p>
<h3><a name="quick">QuickLinks</a></h3>
<A HREF="#nbr">
National Black Republican Empowerment Task Force</A><br>

<A HREF="#naa">National African-American Leadership Summit</A><br>
<A HREF="#affirmative">
Affirmative Action Update</A><br>
<A HREF="#dole">Senator Bob Dole's Speach on Hollywood</a><p>
<p>
<hr><a name="nbr"></a>
<a href="#quick">(Back to QuickLinks)</a><p>
Some black Republican leaders want a hand in writing their party's 1996
platform, and one suggested May 19 he's prepared to demonstrate at the
national convention to make his point.<p>
     	
Leaders of the National Black Republican Empowerment Task Force, which met in Washington to write its own version of a platform, also took issue with GOP lawmakers over affirmative action and the budget.<p>
     	
"We need to be sitting at the table when the decisions are made and when
the pie is cut," said task force co-chairman Maurice Dawkins, who also is chairman of the Florida Republican Black Caucus.  "We'll get there, even if we have to demonstrate outside the convention hall" when the Republican National Convention meets in San Diego, he said.<p>
     
Maintaining affirmative action programs and business set-aside for minorities will be priorities in the
blacks' platform, said Dawkins, declining to outline specifics.<p>
     
The task force, not an official party organization, is comprised of some 30 state and local party officials, many of them veterans of the Nixon administration.  This group differs markedly from that of many of today's younger, more conservative Republicans who emphasize self-reliance and
entrepreneurship, and shun affirmative action programs.<p>
     
Haley Barbour, chairman of the Republican National Committee, has promised blacks a voice in platform discussions.  But the task force's hopes on affirmative action are not echoed by the GOP's congressional leaders.<p>
     
Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole, a presidential hopeful, already has asked Senate committees to schedule hearings on affirmative action.  Another GOP candidate, Texas Sen. Phil Gramm, has
pledged, if elected, to issue an executive order ending federal hiring and contract preferences based solely on race or gender.<p>
     
"A lot of people are misled in terms of what affirmative action means," said James L. Denson, a task force member who is a New Orleans businessman.<p>
     
"We all are opposed to quotas, as such, but we're not opposed to the results of an affirmative-type program," he said.<p>
     
On the budget, Denson criticized GOP proposals to eliminate the Small Business Administration.<p>
    
"They think the SBA only helps women and minorities, but if they did their homework...they'd find that small business is the backbone of the economy," he said.<p>
     
Presidential candidate Alan Keyes and Oklahoma Rep. J.C. Watts, both of whom are black, participated in discussions on the black empowerment platform.  Dole and Indiana Sen. Richard Lugar, another presidential hopeful, sent staff members.<p>

The task force hopes to meet personally with each of the would-be presidents before submitting its
recommendations to the RNC platform committee, Dawkins said.<p>

Dawkins, a Washington-area lobbyist, opposed Democrat Charles Robb in Virginia's 1988 Senate race, but lost with 29 percent of the vote.<p>
	   

<hr><a name="naa"></a>
<a href="#quick">(Back to QuickLinks)</a><p>

Benjamin Chavis has fashioned a new civil rights organization from the hodgepodge of grassroots groups that participated in the "unity" summits he convened after being fired from the NAACP.<p>
     
The National African-American Leadership Summit (NAALS) has been created in response to "an eagerness" to formalize the summit meetings, Chavis said.  It plans to draw members from those outside mainstream civil rights groups.<p>
     
"I'm not trying to pull the rug out from under another organization.  I'm just saying the black community is out there in need of mobilization," Chavis said.  "We need to connect these grassroots brothers and sisters who have not been touched by these other organizations."<p>
     
The new group provides Chavis with a high-profile platform for his quasi-nationalist agenda, something he has lacked since the NAACP fired him last August for using NAACP money to
settle a sex discrimination claim without telling the board of directors.<p>
     
One of the new group's first objectives is to mobilize black men for a Million Man March on Washington,
to be held Oct. 16.  It also plans to focus on fighting to preserve affirmative action programs, black economic and political empowerment and federal aid to Africa--all elements of Chavis'
NAACP agenda.<p>
     
NAALS convened at Texas Southern University in Houston on June 9-11 to approve a constitution and
bylaws and establish rules for membership, said Chavis, who is the group's national spokesman.  It was the first summit at which the new group will operate as an official entity.<p>
     
At the Houston meeting, Chavis stressed the need for self-sufficiency, and vowed that the NAALS would not just talk the talk, but would walk the walk.<p>
     
"The summit will be economically dependent upon support from the African-American community, almost exclusively," Chavis said.<p>
     
Chavis originally said he wouldn't create another organization to continue the work he stared at the NAACP.  But he steadily took steps in that direction by convening two informal summits, one in
Baltimore the day after his firing and the other in Chicago last December.  After losing his status in such a high-profile position, it is not surprising that Chavis would try to stay in the public eye.<p>
     
"I am not at the same place I was last year on that question, obviously," Chavis said.  "There has been evolving enthusiasm and support.  I now believe that NAALS needs to be a permanent organization."<p>
     
The new group is emerging at a time of severe weakness at the National Association of the Advancement of Colored People.   The NAACP is $3.8 million in debt and is struggling to hang onto its
corporate donors.  It also is hobbled by a split between its 86-year-old integrationist mission and younger potential members who are drawn to black nationalism.<p>

<hr><a name="affirmative"></a>
<a href="#quick">(Back to QuickLinks)</a><p>

While vowing to battle GOP attempts to gut affirmative action policies, Rep. Kweisi Mfume (D-Md.) also warned June 5 that White House efforts to date on the contentious issue have left black members
of Congress concerned, and suggested that uneasiness could erode much of President Clinton's base heading into the  96 presidential campaign.<p>
     
"The pres-ident runs the risk of per-manently los-ing large seg-ments of his
base," Mfume contended at a press con-ference.  He said he tele-phoned the White House and told senior Clinton adviser George Stephanopoulos that CBC members "believe that we need bold
presidential leadership.  And bold presidential leadership is not a polite tap on the shoulder."<p>
     
Mfume, formerly head of the Congressional Black Caucus, now heads a caucus task force on affirmative action.  He referred to a recent New York Times story that said the White House is drafting
an affirmative action policy that, as Mfume phrased it, would put minority contracting jobs up for review as "some sort of sacrificial first step."  Mfume also said he expressed alarm that the White House has not consulted CBC members, despite the group's persistent requests for dialogue.  However, Mfume said Stephanopoulos told him White House officials will meet with CBC members to brief them on the administration's preliminary policy outline.<p>
     
But Clinton's foot-dragging may be part of a broader strategy to ease the fears of many white male constituents the Democrats lost in the 1994 elections.  A Clinton administration official said there might be some political benefit if black business executives criticized the administration's 
eventual proposals.<p>
     
"We want black businessmen to scream enough to let angry white males understand that we've done something for them," said the official, who made his comments to a New York Times reporter on the condition that he not be named.<p>
     
Mfume said the caucus also is prepared to fight GOP attempts to revise or repeal affirmative action programs, including a proposal by Rep. Charles Canady (R-Fl.), who is circulating a "Dear Colleague" letter to gather support for his "Civil Rights Act of 1995."<p>
     
Canady's bill, which was introduced in mid-June, would repeal all federal laws and programs that give preferences to racial minorities and women.  In a recent report prepared for Senate Majority
Leader Dole, the Congressional Research Service determined there are 160 such affirmative action programs.<p>
     
Canady's bill also would prohibit preferences for federal contracting jobs.<p>
     
In his "Dear Colleague," which he began circulating a few weeks ago, Canady declared:  "Full compensation and redress will still be available to those who prove they are victims of illegal
discrimination.  But there will be no preferring of individuals based on their membership in a group where they themselves have not been actual victims of discrimination."<p>
     
Mfume, who indicated the CBC task force will propose its own alternative legislation, said he and other black members are prepared to negotiate with congressional Republican leaders.<p>
     
Mfume told Republican leaders that CBC members are "prepared to negotiate," but stressed "we will not have policy imposed upon us without any input."<p>
     
He also warned that protests could come in the form of economic boycotts and "demonstrations in the street."<p>

<hr><a name="dole"></a>
<a href="#quick">(Back to QuickLinks)</a><p>


Senator Bob Dole's blistering attack on the entertainment industry is seen by analysts as a carefully planned strategy with four political goals:  Appeal to skeptical GOP conservatives; swipe at Senator Phil Gramm, who has been embarrassed by the revelation that in the 1970s his brother-in-law convinced him to invest $7,500 in an R-rated film; contrast himself with President Clinton, who has long been enamored with Hollywood stars; and identify with an issue that crosses party lines and appeals
to everyday Americans who feel the nation's moral moorings are coming loose.<p>  
     
"A lot of parents don't want their children exposed to this...trash," said GOP strategist Bill Kristol.<p>
     
Clinton strategist James Carville said Dole's strategy smacks of hypocrisy.  "He [Dole] sure is brave with people he doesn't get money from, like Hollywood," said Carville, "but very cowardly with people he does get money from, like the NRA."<p>
     
And Clinton, in his Montana town-meeting June 1 took a veiled swipe at Dole, accusing him of criticizing popular culture but not conservative extremists.  "There are some public officials in our
country who are only too happy to criticize the culture of violence being promoted by the media," said Clinton, "but are stone silent when these other folks are talking and making violence seem 
like it's OK."<p>
     
For the GOP presidential stakes, Dole's speech appeared to complete the process of converting the skepticism of his bid among leaders of the religious right to more enthusiastically consider supporting
him.<p>
     
"In every campaign, there is what Lee Atwater would say was a defining moment," said Christian Coalition executive director Ralph Reed.  "You can make a very strong case that Dole's Hollywood speech is such a defining moment for his candidacy.  He clearly recognizes the importance of the appeal that can be gained by making themes about the culture a centerpiece of his
campaign."<p> 
<p>
